[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello everyone, and welcome to my course. I hope that you will enjoy it!What I try to do here is to cover my career in a couple of courses, beginning in the year 1995. The reason for this is that, prior to becoming an FM, my games were of a low-quality @@StartBracket@@I think that players in the past made more mistakes@@EndBracket@@. I tried to pick games where the mistakes I made can be educational. This first part is about my rise from an FM to a Grandmaster rated 2615, covering my career from 1995 until 2013.In this course, I try to remember the emotions and challenges I had during the games. And, of course, each game has a specific theme accompanying it. Some of these themes are about determination. Others are about understanding the structure or what I'm trying to gain from a position.I also tried to link these games to openings and the ideas I've discovered, learned, and managed to use in the future. In fact, even some of the thoughts I had during the game that never appeared on the board helped me discover some novelties in completely different positions. I hope that you will see the connection.I also have a couple of funny games, so I added a couple of tricks that I managed to pull on my opponents in different stages of the game. In addition, there are puzzles that occurred in my games, and even some puzzles that I really like. There is a lot of material that can either be structured chronologically if you want to follow and hear my story, or by theme if you want to learn about the concepts I brought into those games.Thank you once again, and let's hope this way I took will be educational and that it helps you on your own path.- Levon Aronian }
1. -- *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) FM to Strong IM"]
[Black "Radu Breahna vs. Levon Aronian, Bucharest 1995"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hi everyone! This is a game I played in 1995; why did I start showing my career from that year? Well, I began to play at the age of 9, and unlike today I wasn't a great player, so my games aren't that valuable.  The games that show where it really starts to come together for me, were around 1995 when I was already a Fide Master. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ I used to play the GrÃ¼nfeld because it is a dynamic opening, my coach Grandmaster Melikset Khachiyan taught me how to play it. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 { Basically, White is immediately attacking the center. }
5... Ne4
{ A tactical maneuver, which makes sure that Black doesn't lose the center while also developing the pieces. }
6. cxd5
{ There are other moves that I have played myself, for example,  6.Bh4  or  6.Bf4  , which leads to a completely different kind of game.  6...Nxc3  7.bxc3  dxc4  8.e3  c5  9.Bxc4  and then Black is trying to fight against this center slowly, maybe trying to play ...e5 liquidating the center and the position. }
6... Nxg5 7. Nxg5 e6
{ As you can see, I am attacking both the g5-knight and the d5-pawn. } 8. Qd2
{ An extremely popular system at that time. } 8... exd5 9. Qe3+ Kf8
{ There is no good way to cover the check, so I have to move the king. This  9...Qe7  simply loses material  10.Qxe7+  Kxe7  11.Nxd5+  . }
10. g3
{ And here he played the strange-looking move g3. It was something that I had never seen before the game. The normal move is  10.Qf4  Bf6  11.h4  , and this is something I will also discuss in a different game later in the course. }
10... h6
{ This move makes a lot of sense, because either way, I will have to kick the knight out.  10...Bf6  is also possible but I liked ...h6 more. }
11. Nh3
{ If White goes  11.Nf3  , then it is not totally clear what he had really achieved with the move g3. It should be noted that the bishop on g2 will be blockaded with ...c6 and ...d5, so in a way, it feels like the bishop does not belong on g2. }
11... c5
{ Of course, I can play  11...c6  12.Nf4  h5  and then bring the b8-knight to f6, and Black has a healthy position. But then I started thinking about it, it is time to punish my opponent.   Another decent move here would be  11...Nc6  12.Rd1  , and now I can either go  12...Nb4  to generate some threats or even  12...Ne7  .  I concluded that although the move g3 was a novelty, it is not of excellent quality.  We also have to take into account that I wasn't a very experienced player, I started playing chess very late, and I did not have many games in these structures. The point of this entire course is to show you more or less how I evolved as a player. }
12. dxc5
{ It is obvious that White does not have any good ways to defend the d4-pawn. }
12... d4 13. Qd2 { The knight is not hanging because of the pin. } 13... Qe8
{ Black has plenty of options to get out of the pin, my ...Qe8 was also good, but I missed a powerful idea in this position:  13...Qe7  14.Nb5  Bd7!   I missed this move from a distance and thought this was the way to go @@StartFEN@@rnb2k1r/pp2qpb1/6pp/1NP5/3p4/6PN/PP1QPP1P/R3KB1R b KQ - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qxc5  , but after the winning reply  15.Rc1  Qxb5  16.Rxc8+  Ke7  17.Rxh8  Bxh8  18.Bg2  , White is already close to winning.   After @@StartFEN@@rnb2k1r/pp2qpb1/6pp/2P5/3p4/2N3PN/PP1QPP1P/R3KB1R w KQ - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nb5  I thought that  14...Nc6  was also possible but after  15.Nd6  it will take a lot of time to get rid of the strong d6-knight.   Another important point in this position and a difficult one actually if you're not used to sacrificing material is @@StartFEN@@rn3k1r/pp1bqpb1/6pp/1NP5/3p4/6PN/PP1QPP1P/R3KB1R w KQ - 4 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Nxd4  Nc6  which is pretty much crushing because the a8-rook will enter the game quickly, and White will lose a lot of time coordinating his pieces  16.Nb3  Rd8  17.Qe3  then b2 hangs. Or  17.Qc1  is even worse, now  17...Ne5  is completely crushing.  18.Qe3  Bc6  and Black has also crazy threats  like ...Nd3+ and ...Nxf3+, in case White goes f3.   Another possibility for White here is @@StartFEN@@rn3k1r/pp1bqpb1/6pp/1NP5/3p4/6PN/PP1QPP1P/R3KB1R w KQ - 4 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Nd6  , but then after  15...Bc6  , the real problem in this position is that once White loses the right to castle after  16.Rg1  , then everything falls apart because O-O-O is not an option  16...Nd7  17.b4  a5  18.b5  Bd5  and the g7-bishop is absolutely dominating the game.   After @@StartFEN@@rn3k1r/pp1bqpb1/6pp/1NP5/3p4/6PN/PP1QPP1P/R3KB1R w KQ - 4 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Nc7  Bxh3  16.Nxa8  Bxf1  It is not so difficult to see that after ...Nc6-...Qd8, I'm trapping the knight on a8 and gaining a material advantage and it's actually losing for White because he doesn't have any open files for his rooks.   17.Rxf1  Nc6  18.O-O-O  Qd8  19.e3  Qxa8  20.exd4  Bxd4  . Now the d4-bishop will become a very strong piece, and the king will be safe on g7.  It would be a completely different story if the queens were off the board, but after  21.b4  a6  , the white king is too exposed.   There's nothing wrong with @@StartFEN@@rnbq1k1r/pp3pb1/6pp/2P5/3p4/2N3PN/PP1QPP1P/R3KB1R b KQ - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nc6  , but after  14.Ne4  Qd5  15.f3  and then Nf4 incoming. For me it seems that I had to force his knight to retreat to d1, which is a better option. }
14. Nd1 Nd7 { A tactical move! } 15. Nf4
{ Can you guys tell me what's wrong with the move  15.Rc1?  After  15...Ne5!  16.Bg2   @@StartBracket@@Or  16.Ng1  Qc6  17.f3  Be6  and Black is completely crushing.@@EndBracket@@  16...Bxh3  17.Bxh3  Nf3+  it's 'finita la comedia'. }
15... Nxc5 16. Bg2
{ We come to a point of why I'm actually sharing this game with you.  If we look at this position, what is my main problem with Black? Well, the glaring problem is that my king is on f8. If my king was on g8 and my rook on f8 then Black would be much much better.   Another issue is of course the unstable position of my knight on c5. The knight belongs on the e4-square, therefore I need to prepare for it before White gets Rc1 in. }
16... Be5
{ In the game, I thought what I was doing made a lot of sense, but we will see why it doesn't work. }
17. O-O
{ 17.Rc1  here I have this tactical idea  17...Bxf4  18.Qxf4   @@StartBracket@@  18.gxf4  Ne6  19.e3  more knight tricks with  19...Nxf4  @@EndBracket@@  18...Nd3+  I was so in love with these knight checks, being the young trickster that I was, which I am now as well. Generally, I was thinking that I will manage to give the check somehow; my older opponent will blunder it somehow as I naively believed. }
17... Kg7 18. Nd5 Qd8
{ Black can play  18...Be6  as I thought from distance. What do you think is wrong with this move?   19.Nc7  tactical trick!  19...Bxc7  20.Qxd4+  and then he's taking my knight.  20...Kh7  21.Qxc5  , White has a healthy pawn up and the knight on d1 that was supposed to be passive because my d4-pawn wedge just comes out to c3. It seems that the move that was quite obvious to me turned out to be a bad mistake.   I should have played  18...Bf5  the last moment where I could at least hope for some relief.  19.f4  Ne4  20.Bxe4  Bxe4  21.fxe5  Bxd5  22.Qxd4  Be6  and White is much better but at least I'm still in the game for now. }
19. Rc1 Na6 20. b3
{ My opponent played slowly and I somehow managed to survive. Had he played  20.f4  Nc7  or even f4 one move earlier: @@StartFEN@@r1bq3r/pp3pk1/6pp/2nNb3/3p4/6P1/PP1QPPBP/R2N1RK1 w - - 6 19@@EndFEN@@  19.f4  Bf6  20.Nf2  , these positions are collapsing for Black.   Let's go back to the position on move 16 and try to figure out what I should've done.  @@StartFEN@@r1b1qk1r/pp3pb1/6pp/2n5/3p1N2/6P1/PP1QPPBP/R2NK2R b KQ - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bf5  but then I wasn't so sure after he goes  17.Qb4  Qe7  18.O-O  and some Nd5 will come and it is kind of annoying.   Another option is @@StartFEN@@r1b1qk1r/pp3pb1/6pp/2n5/3p1N2/6P1/PP1QPPBP/R2NK2R b KQ - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Rb8  but then you have to calculate what happens after  17.Qa5  b6  18.Qxa7  Bb7  is probably okay for Black, but this is not ideal.   @@StartFEN@@r1b1qk1r/pp3pb1/6pp/2n5/3p1N2/6P1/PP1QPPBP/R2NK2R b KQ - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Kg8  is the best move, only now with the idea to bring the king to h7 and get rid of the tactical problems. After  17.Rc1  , I can finally put the knight on e4.  17...Ne4  18.Qb4   @@StartBracket@@  18.Qd3  Bf5  19.g4  doesn't work because of?  19...Nxf2!  @@EndBracket@@  18...a5  19.Qb6  Kh7  20.O-O  Ra6  21.Qc7  and finally my pieces are harmonious, while the d1-knight is still wedged in. I can do any move  21...f5  or  21...Nd6  and this would have been a mature reaction, but I wouldn't have learned this valuable lesson if I didn't make this mistake. }
20... Re8 21. Nb2 Nc7 22. Nf4 Ne6 23. Nfd3 Bf6 24. Nc4 Ng5 25. Nc5 Qe7 26. Qb4
Bg4 27. h4 Ne6 28. Nxe6+ Qxe6 29. Qxb7 Rad8 30. f3 Bh3 31. Rc2 g5 32. h5 Rd7
33. Qb5 Rde7 34. g4 Bxg2 35. Kxg2 Qc8 36. Na3 Qd8 37. Rd2 Qd6 38. Nc4 Rxe2+ 39.
Rf2 Rxf2+ 40. Rxf2 Qe6 41. Nd6 Rd8 42. Nf5+ Kh8 43. Re2 Qc8 44. Qd3 Qc3 45.
Qxc3 dxc3 46. Kf2 Rd1 47. Rc2 Kh7 48. Ke2 Rh1 49. Nd6 Rh2+ 50. Kd3 Rh3 51. Ke3
Be5 52. Nb5 f5 53. gxf5 g4 54. Ke4 Rh2 55. Rc1 Re2+ 56. Kd3 gxf3 57. Nxc3 Bxc3
58. Rxc3 Rxa2 59. Ke4 f2 60. Rf3 Kg7 61. Ke5 Re2+ 62. Kd6 Kf6 63. b4 Rb2 64.
Kc5 a6 65. Kc4 Ra2 66. Kb3 Re2 67. Kc4 Rd2 68. Kc5 Rb2 69. Kc4 Rc2+ 70. Kd3 Ra2
71. Kd4 Rb2 72. Kc3 Ra2 73. Kd4 Ra4 74. Kc5 a5 75. b5 Ra2 76. b6 Rb2 77. Kc6 a4
78. b7 Rc2+ 79. Kd7 Rb2 80. Kc7 Rc2+ *


