13. Qd2 { What powerful idea did I miss? } 13... Qe7 14. Nb5 Bd7
{ I missed this move from a distance! I thought this was the way to go:  14...Qxc5  , but White has a winning idea.  15.Rc1!  Qf5  @@StartBracket@@  15...Qxb5  16.Rxc8+  Ke7  17.Rxh8  Bxh8  18.Bg2  and White is better.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb2k1r/pp3pb1/6pp/1N3q2/3p4/6PN/PP1QPP1P/2R1KB1R w K - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Nd6+-  .   I thought  14...Nc6  is also possible, but it will take a lot of time to get rid of the strong d6-knight after  15.Nd6  . }
15. Nc7
{ Another important point in this position and a difficult one actually if you're not used to sacrificing material is  15.Nxd4  Nc6  . This is pretty much crushing because the a8-rook will enter the game quickly, and White will lose a lot of time coordinating his pieces.  16.Nb3  Rd8  After  17.Qe3  , b2 hangs, and  17.Qc1  is even worse now as  17...Ne5  18.Qe3  Bc6  is completely crushing.  Black has also crazy threats like ...Nd3+ and ...Nxf3+, in case White goes f3.   Another possibility for White here is  15.Nd6  , but then after  15...Bc6  , the real problem in this position is that once White loses the right to castle after  16.Rg1  , then everything falls apart because O-O-O is not an option.  16...Nd7  17.b4  a5  18.b5  Bd5  and the g7-bishop is absolutely dominating the game. }
15... Bxh3 16. Nxa8 Bxf1
{ It is not so difficult to see that after ...Nc6 and ...Qd8, I'm trapping the knight on a8 and gaining a material advantage. This is losing for white because he doesn't have any open files for his rooks. }
17. Rxf1 Nc6 18. O-O-O Qd8
{ Black is just winning. For example, after  19.e3  Qxa8  20.exd4  Bxd4  ,  the bishop on d4 will become a very strong piece, and the king will be safe on g7. It would be a completely different story if the queens were off the board. }
