[Result "*"]

{ This is another game I played in 1995 against the Romanian IM Marius Manolache. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5
{ Again, in 1995 this was a very popular line. } 5... Ne4 6. cxd5 Nxg5 7. Nxg5
e6 8. Qd2 exd5 9. Qe3+ Kf8 10. Qf4
{ Unlike the game against Radu Breahna my opponent here played the more topical move Qf4. }
10... Bf6 11. h4 h6
{ Honestly, at that moment when I was playing the game, I didn't know that there's a really tricky line for White here that starts with  12.Nxd5  Bxg5  13.Qe5  . There are many games like this and  13...f6  doesn't work because of  14.Qxc7  , so the theory is: @@StartFEN@@rnbq1k1r/ppp2p2/6pp/3NQ1b1/3P3P/8/PP2PPP1/R3KB1R b KQ - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rh7  14.hxg5  Nc6  15.Qe4  Bf5  16.Qf3  Nxd4  17.Qa3  Kg7  18.Ne3  . This is extremely dangerous for White but very interesting after White tries to castle queenside, and Black's pieces are perhaps misplaced.   Sometimes it is a good thing when you don't know certain lines. Later in a game in the same year I played  11...c6  , and then after  12.e4  , my position was horrendous and I lost without a fight. }
12. Nf3 Kg7 13. O-O-O
{ On the subject of knowing theory, this is the problem sometimes. When you're trying to avoid forced lines and go into something passive, normally, it doesn't lead to good things.  If the move that avoids the forced line is just a little bit worse than the main variation, then maybe you can afford to do that. But in this position, @@StartFEN@@rnbq1k1r/ppp2p1p/5bp1/3p2N1/3P1Q1P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R3KB1R b KQ h3 0 11@@EndFEN@@ if your only alternative is  11...c6  instead of the forced line after ...h6, then you are better off forcing yourself to spend a lot more time on the forced line. }
13... Be6 14. e4
{ Back in the day they also played with  14.e3  but there's a very nice plan for Black here after  14...Nd7  15.Bd3  c6  and the idea is quite nice for Black, whatever White does  15.Kb1  for example, Black will oppose White's strongest piece, the queen on f4 with  15...Qb8!  @@StartBracket@@once you see this idea it is very hard to forget it@@EndBracket@@  16.Qxb8  Raxb8  and Black has easy play with ...Be7-d6, ...Nf6-h5-g4 or ...Rc8, ...c5, ...a6, ...b5-b4. }
14... dxe4 15. Ne5
{ 15.d5  Bf5  16.Nd4  Bxd4  17.Rxd4  h5   15.Nxe4  is also possible, knowing myself I'll probably play  15...Bd5   @@StartBracket@@  15...Bxa2  is supposedly the best move in the position but it is rather scary to allow Black to play  16.d5  @@EndBracket@@  16.g4  Nc6  17.Bd3  Bxe4  18.Bxe4  Qd6  19.Qxd6  cxd6  20.Kb1  Rae8  . }
15... Nc6
{ Black can also play  15...Nd7  16.Nxe4  Bxe5  17.dxe5  Qe7  this is totally fine  18.h5  g5  19.Qe3  is creating some disbalance; White is trying to play with f4, an interesting position.  Generally, if we look at this @@StartFEN@@rn1q3r/ppp2pk1/4bbpp/4N3/3PpQ1P/2N5/PP3PP1/2KR1B1R b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@ position, Black is a little bit underdeveloped, but on the other hand, white has an Isolani. I really like what Nimzowitsch said: 'Isolani means that you will have weak squares around it, ' so the weak squares are also the central squares @@StartBracket@@e4-d4-c4@@EndBracket@@ and so even when the Isolani is gone, the central squares remain weak without any support.   Another way for Black to play is, of course,  15...Re8  16.Nxe4  Nd7!?  and if  17.Nxd7  Bxd7  18.Bc4  Bf5  is extremely healthy for Black; no wonder they don't play this line anymore.   I played ...Nc6. In fact, I'm showing this game as an example of a tactical idea and generally understanding the pawn structures in the opening. So why is ...Nc6 a good move?  After  16.Nxc6  bxc6  , I get the b-file, and after  17.Nxe4  I can take on a2 safely  17...Bxa2  because I'm not worried about my bishop getting stuck anymore. }
16. Nxe4 Nb4 17. a3 Nd5 18. Qg3
{ Now we reach a critical point. As often, these critical points happen before White gets his last pieces in the game. Black has time here to improve his position. In the game, I didn't realize that I played a passive move and got in trouble really quickly.   Black has an excellent way to solve all of his issues, I'm sure you can find it. Personally, I couldn't find it in the game, but once you realize it is there, it is not so difficult; a tactical way to solve all our problems.  18...c5  is a possibility but I'm not sure we are going anywhere after  19.Nxc5  .   If you are thinking about  18...Bf5  then yes, this is the first move and now after  19.Bd3  , the star move  19...Nf4!  is absolutely gorgeous. We're threatening to take on d3, and if White takes on f4  20.Qxf4  we take on d4  20...Qxd4  and we created a pin on the queen along the fourth rank. If White plays  21.Nc4  , then simply  21...b5  and he can't protect the knight! Obviously, the knight can't move because of the mate on b2, and if any bishop move we can take one of the knights. White is losing here.  White had to settle with @@StartFEN@@r2q3r/ppp2pk1/5bpp/4Nb2/3PNn1P/P2B2Q1/1P3PP1/2KR3R w - - 5 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Nxf6  Nxd3  21.Rxd3  Qxf6  . We got rid of the pressure in the center and we are ready to counterattack the d4-pawn.  22.Rf3  is nothing after  22...h5  and the bishop is fantastic on f5, eying the white king. }
18... b6
{ One lesson from this game is when you generally play normal moves throughout the game, then there should be an active way for you to solve all of your problems. In the game, I played the passive 18... b6. }
19. Bc4 c6 20. Rd3
{ My position became unpleasant because now the rook is coming to f3. Although I somehow managed to survive this terrible position in the end. }
20... Be7 21. Rf3 Qc7 22. Kb1 Rac8 23. Rc1 c5 24. Bb5 Nf6 25. Bd3
{ In general, when you see five enemy pieces around your poor king, something bad is going to happen for sure, by some miracle I managed to survive this. }
25... Nh5 26. Qh2 Rhd8 27. g4 Nf6 28. g5 Nxe4 29. gxh6+ Kh8 30. Bxe4 Rxd4 31.
Re1 Bd6 32. Bc2 Rd5 33. Rfe3 Rxe5 34. Rxe5 Bxe5 35. Qxe5+ Qxe5 36. Rxe5 Re8 37.
Kc1 Kh7 38. h5 Kxh6 39. hxg6 fxg6 40. Ba4 Re7 41. Bb3 c4 42. Bxc4 Rc7 43. Rxe6
Rxc4+ 44. Kd2 Rd4+ 45. Ke2 Rc4 46. Kd3 Rf4 47. Ke3 Rc4 48. f4 Kh5 49. Re5+ Kh6
50. Re6 Kh5 51. Re7 Rc2 52. Kf3 Kh6 53. Rxa7 Rxb2 54. Ke4 b5 55. Ra6 Kg7 56.
Ke5 b4 57. Ra7+ Kh6 58. a4 Kh5 59. Rb7 b3 60. Kd4 Ra2 61. Rxb3 Rxa4+ 62. Ke3
Kg4 63. Rb6 Ra3+ 64. Ke4 Ra4+ 65. Ke3 Ra3+ 66. Ke4 Ra4+ 67. Ke3 Ra3+ *


