[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) FM to Strong IM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Nebojsa Nikcevic, Cannes 1996"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Up to this point in my career, I mainly played sidelines of the Italian. I now felt that I was time to shift to main lines. }
3... a6 4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ Black decided to go after my bishop immediately. I had never seen this idea before. }
6. O-O
{ Of course, there are many options for White here:  6.a4  and  6.d4  both look logical to me.   In general, White can't easily capture on e5 in the Ruy Lopez. In this case, Black wins the pawn on g2 after  6.Nxe5  Nxb3  7.axb3  Qg5  . This feels wrong for White. }
6... d6 7. d4 f6
{ Let's look at White's options. First of all, why not take on g8?  8.Bxg8  Black loses the right to castle kingside after  8...Rxg8  , considerable slowing down his development. After  9.a4  b4  10.c3  ,  White opens files and tries to exploit the fact that Black's king is still in the center.   Another interesting option is  8.a4  , freeing the a2-square for the bishop, essentially forcing Black to capture on b3. Play could continue  8...Nxb3  9.cxb3  Bd7  10.Be3  Ne7  11.Qc2  Ng6  12.Nc3  Be7  13.dxe5  fxe5  14.Nd5  and White has a strong knight on d5 and pressure against Black's backward c7-pawn. I liked this option for White.   A lovely 'trick' for White is  8.Bd5  . With the knight on a5, we can provoke Black into playing ...c6.  8...c6  9.Bxg8  Rxg8  10.Nc3  . Now that ...Nc6 is no longer possible, Black will need three moves to bring the knight back into play: ...Nb7-d8-e6. Of course, in order to do that, Black would need to remove his queen from the d8-square too.  In conclusion, there were many good moves available to White. }
8. h3
{ 8.h3 wasn't one of them. It was not at all necessary to prevent ...Bg4. I was clearly inexperienced. }
8... Ne7 9. Qe2
{ What am I trying to accomplish? Black needs ...Ng6, ...Be7, ...Bd7 and ...O-O to complete his development. In the meantime, I need to make use of my lead in development.  9.Qe2 is a very timid move. I'm trying to play Rd1 and develop slowly, pretending to understand the position. 'When we face higher-rated opponents, we try to play classically and it's simply insecurity'.   9.Nc3  followed by a4 and bringing the knight to d5 was a better plan. }
9... Nxb3 10. axb3 Ng6 11. Be3 Be7 12. Rd1
{ 12.c4  is more in the spirit of the position. The queen is on e2, attacking b5. After  12...b4  I would have been able to complicate the game with  13.c5  dxc5  14.dxe5  , but quite often, when facing a higher-rated opponent, we tend to avoid any kind of unbalance. }
12... O-O 13. Nc3 Bb7 14. dxe5
{ My plan was to play  14.Nd5  , but then I saw a problem:  14...Bxd5!  15.exd5  e4  16.Nh2   16.Ne1  From e1, the knight could still be rerouted to c6 via c2 and b4 @@StartBracket@@after c2-c4@@EndBracket@@. Still, after  16...f5  17.f4  exf3   17...Bh4  is too eager, I can still control the dark squares with  18.Kh2  .  18.Nxf3  Bf6  my pawns are doubled and Black will play ...Qd7 and ...Rae8.  16...f5  and Black is simply better: he can bring his bishop to g5, threatening ...Nf4. Meanwhile, White's knight will never reach the e6-square. }
14... fxe5 15. Nd5
{ I remember being quite optimistic about my chances here: I will play c2-c4-c5 and pressurize the c-file. However, I learned a tough lesson now. }
15... Qd7
{ I had missed this extremely strong move. Black intends ...Bd8 and ...Ne7, possibly followed by ...c7-c6. Now the d5-knight doesn't look so impressive anymore.   15...Bxd5?  16.exd5  gives White the advantage because of the g6-knight. After Nd2-e4, I dominate the light squares.   15...c6  is quite a concession:  16.Nxe7+  Qxe7  17.c4â©²  . }
16. c4
{ Let's make some normal moves, to see quickly things can go wrong for White:  16.b4  Bd8  17.b3  Qe6  18.c4  c6  19.Nb6  Bxb6  20.Bxb6  Nf4  21.Qe3   21.Qf1?  Nxh3+  22.gxh3  Rxf3-+  21...Qg6-+  . }
16... Bd8 17. c5 Qe6
{ Objectively, White's position is acceptable â I can't be worse. } 18. Rac1
{ White plans to trade pawns on d6 and play Nc7, ...Bxc7, Rxc7, activating the rook on the 7th rank.   A neutral move to illustrate White's idea is  18...Kh8  . After  19.cxd6  cxd6  20.Nc7  Bxc7  21.Rxc7  things start to look dubious for Black. The tactics after  21...Bxe4  22.Ng5  Qf5  23.g4!  Bf3  don't work for him; he loses material after  24.gxf5  Bxe2  25.Rd2-+  with a double attack. }
18... h6
{ A pretty good move, preventing Ng5. Black wants to play ...Ne7 and after the exchange of knights, my b3- and e4-pawns will be weak. Black would have the bishop pair and a very solid structure too. }
19. cxd6 cxd6 20. Rc3
{ I should have realized that ...Ne7 is coming. A good way to prepare for the exchange of knights is  20.Ne1  . Now I can solidify my center with  20...Ne7  21.Nxe7+  Bxe7  22.Qd3  and possibly bring the other knight to d5. }
20... Ne7 { Here I finally realized what was happening. } 21. Nb6
{ If  21.Qd3  then  21...Nxd5  22.exd5  Qf5  is strong. Black's bishop pair gains in strength with the exchange of queens. The d5-pawn becomes a liability too. I wanted to avoid this scenario with 21.Nb6. }
21... Bxb6 22. Bxb6 Ng6 { The knight is coming to f4. } 23. Rc7 Nf4 24. Qe3
{ The queen has to protect the knight on f3, not allowing ...Nxh3+ tricks. }
24... Bc8
{ I thought  24...Rf7  25.Rxf7  Kxf7  26.Bc7  was a logical continuation, when I was optimistic about my position. After the text move, I can't get my bishop to c7 and Black is threatening ...Qg6 when the h-pawn becomes very weak.  My rook is on the 7th rank but it isn't doing anything. }
25. Ne1
{ I should have played  25.Nh4  Qf6  26.Nf5  Bxf5  27.exf5  in order to exchange some pieces and reduce my opponent's attacking chances. After  27...d5  I'm still worse, but I may be able to hang on. }
25... d5 26. Nd3
{ The best chances of survival were offered by  26.Qc5  Qg6  27.Qc6  . } 26...
d4 27. Nxf4 Qxb6 28. Qc1
{ 28.Nd5  doesn't work because of  28...Qxc7  29.Nxc7  dxe3  30.Nxa8  exf2+  31.Kf1  Bb7  32.Nb6  Bxe4  . }
28... exf4
{ White lost a piece. From here on, I missed many opportunities to resign. }
29. Rc6 Qd8 30. Qc5 Qg5 31. Qxg5 hxg5 32. Rxd4 Ra7
{ I should have resigned here. } 33. Rc5 g4 34. hxg4 Bxg4 35. f3 Be6 36. b4 Bc4
37. Kh2 Rf6 38. e5 Rf5 39. g4 fxg3+ 40. Kxg3 Raf7 41. f4 g5 42. Rdxc4 bxc4 43.
e6 R7f6
{ I played too academically in this game. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p3pp/p2p1p2/np2p3/3PP3/1B3N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h3  was completely unnecessary. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2p1n1pp/p2p1p2/np2p3/3PP3/1B3N1P/PPP2PP1/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qe2  followed by Rd1 was a poor decision too; not using my lead in development.  But things really started to go wrong for me after @@StartFEN@@r2b1rk1/1bp3pp/p2pq1n1/1pPNp3/4P3/1P2BN1P/1P2QPP1/2RR2K1 b - - 2 18@@EndFEN@@  18...h6  , when I wasn't aware of his threat ...Ne7. The same goes for @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/2R3p1/pB1pq2p/1p2p3/4Pn2/1P2QN1P/1P3PP1/3R2K1 w - - 5 25@@EndFEN@@  25.Ne1  , when I didn't realize Black was threatening ...d5.  In conclusion, I was completely unaware of the middlegame ideas: I had never seen @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2pp1ppp/p1n5/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Na5  before, and more importantly, I didn't know the @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1b1pp/p2p2n1/1p1Np3/4P3/1P2BN1P/1PP1QPP1/R2R2K1 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Qd7  followed by ...Bd8 idea @@StartBracket@@or ...Rae8 first, to activate the rook@@EndBracket@@. Later in my games, I have been able to use this maneuver as Black many times â it was a valuable lesson. }
*


