[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) FM to Strong IM"]
[Black "Christian Bauer vs. Levon Aronian, Cannes 1996"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played in the Cannes Open in France. I was 14 years old and my opponent, Christian Bauer, was an IM at that time. He is a well-established 2600-player now, with a peak rating of 2682 in August 2012. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ I was very ambitious and played sharp openings. } 6. Be2
{ This variation was very popular back then. One year earlier, the World Championship match Anand-Kasparov was played. Kasparov played the Dragon and it became extremely popular. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nb3 O-O 9. Re1
{ This was Karpov's pet line. Nowadays, it's not so popular anymore because it's not overly ambitious. }
9... Be6
{ Another way to play is  9...a6  , followed by ...b5 and ...Bb7. With the text move, Black aims for a quick ...d5. }
10. Bf1
{ 10.Bg5  allows a neat tactical resource:  10...d5  11.Bxf6  Bxf6  12.exd5  Bxc3  and because the rook on e1 is attacked, Black regains his pawn. }
10... d5 { My opponent was very surprised to see this move. } 11. Nc5 d4 12.
Nxe6 fxe6
{ The doubled e-pawns look ugly, but I had some concrete ideas, based on my piece activity. }
13. Nb1
{ Forced. The natural  13.Ne2  lands White in trouble:  13...Nxe4  14.Nf4  Nxf2!  15.Qe2   15.Kxf2  e5-+  15...e5  16.Ne6  Qb6  . In return for the exchange, I would have had two pawns and a strong center. White has to watch out for ...d4-d3 ideas, or simply ...e5-e4-e3. }
13... Ne5 14. h3
{ 14.Nd2?  Nfg4  15.Re2  d3  16.cxd3  Qd4  isn't going to end well for White. }
14... Qb6 15. Bd3
{ White still can't develop his knight, since  15.Nd2  runs into  15...d3  again.  16.cxd3  Nfg4  This is a recipe for disaster for White! }
15... Nh5
{ If White plays too slowly, I may capture on d3 and try to checkmate him on the dark squares with ...Be5-c7 and ...Qd6. Of course, ...Nf4 is in the air too. }
16. Nd2 Nf4
{ This was still my preparation and I knew Black was doing more than fine. }
17. Nc4
{ This was the first new move for me. It very much feels like a bailout.   17.Nf1  loses a pawn to  17...Nfxd3  18.cxd3  Qb5  .   17.Nb3  also looks dangerous for White. At the very least, I can force a draw with  17...Nfxd3  18.cxd3  Qa6  19.Nc5  Qb6  20.Nb3  Qa6  , but maybe I should keep the tension with @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp2p1bp/1q2p1p1/4n3/3pPn2/1N1B3P/PPP2PP1/R1BQR1K1 b - - 6 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Rac8  . }
17... Nxc4 18. Bxc4 d3 19. Be3
{ 19.cxd3  will lead to disaster again:  19...Nxg2  20.Kxg2  Rxf2+  21.Kh1  Raf8  and there are simply too many black pieces around the white king.  Chessable note: In the video, Aronian shows @@StartFEN@@r5k1/pp2p1bp/1q2p1p1/8/2B1P3/3P3P/PP3r2/R1BQR2K b - - 1 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Qd6  but this allows the unusual defense  22.e5  Qc6  23.Re4!  and White is better. }
19... Qxb2 20. cxd3 Qxa1 21. Qxa1 Bxa1 22. Rxa1
{ Now I'm an exchange up and we have an equal amount of pawns. White has the bishop pair, though.  This was the key moment of the game. First of all, we need to understand what White's threat is. White is threatening g2-g3.   Let's play a random move to demonstrate how strong g2-g3 is.  22...b6  23.g3  Nxh3+  @@StartBracket@@After  23...Ne2+  24.Kg2  Kf7  the e6-pawn is too weak.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/p3p2p/1p2p1p1/8/2B1P3/3PB1Pn/P4P2/R5K1 w - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24.Kg2  and the knight is trapped. }
22... Kg7
{ From here on, my position started deteriorating.   If I had taken the time to study the position, I probably would have found  22...a6!  . This move undermines the d3-square and brings all my pieces to life.  23.a4  b5  Exchanging rooks favours Black.  24.axb5  axb5  25.Rxa8  Rxa8  26.Bxb5  Ne2+  27.Kh2  e5  . Now I sacrificed a pawn but the quality of my pieces increased by at least 2 points or pawns.  In this position, Black can play for a win without risking anything. The d4-square is a strong outpost for the knight and White's d3-pawn is weak.   After  22...Rad8  23.Bxa7  Nxd3  24.Bxe6+  the bishops are extremely strong in an open position like this, especially with one pair of rooks remaining on the board.   22...g5  is too weakening. }
23. Kf1 e5 { I didn't consider the time factor.  23...a6  was still possible. }
24. g3 Nh5 25. Ke2
{ Now the position is unclear and in fact, I would already prefer White.  It will take Black 5 moves to get the knight to d4 whereas it could immediately have jumped to d4 from e2. Now, e5 is weak and White's rook is coming to b5. }
25... b6 26. Rb1
{ I played all my pawns to the dark squares and still, my position was dreadfully unpleasant. White consolidated his position because I didn't consider the quality of my pieces.  If the knight were on d4, it would completely have changed the assessment of the position. The knight is only strong when it's on a strong square. }
26... Nf6 27. Rb5 Nd7 28. Rd5
{ I'm still an exchange up, but in reality, I'm completely lost. } 28... Rad8
29. Bb5
{ Even without 29.Bb5, I would have been lost. For example, after  29.h4  I'm out of moves.  29...Rf6  loses to  30.Bg5  . The bishops are simply too strong now. }
29... Nc5 30. Rxe5 Kf6 31. d4 Ne6 32. Kd3 Rd6 33. Bc4
{ I lost without a fight.  I learned to have a good long think when my analysis finishes.  On move 22, the structure has changed and the material is unbalanced. Spend some time and try to understand what happened. If you don't, you can lose without ever having understood what happened. }
33... Rfd8 { 33...Nc7  34.Bg5++- } 34. Bd5 R8d7 35. h4 b5 36. g4 Ra6 37. g5+
Kf7 38. Bb3 Rdd6 39. Rxb5 Rab6 40. Ra5 Ra6 41. Rc5 Ke8 42. Rc3 Nxd4 43. Bxd4 e5
44. Bd5 exd4 45. Rc7 Ra3+ 46. Kxd4 Rd7 47. Rc8+ Rd8 48. Rc2 Kd7 49. Rb2 Ke7 50.
Ke5 Kf8 51. f4 Re8+ 52. Be6 Re3 53. Rb4 Kg7 54. h5 gxh5 55. f5 h4 56. Rb7+ Kh8
57. Kf4 Re1 58. f6 Rf1+ 59. Kg4 Rg1+ 60. Kh5 h3 61. Kh6 *


