[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) FM to Strong IM"]
[Black "Rasul Ibrahimov vs. Levon Aronian, Moscow 1997"]
[Result "*"]

{ It was the year 1997, and I got an invitation to play in the Kasparov Cup in Moscow. I was rated 2420 and quite confident after becoming an IM in 1996 during the Olympiad in Yerevan, and I was the highest-rated player in this tournament. This game was played against Rasul Ibrahimov, a very solid player from Azerbaijan who would later become a Grandmaster.Back in the day, I used to play this line with Black. It wasn't very good, but it was something I used to play successfully. Let's take a look at the game. }
1. e4 c5 { A Sicilian. } 2. c3 d6 3. d4 Nf6
{ Generally ...d6 is a kind of passive option against c3, but it was kind of popular back then and somehow mimics the Pirc. }
4. Bd3 Nc6 5. Ne2 { This is a very flexible setup for White. } 5... g6 6. O-O
Bg7 7. h3
{ White is playing very well. He is developing his pieces and has the center, so it's all very logical. }
7... O-O 8. Be3
{ In such structures, Black has a choice. Whenever White plays  8.Be3  you have the option to take  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  and play  9...Nb4  10.Nbc3  Nxd3  11.Qxd3  .  Black gets two bishops. The only drawback is that White has the center and that the c8-bishop is a bit passive. It takes a long time for the bishop on c8 to develop. Because where is it supposed to go?If I play something like  11...b6  ,  then there are these dangers of the c6-square being a bit too weak after  12.d5  The knight will go to d4 and the position might be a bit passive for Black. This was one of the alternative options in the game. }
8... b6 { I decided to go for a neutral move. } 9. Nd2 Bb7 10. a3
{ So far my opponent's play makes a lot of sense. He has a very symmetrical setup and is slowly preparing to play b4. White is slightly better. }
10... e5
{ This is more or less an intimidation tactic. Since I was 100 points higher rated than my opponent, I felt that it would just scare him. And it actually worked. But of course,  10...e5  is not a good move.Instead I think I should have, objectively speaking, played something more fluid like  10...e6  .  Not really giving up on my plans, and then I can maybe slowly bring my queen to e7 and the knight to d7. Trying to keep the game unclear and not show my plans too much. }
11. d5 { A very good move. White is gaining space. } 11... Ne7 12. b4
{ And then, I noticed something. I thought, wait a second, what if I can do this. Will I get compensation? I wasn't so sure, but I went for it anyway. }
12... Nexd5 13. exd5 Nxd5
{ Here he made a mistake. Ibrahimov took on c5, which is not a good move. But at this moment, the reason why I'm actually showing this game is for you to find how White should play. There is an extremely strong idea for White of a tactical nature that my opponent didn't manage to find. I hope that you will find it. It's kind of strategically and tactically sound, and it actually refutes my whole setup.If you think that White should play  14.Nc4  , this is a normal move. But it is not refuting anything. It is actually one of the best moves in the position because White keeps the balance. Black has different options, but the best is  14...e4  . White has to play  15.Bc2   White cannot capture the pawn with  15.Bxe4  because he loses the bishop on e4 after  15...Nxe3  .  The bishop is gone and Black regains his piece with a better position.  15...Nxe3  16.Nxe3  d5  17.bxc5  bxc5  Black is threatening to play d4. A move like  18.Rb1  is the best, because if I play now something like  18...Rb8  ,  what do you think that White would play here? Correct,  19.Rxb7  is the best. White is sacrificing the exchange but gets rid of the strong d5-pawn.  19...Rxb7  20.Nxd5  and now e4 is hanging. White gets good play.   @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3pbp/6p1/2pp4/4p3/P1P1N2P/2B1NPP1/1R1Q1RK1 b - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@If I play  18...Bc6  ,  what do you think is best here for White? Yes,  19.Ba4  since the bishop has to protect the d5-pawn, Black cannot afford to take the bishop on a4.  After  19...Bxa4  20.Qxa4  d4  ,  White can simply take and because of the tactics I'm losing the game.  21.Rfd1  d3  22.Qxe4  when everything is gone. The pin over the d-file is the problem.   @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3pbp/6p1/2pp4/4p3/P1P1N2P/2B1NPP1/1R1Q1RK1 b - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@Therefore, after Rb1 there is only one move that actually leads to equality for me. I believe you have already found it. Yes, it is  18...Ba6  .  Black is now threatening to play d4 anyway. And if you take on d5  19.Nxd5  I take on e2  19...Bxe2  20.Qxe2  Qxd5  21.Bxe4  when it looks like a skewer but isn't one at all because Black can play  21...Qe5  ,  21...Qe6  , and  21...Rae8  , so there are three good options. Because of the pin, Black manages to keep the material and position equal. So that was 14.Nc4, which is not the best.   You might ask me if there is something wrong with  14.c4  .  I felt that c4 is losing since I thought that I can take  14...Nxe3  15.fxe3  Qg5  .  But what do you think I missed? You have probably found it by now. Correct, it is  16.e4  ,  a very nice and beautiful move that is actually the solution to all of White's problems. So if you found this, good on you, well done! If I play now  16...Qe3+  ,  it seems like I'm winning the bishop, but no, the queen is getting trapped.  17.Kh1  Qxd3  18.Rf3  .  So what happens after c4 is that White is solving his problems by first of all establishing control over d5.   If White plays another move like  14.Be4  in an attempt to stop ...Qg5, then after  14...Nxe3  15.fxe3  d5  despite the fact that White has an extra piece for just two pawns the activity in Black's position gives him better play with many moves.  16.Bc2  One of them being  16...f5  , another one being with  16...Bh6  and the reason for it is that the white knights don't have a strong and protective position in the game.And this is, as I mentioned in some other examples, all about the quality of the pieces. So the quality of my bishops is excellent because they're helping the pawns move forward. White has lots of weaknesses @@StartBracket@@the c3 and e3-pawns for example@@EndBracket@@. The quality of the white pieces is not good because the knights don't really have a good square, and while the bishop is fine, White's main problem is that there are too many weaknesses. So 14.Be4 was not the solution.   What White accomplishes with @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3pbp/1p1p2p1/2pnp3/1P6/P1PBB2P/3NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.c4  Nxe3  15.fxe3  is that if Black tries to play anything like  15...f5  ,  then after  16.e4  we see that the quality of this knight on e2 has improved because the knight will come to d5 eventually with Nc3 and Nd5. White has a nice position.  Black has to close the center with  16...f4  when I think Black's counterplay is a bit too slow. White will just bring the knight to d5.  17.Nc3  the bishop can retreat to e2 and then there are no real prospects for Black. Because well, how am I supposed to attack? I'm supposed to attack with g5 and h5, but with the bishop on e2 you're just protecting everything. This is probably a lost position for Black. So 14.c4 was refuting my whole setup.   @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2npbp/1p1p1np1/2pPp3/1P2P3/P1PBB2P/3NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@I'm not saying  12...Nexd5  is a bad move, but @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2ppbp/1pnp1np1/2p5/3PP3/P1PBB2P/1P1NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...e5  was a bad move. And in order to prove that it's a bad move of course White had to either play @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2npbp/1p1p1np1/2pPp3/4P3/P1PBB2P/1P1NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.c4  and then slowly improve his position,  or find @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3pbp/1p1p2p1/2pnp3/1P6/P1PBB2P/3NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.c4  . }
14. bxc5
{ In the game, my opponent erred by playing  14.bxc5  after which it became a very bad position for White because I did go for the same ...Qg5 plan that didn't work after  14.c4  . }
14... Nxe3 15. fxe3 Qg5 { And now the queen is clearly not getting trapped. }
16. Rf2
{ The only reasonable defending move as the rest of the moves are losing even more material. For example, if I take after  16.Nf3  Qxe3  17.Kh1  and play  17...e4  , White loses everything. }
16... Qxe3 { I went on to take. } 17. Nb3 dxc5
{ I have three pawns for the knight and once again White didn't manage to create any space for his knight. He will not be able to come up with a defensive setup nor get any anything out of his pieces. }
18. Bc4 Rad8 19. Qf1
{ Played in order to untie his king, as the pin is really annoying. } 19... Bd5
{ Quite often we're told that we're supposed to hold on to the bishop pair because it is such a powerful combination. Even though it is a powerful combination, it is important not to fall in love with your pieces.  At the end of the day, pieces are like colors in a painting. You're going to use the colors you need, but you are not going to paint everything in one color. And here, if we look at the position, what does White have? One good bishop and nothing else. }
20. Bxd5 Rxd5
{ We just remove the bishop and after that everything becomes very smooth because Black is just too active. I am threatening to play ...f5 and can even play ...c4 and put this knight in the most awkward position on c1. So this transformation is good for me. }
21. Re1 { Threatening Nf4. } 21... Qd3
{ The queen is a good blocker in this position. The knight cannot really move from e2, as then the c3-pawn is lost. }
22. Nbc1 Qc4
{ If White wants to untie his pieces he will have to give up his c3-pawn, which is of course going to be bad for him. But I still felt that he needs to play  23.Ng3  .I felt that after this, despite the fact that White is losing some important pawns, he is at least getting some play. I think that White's position is still objectively lost, but he gets some activity. At least he could try it. }
23. Kh1 { Was what my opponent played instead. } 23... f5
{ And now White doesn't even have the Ng3 option. The game didn't last too long, and the rest was very easy. Once you don't activate your pieces, these things are bound to happen. }
24. g3 Rfd8 25. Kh2 Rd2 26. Kg2 Bh6 27. Kh2 Qd5
{ I pushed ...e4 next and won a smooth game. What I wanted to discuss with you in this game was that if you play such a risky line with Black, make sure that you have something tactically, as strategically it's all very risky.@@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2ppbp/1pnp1np1/2p5/3PP3/P1PBB2P/1P1NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@Today you cannot force me to play  10...e5  , even when playing against players of similar strength as my opponent back then @@StartBracket@@who was rated 2300@@EndBracket@@. Right now I understand how risky it is, as you might not get any counterplay. In the present day, I would play something like  10...e6  and try to slowly mix up the plans making sure that I don't commit too much.  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2npbp/1p1p1np1/2pPp3/1P2P3/P1PBB2P/3NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@But even today, I would probably take on d5.  12...Nexd5  ,  otherwise, it is just too dangerous, as strategically it is already the point where I have to commit to something.The message of this game is more or less if you are facing something unexpected, a sacrifice like this, you have to find the most precise move. No matter how much time you spend. You need to find it. If you just play any move, like my opponent taking on c5 in the game, you might end up in a losing position without any prospects. And if you don't find the c4 and e4-idea,  which I think is beautiful and gives White a big advantage, then at least play something like @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3pbp/1p1p2p1/2pnp3/1P6/P1PBB2P/3NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nc4  .  My opponent lost this game because he was shocked and didn't really get deeper into the position to understand that this was a very critical moment. }
28. Ng1 e4 29. Rxd2 Qxd2+ 30. Nce2 Rd3 31. Rb1 Be3 32. a4 Qc2 33. Re1 Rxc3 34.
h4 Rd3 35. Kg2 c4 36. Nh3 Bd2 37. Ra1 Be3 38. g4 f4 *


