[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) FM to Strong IM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Reynaldo Vera Gonzalez Quevedo, Ãbeda 1998"]
[Result "*"]

{ I played this game against GM Reynaldo Vera at the Ãbeda Open in 1998. At the time I was an IM rated 2455 who was exploring new openings with White. In this game, I was trying to play a RÃ©ti when my opponent surprised me. It was quite a lesson for me, so let's take a look at the game. }
1. g3 d5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ I had never seen this opening prior to this game and I wondered why a respected grandmaster is doing something so strange. }
3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 Nb4
{ This is a very direct line, and it is a line that I liked so much that I started playing it myself with an extra tempo. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  g6  3.Nc3  and after  3...d5  4.Bf4  ,  it is more or less the same variation, but with one extra tempo for White.I have won a very current game against Maxime Vachier-Lagrave with this line in the Chess World Cup @@StartBracket@@Tbilisi, 2017@@EndBracket@@ that I won. So even some traumatic experiences can be educational. You can start playing the openings that your opponents played against you. }
5. Na3 { A forced move. } 5... e6
{ Back then, I didn't really understand this idea. I remember that while I was playing the game I was wondering what the point of this is. If I play something like  6.c3  ,  I thought that Black has wasted so much time. He might play something like  6...Nc6  7.Nc2  ,  but what will then happen? And then I started understanding. His point is to play  7...h6  and then bring the knight to f6, keeping control over e4. It's a strange concept.   Generally, we're taught that bringing the knight to c6 is not great, as it is blocking the c7-pawn. But unless the white knight stands on c3, we can't really take advantage of that.Let's take a look at this kind of setup. @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp1pppp/2n5/3p1b2/3P4/5NP1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@Had Black just played something more regular like  4...e6  5.O-O  and let's say something like  5...h6  not really caring about anything  6.c4  Nf6  7.Nc3  Be7  8.cxd5  exd5  ,  then the main problem would be that White has  9.Qb3  when it's not easy to defend the b7-pawn.  9...Rb8  and  10.Bf4  will come.  10...O-O  11.Rfd1  when Ne5 will soon be played and it looks like a terrible position for Black.When people or coaches are telling us not to bring out our knight to c6 because it will be problematic, this is the particular position they have in mind. The point of my opponent, as this setup has been used quite a lot, is that Black doesn't mind putting the knight on c6. Black just doesn't want White to have this quick c4 and Nc3 idea. }
6. O-O { This is what I played in the game, which is a normal move. } 6... Be7
7. Ne5
{ I tried to stop my opponent with  7.Ne5  ,  which I think is a decent move. If Black plays something like  7...f6  I can bring my knight back when the e7-bishop is preventing the knight from developing. So it's not that I have lost a lot of tempi. I have maybe lost half a tempi, and at the same time, it is quite annoying for Black once I start playing c3 and c4 because the f6-pawn is quite a weakness. The whole a2-g8 diagonal is becoming weakened.   @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/1n1P4/N4NP1/PPP1PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@I have to mention that, as I understood it, Black played  6...Be7  because he didn't like  6...Nf6  7.Nh4  .  Black wanted to develop first, because after something like  7...Be4  8.f3  Bg6  9.c3  Nc6  10.Qb3  Rb8  11.e4  ,  White has a lot of quick play, and if Black takes  11...dxe4  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.fxe4  White gets the center. That is the purpose of ...Be7, which is not the way we normally develop.   So here I played  7.Ne5  ,  which is a normal move.  7.c3  would also be an alternative, when after  7...Nc6  there is a move like  8.Ne5  ,  which is very positional. The point of it is that if Black takes on e5  8...Nxe5  9.dxe5  ,  we can see that  9...Bxa3  is not too good because of  10.Qa4+  c6  11.Qxa3  when White places the queen on this nice a3-f8 diagonal.   @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3pPb2/8/N1P3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@And if Black play something like  9...c6  trying to take, what do you think is the best move for White here? Correct!  10.e4  is a positional sacrifice. If Black takes either way @@StartBracket@@with the bishop or the d-pawn@@EndBracket@@  10...dxe4  ,  then the knight will be placed excellently on c4,  11.Nc4  when the d6-square is a bit weak, which I will use to my advantage because once I play Qd3 and Rd1, it's not easy for Black to develop.  After  11...Qd5  ,  I can play 12. Qe2 or  12.Qb3  .  In order for Black to develop, he will have to commit with something like  12...b5  when the problems will appear.  13.Ne3  White can sacrifice some material but creates lots of play.  13.Na5  might even be a better option. I have c4 and a4 coming, and it's not an easy position for Black.   @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/ppp1bppp/2n1p3/3p1b2/3P4/N1P2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@ In other words,  8.Ne5  was an interesting option. I think that I have played a couple of blitz games with it against my friends in anticipation of this line to appear.  8...Bxa3  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.bxa3  .  These positions are generally okay for Black,  10...Nf6  but maybe here I keep a slight press because I am in time to play  11.Bf4  O-O  12.c4  and I can bring the queen to a4. It's a tiny bit better for White, mainly because it seems that the a2 and a3-pawns are weaker than the c6 and c7-pawns, the c7-pawn is vulnerable and the bishop on f4 continues to look at it. It's slightly better for White here.   Therefore, I went  7.Ne5  thinking that I should stop him from bringing the bishop and knight to c6. }
7... Nf6 8. c3 Na6
{ Here I felt that this is good for me and that I should just develop and things will work out. This is normally a dangerous thing to do because if you don't have a clear plan and just put your pieces on central squares the results aren't necessarily good.In this position, I want you to consider what you think White should play here. There are many interesting options for White here, one of them being a surprising sacrifice.  9.Nac4  O-O   9...dxc4  10.Bxb7  and Black cannot take because he will lose the a6-knight.  So Black had to castle.  10.Ne3  Be4  11.f3  Bg6  And this is an interesting position. You can't really play such a line with White without a continuation. If you just put the knight on e3 and play some random moves like Kh1, then ...c5 will come and White is worse.The idea of this whole strange setup is that White can play  12.Qb3  Rb8  13.N3g4  ,  which is an interesting idea that I only recently found. I didn't really know that this idea existed in this position. The point is that White wants to develop the bishop from c1 to f4. If Black takes, then White takes back with the f-pawn and tries to play h4 and h5, which is a very interesting position.I have analyzed the position for a bit and can say that White keeps the initiative. It seems to be because it takes a long time for the a6-knight to come into play. Now, this is one option.   Another interesting and surprising option here is  9.f3  and if you're not paying attention and play something like  9...O-O  ,  then this is trouble.  10.g4  Bg6  11.h4  ,  I'm threatening to trap the bishop. After  11...h6  12.Nxg6  fxg6  ,  this type of structure is rather dreadful for Black.  13.Qd3  ,  it's impossible to properly defend the g6-pawn. If the king goes to h7 then h5 is coming. Black has to defend with  13...Qe8  when it's really passive for Black. White can play g5, f4.  14.g5  hxg5  15.hxg5  is one possibility.  15...Nh5  and something like  16.f4  to trap the knight on h5. There are many options for White. I can also retreat with my knight if I want to, or even play b4 just to stop c5. A difficult position for Black.   9.f3  Basically forces Black to play  9...h6  10.e4  Bh7  12.exd5  exd5  is possible for Black when White is keeping an advantage. I can always play f4 and f5, or f4 and g4. It's a difficult concept. It's symmetrical, but White has the upper hand because of the unfortunate position of the a6-knight, which takes a long time to bring into play.   If Black takes with  12...Nxd5  I can go for  13.f4  ,  which is what I had analyzed back then. If Black plays  13...O-O  then White has the surprising  14.f5  Bxf5  .   If Black instead plays  14...Bxa3  15.Bxd5  Qxd5  16.f6  with a crushing attack. These are some difficult concepts, but in order to refute such a solid line we need to play something like this.  15.Qb3  is a tactical idea, where White is attacking both the knight on d5 and the pawn on d7. After this, the position is very good for White because once the b7-pawn is gone everything is very vulnerable here. The knight on a6, the rook on a8. It isn't easy to protect everything. It isn't every day that you see White voluntarily playing f3. }
9. Qa4+
{ This is what I went for in the game. My logic was that he wants to castle and that ...c6 will actually benefit me because I have an Nxc6 tactic after he castles.  9...c6  10.--  O-O  11.Nxc6  .  Therefore, I will give him a check instead of just developing, and Black will have trouble developing.   I should have probably opted for something like  9.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@  9.f3  is difficult to find unless you have analyzed the line@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp1bppp/n3pn2/3pNb2/3P4/NQP3P1/PP2PPBP/R1B2RK1 b kq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Rb8  and then probably play something like  10.Bf4  ,  trying to go for Rc1 and c4 ideas. It's about equal in this position. }
9... c6 10. Bf4 Qb6 { So here I started thinking, okay, what is happening. }
11. b4
{ Not a good move. I think that this was the last moment where I could equalize the game, or make the game unbalanced.  But in order to do that, I had to understand that my pawn is not going anywhere.If you can find the move here it will be very good because it is a difficult concept. A move like   11.Qb3  is not good because Black just castles  11...O-O  and then starts playing for ...c5. This is just slightly worse for White, as my knight on a3 is worse than his knight on a6. I'm not going to be able to play c4 because d4 is always going to be weak.   The move that I had in mind is  11.Nac4  .  I saw it during the game, but I thought to see a refutation and I didn't play it.  11...dxc4  12.Nxc6  .  It doesn't seem easy for Black to find a move here, and it's basically the only move for Black. Let's see if you can find it. It is  12...Bc2  ,  Black has to immediately create a counterattack. After  13.b3  cxb3  ,  I didn't really believe in the position, but it turns out that it is actually quite balanced and that White has good compensation after  14.Rac1  for the piece because it's a kind of locked position for Black. Black has to play  14...Kf8   14...Nd7  doesn't really do anything for the position because I can always take with  15.Nxe7  .  The knight really belongs on f6.  15.Nxe7  Kxe7  16.Qa3  Kd7  17.axb3  and now taking on b3 is impossible. Black needs to play  17...Be4  ,  trying to block the bishop.   17...Bxb3  18.Rb1  is a pin.   And after  17...Qxb3  there is  18.Qd6+  ,  which looks completely crushing.  18...Ke8  19.Rxc2   Or even  19.Bc6+  ,  there are too many ideas for White.  18.f3  Bg6  19.e4  .  This position is kind of balanced and interesting. Black has an extra piece, but I have a tremendous center and after playing something like Be3, I can play for c4. It takes a long time for Black to bring the king to the kingside, making this position balanced and interesting.   In the game, I was a bit shy because I was playing against a strong grandmaster, and I thought that after playing  11.b4  ,  I could slowly work things out. }
11... O-O 12. Rac1 Rfc8
{ I understood what is happening. He is going to bring his knight to c7 and play ...a5. So my whole setup, which was looking pretty okay, is actually rather stupid. I mean, what am I supposed to do here? }
13. f3
{ I rejected  13.b5  on the grounds that Black can always play  13...Nb8  14.bxc6  Nxc6  and the only piece that is at least putting some pressure, this knight on e5, is going to be exchanged. Afterwards I'll be stuck with this donkey of an a3-knight. }
13... h6 14. Rfe1 { I mean, what else. } 14... Nc7 15. e4 Bh7
{ The game didn't last too long. } 16. Rb1
{ With the hope to meet  16...a5  with  17.b5  which is also looking pretty good for Black. }
16... Nb5
{ This is of course much stronger. I have a clear weakness on c3 and my center is also wobbly. }
17. Nxb5 cxb5 18. Qb3 Bd6
{ I've tried to put up some resistance. Black is threatening to play ...a5, ...Qc7, and all kinds of things. }
19. Kh1
{ Preventing the threat of ...Bxe5. If I play something like  19.Rbc1  ,  then  19...dxe4  20.fxe4  Bxe5  20.Bxe5  and I have to watch out for threats like  20...Ng4  21.Bf4  e5  when things might just fall apart. }
19... dxe4 20. fxe4 Bxe5 21. Bxe5 Ng4 22. Bf4 e5 23. Bxe5 Nf2+ 24. Kg1 Nd3 25.
Kh1 { At least I was trying to keep some counterplay. But he just took. } 25...
Nxe5 26. dxe5 Re8
{ After he captured on e5, it's clear that Black has clear and easy play. There is not much I could do. Of course, I could put up better resistance, but I was already quite upset. You know, somebody is playing Nc6 against you and you get in a very difficult situation right out of the opening.The lesson of this game is that first of all it would be useful to know these ideas. That Black can actually play like this in order to use it in the future. @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p1b2/1n1P4/N4NP1/PPP1PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@And second of all, if you're going to play some idea like  7.Ne5  Nf6  8.c3  Na6  you better have a follow-up.   @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p1b2/1n1P4/N4NP1/PPP1PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@Because if you're not so sure about this  7.Ne5  business, then I could also just play with  7.c3  Nc6  and something simple like  8.Nc2  .  And this is actually quite popular.  8...Nf6  9.Bg5  O-O  10.Nd2  .  White wants to take on f6 and play e4. It's a slightly better position for White.   @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p1b2/1n1P4/N4NP1/PPP1PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@Once I've played  7.Ne5  ,  I should have known what was going to happen later.   @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp1bppp/n3pn2/3pNb2/3P4/N1P3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@And by playing  9.Qa4+  ,  I already committed my queen's position, so Qb3 doesn't make sense anymore.   @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp2bppp/nqp1pn2/3pNb2/Q2P1B2/N1P3P1/PP2PPBP/R4RK1 w kq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@Once I played  11.b4  ,  there was no way back. I just took many poor decisions without having a clear plan of what I'm doing. Had I thought for some time of course I would have found both  11.Nac4  with this interesting idea.   @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp1bppp/n3pn2/3pNb2/3P4/N1P3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@Or  9.f3  .  Or even if I hadn't found it I would've just played  9.Qb3  --  and  10.Bf4  .   @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp2bppp/n1p1pn2/3pNb2/Q2P1B2/N1P3P1/PP2PPBP/R4RK1 b kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@These were just some logically looking stupid moves I would say. They look logical, I'm developing my pieces, and then oh I have this Nxc6 trick. But had I looked a little bit deeper and felt wait, what am I doing against  10...Qb6  .  How am I protecting the b2-pawn? I would've understood that my setup makes zero sense. And this is how I learned it.   @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp1pppp/2n5/3p1b2/3P4/5NP1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@By making those mistakes I think I learned not to treat such strange and seemingly illogical openings like  4...Nb4  without proper respect. }
27. a4 bxa4 28. Qxa4 Rxe5 29. c4 Qe6 30. Qc2 Rd8 31. c5 Rd4 32. Rbd1 Bxe4 33.
Bxe4 Rexe4 34. Rxe4 Rxd1+ 35. Kg2 Qd5 36. Qc4 Rd2+ 37. Kf3 Qd7 38. b5 Rxh2 39.
c6 bxc6 40. bxc6 Qd1+ 41. Kf4 Rf2+ 42. Ke5 Rf6 43. Rd4 Qh5+ *


