[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Artashes Minasian, Ãbeda 1999 "]
[Result "*"]

{ The year is 1999, this is the tournament in Ãbeda. I would normally go there every year to play the Ãbeda Open in Linares in the south of Spain, a place that I love a lot. What I would usually do there, I was an IM with not a lot of money so I would play blitz nights with amateurs for 100 pesetas or more and that is why how I could afford food at that time. Of course, it was not a great idea but I didn't have enough financial resources to completely focus on my tournament.  This game was the fifth round of the tournament, I was paired against the legendary GM Artashes Minasian, he was the last champion of the Soviet Union, a solid member of the Armenian national team back then, and the winner of multiple tournaments. I was playing white and I opened with the RÃ©ti: 1.Nf3. }
1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Nd7
{ A rather new move to me back then, but I thought it was only logical that I prevent e5. }
4. d4 { I still think this is the best move here. } 4... e6
{ This came a bit as a surprise for me during the game. } 5. O-O Bd6 6. c4
{ Now I understand that my opponent intends to play a Stonewall. Normally, if Black wants to play the Stonewall, he will do it like that with a knight on d7. If we go back just to show you the example, let's set up a regular Stonewall position: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/ PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.g3  e6  4.Bg2  d5  5.O-O  Be7  6.c4  O-O  7.b3  c6  here, quite often, Black will play with the idea of ...Bd7-e8 and only then bring out the knight. In the endgame, we got a Stonewall with a knight on d7, meaning that Black will have to play with ...b6. }
6... f5 7. b3
{ Now that I think of it and I look at the position since the knight is already committed to d7, it would make much more sense to play with  7.Nc3  Ngf6  8.c5  Bc7  9.b4  because now after ...b6, we have Qa4. But this is a different type of approach of course. }
7... Ngf6 8. Ba3
{ The idea behind b3. Quite often Black will play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1n2pp/2pbp3/3p1p2/2PP4/1P3NP1/P3PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qe7  in these types of structures, but with the knight already committed to d7, after  8.Bb2  Ngf6  9.Ne5  , my opponent understood that he might not be able to come out at all.  9...O-O  10.Nd2  , normally in these structures Black's knight is still on b8 and he manages to play ...b6, ...Bb7. }
8... Bxa3 9. Nxa3 O-O 10. Nc2
{ A normal move, what I'm trying to do is to bring this knight into a better position through either b4-d3 or e1-d3. }
10... Ne4 11. Nce1 dxc4
{ Again, very surprising for me, and it does look kind of strange. } 12. bxc4
c5
{ What my opponent is trying to do while I am bringing my knights into the game, is trying to bring out his bishop from c8. }
13. e3
{ A bit of a tame move, but after all, I was much lower rated than my opponent and I was just trying to play solidly. Today, I would play in a much more active way, Nd3 perhaps. }
13... b6 14. Nd3 Bb7
{ So far we have a pretty solid position. White will most likely get the hanging pawns structure on c4/d4, but Black is saddled with a long-term weakness: the e6-pawn. }
15. Qb3
{ Not the most brilliant move, but a solid one. Intending Qb2, Rac1, Rfd1, and then maybe I'll try to do something against the e4-knight, maybe exchange it or play Nfe5 and push it out with f3. }
15... g5
{ This was one of my first games in this opening and of course, ...g5 came as a huge surprise. I was quite shocked, during the game I was thinking: what is happening to me? But actually, this is a very logical move. Black is trying to play ...g4 and if he manages to exchange the light-squared bishops, he will get a very nice pressure on the a8-h1 diagonal. The reason why it was shocking for me is that now the Black's king position is opened up but in fact, it is not so easy to attack the weakened king.  First of all, I don't have any pieces around the king, and second of all, I think opening up the center is strategically wrong for me because after  16.dxc5  Nexc5  16.Nxc5  Nxc5  , Black gets a powerful knight on c5. }
16. Rad1
{ The reason I picked the a1-rook instead of the f1-rook is to have the f3 option later on. }
16... Qc7 17. Qb2
{ A logical move, preparing Nfe5. I didn't want to commit with Nfe5 immediately now, I just wanted my opponent to make a move before I did so.   But  17.Nfe5  is, of course, a decent move.  17...Nxe5  18.Nxe5  and right now I want to play f3, so he probably has to play  18...g4  19.f3  ,  I can play this anyway.  19...gxf3  20.Bxf3  looks quite logical, and probably White is a tiny bit better. }
17... g4 18. Nh4
{ 18.Nfe5  is also possible, of course, but I already thought that after  18...Nxe5  19.Nxe5  ,  Nh4 is probably the better option. Here he can play  19...Rad8  and with Ng5 coming at some point, I wasn't so sure about the position. }
18... cxd4
{ Here, of course, Black can just play  18...Rae8  and keep the game solid. }
19. exd4 Qxc4 20. Nf4
{ This is what I had in mind. Now, the e6-pawn is weak, and I'm threatening to blow up the position with d5 and Rc1 to follow.  At this moment, I was extremely optimistic. I was thinking, okay, I'm going to crash through, and that ...cxd4 was a big big mistake. }
20... Bd5
{ This move came as a cold shower for me, and on top of that, the a2-pawn is hanging.  The reason why I'm showing this particular game is not that I won against a much higher-rated player than me, but mainly for this exact moment.   This was a display of my maturity at that time, that I had already become a much better player at that moment than I was before, mainly thanks to being able to find such moves. I want you all to think about it and try to find what White should play. }
21. Ra1
{ Why am I so proud of this move? Because it looks super passive! It looks rather like a move a novice would make. But the good thing about this move is it keeps the pressure in the game. It took a lot of confidence from my side to play such an ugly-looking move.  You can't play such a move without a lot of calculations and understanding one crucial factor: this position still has a lot to offer.  Let us go into the lines and understand what I had in mind. Firstly, my main point now is that I want to play Rfc1. If Black plays something like  21...Ndf6  , I can go  22.Rfc1  and after  22...Qa6  23.Rc7  , I have this Bf1 idea followed by bringing the other rook to c1. Other than that, of course, I'm keeping my knight on f4 and I'm not allowing him to activate his pieces soon.  My opponent was very nervous because usually, you don't expect a very calm move from a weaker opponent instead of panicking already after ...Bd5.   21.Nxd5  ,  I don't think this is very good. Black can just take back  21...Qxd5  and then blockade with ...Ndf6, the knight on h4 is a little bit awkward for me.   21.Rc1  is not doing anything great for me either.  21...Qxa2  22.Qb5  Ndf6  . }
21... Rac8
{ Not the best reply because now I can activate all of my pieces.   Instead, he should have tried something like  21...Qc3  22.Qe2  and then once again, maybe  22...Qc4  ,  trying to force a draw somehow. }
22. Rfc1 Qa6
{ And here I have an excellent idea which I managed to find during the game. }
23. Bxe4 fxe4
{ Taking with the bishop of course allows  23...Bxe4  24.Nxe6  . } 24. Nxd5
exd5 25. Qd2
{ Now the queen on a6 is very passive while my queen is invading through the g5-square. }
25... Nf6 26. Qg5+ Kh8 27. Qh6
{ In this position, I had many many tempting moves. I can play  27.Nf5  and it is unclear how he can defend against the Qg7+. Nevertheless, to tell you the truth, I was a bit nervous. The game is almost finished and I got too emotional. }
27... Rf7 28. Ng6+ Kg8 29. Ne5 Rff8 30. Qg5+ Kh8 31. Qh4
{ Here, we were already both in time trouble, so we repeated the moves. But both of us blundered the only way for Black to create counterplay.  31...Rxc1+  32.Rxc1  e3!  which is of course a difficult move to see.  33.Ng6+  is not a serious threat because after  33...Kg8  34.Nxf8  exf2+  35.Kxf2+  Qxa2+  36.Kg1  , Black manages to make a draw by activating his queen  36...Qd2! }
31... Kg8 32. Qg5+ Kh8 33. Rxc8 Qxc8 34. Rc1
{ I am dominating the position, of course, but this is a great chance to show you how resilient good players are in tough positions. }
34... Qb7 35. Rc6 Qg7 36. Qf5 e3 37. fxe3 Qh6 38. Qf4
{ Here I can win on the spot with  38.Rc8!  but I didn't see during the game that after  38...Qxe3+  39.Kf1  ,  there are no checks anymore! My nervousness got the better of me.  39...Rxc8  40.Qxf6+  is completely crushing for White. }
38... Qg7 39. Rc7 Qxc7 40. Ng6+ hxg6 41. Qxc7
{ This is move 41, I have an extra queen. It seems like I'm just taking all of the pawns as well. }
41... b5 42. Qxa7 Rc8 43. Qf7 Ne4 44. Qxg6
{ Here I started thinking. What happens after  44.Qxd5?  He will give a check  44...Rc1+  ,  and then it is a draw!  45.Kg2  Rc2+  46.Kf1  Rc1+  .  Oops!  47.Ke2  Nc3+  ,  oops again. }
44... Rc1+ 45. Kg2 Rc2+ 46. Kf1 Rc1+
{ If he takes on a2, then I get to take on g4 with a check, and the king can hide on h3. }
47. Ke2 Rc2+ 48. Kd1 Rxh2 49. Kc1
{ Here I thought, OK, I play Kc1, and then he has to resign. } 49... b4
{ Again, very resourceful. The thing is, the rook on h2 is protected against all forks and attacks by my pawn on g3. }
50. Qe8+ Kg7 51. Qd7+ Kf6 52. Qc6+ Kg7 53. Qxd5 Nc3
{ Can you guys tell me what Black's threat is in this position if White just moves the queen away?   The drawing mechanism begins with ...Re2! and if Black can safely follow it up with ...Nxa2+ and ...Nc3+, White is forced to settle for a draw! I still have to play precisely to stop that. }
54. Qb7+ Kf6 55. Qc6+ Kg5 56. a3 { Keeping the pressure on the c3-knight. }
56... Na2+ 57. Kd1 Nc3+ 58. Ke1 bxa3 { Again very resourceful. } 59. Qc5+
{ 59.Qxc3  and I can't stop the pawn from promoting, I can only give a perpetual check. }
59... Kg6 60. Qxa3 Re2+ 61. Kf1 Rxe3
{ Of course, if Black gets one more move to set up the rook on f3, it becomes tough to win the resulting position. But here I have this very nice trick }
62. Qd6+ Kh5 63. Qc7 { Black will not be able to stabilize. } 63... Ne4
{ My opponent blundered with ...Ne4. Can you tell me how I can win on the spot? }
64. Qf7+
{ And my opponent resigned because I have Qf4+. The position anyway is completely lost for Black. This was my win against a solid player; the main reason for this victory, in my opinion, was the fact that I got myself together, didn't panic, and played this @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/p2n3p/1p2p3/3b1p2/2qPnNpN/6P1/PQ3PBP/3R1RK1 w - - 2 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Ra1  move, which was a display of my confidence, a sign that my level was visibly improving. }
*


