[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) FM to Strong IM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Irisberto Herrera, Ãbeda 1999"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a game I played in 1999, against IM Herrera in round 9 of the same Ãbeda Open. }
1. Nf3
{ The reason why I was playing this RÃ©ti is that I analyzed with my coach Arshak Petrosian. He told me that I'm playing these e4 openings without knowing any theory, so I'm better off learning a new opening from scratch and that's what he showed me: the RÃ©ti. I kept playing it from 1999 until maybe 2000 and it was very beneficial for me to learn all about these new English and d4 structures. }
1... Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5
{ A GrÃ¼nfeld setup for Black. } 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 Nb6
{ A bit of a passive approach. I think modern theory recommends  7...c5  .  Black is putting a pawn in the center. Back in the day, people thought that anyway White is going to play d4 and transpose to this well-known variation of the g3 GrÃ¼nfeld. }
8. d3 Nc6 9. Be3
{ What I'm trying to get is a kind of English, but because the bishop is on g7, I would say it is more beneficial for White. If Black plays ...e5, I can try and put a knight on c5 easier than a typical English structure: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.Bg2  Nb6  6.d3  Be7  7.Nf3  O-O  8.O-O  Nc6  9.Be3  . Look at this position and compare it with the game position @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/1nn3p1/8/8/2NPBNP1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 9@@EndFEN@@ @@StartBracket@@where we basically can now play Ne4 with ideas like Nc5 and Bg5@@EndBracket@@. In the typical English structure with a bishop on e7 instead of g7, after for example  9...Re8  10.Ne4  Bf8  11.Nc5  is met with  11...Nd4  . }
9... Nb4
{ Not a great move.  9...e5  is still totally fine for Black.  10.Ne4  and maybe now play with  10...h6  , to stop Bg5 ideas,  11.Qc1  Kh7  and just ignore the knight on c5.  12.Nc5  a5  or  12...Nd4  .   Why is ...Nb4 inaccurate? If we look at the position, we can see that Black did not develop the c8-bishop yet, and he doesn't have any pawns in the center so he has to do something about it.  9...a5  also makes a lot of sense. I'm not too fond of  9...Be6  because White will always have Qc1, Rd1, and it is not clear what Black is doing. }
10. Qc1 Re8 { Trying to keep the bishop in the game. } 11. Bh6 Bh8 12. d4 N4d5
{ Black can never take because of the pin  12...Bxd4  13.Rd1  . } 13. Ne4 Nf6
14. Nc5 Nbd7 15. Nd3 c6
{ Here, my position is much better. Black didn't accomplish anything and I can just slowly play for e4. }
16. Qf4 Nh5 17. Qh4 Bf6 18. Qe4 Bg7 19. Bxg7 Nxg7
{ This particular moment is why I'm showing this game. Here, I played a move that showed my understanding has improved. What do we have in this position? We have White with a great center. Black doesn't have any active plans in sight. So now I have to come up with a plan. The only piece that I don't like in my position is the queen on e4. }
20. Qf4 Ne6 21. Qc1
{ The queen completed its task and comes back where it belongs. Surprisingly enough, White's position improved drastically: e3, Rd1 followed by b4, and domination on the queenside. Note that because the g7-bishop was exchanged, Black has no real counterplay, his central pressure is very little and the c8-bishop is out of play, with terrible squares for his knights.  Actually, I want to show you that I've used this exact same idea before, which goes to show how ideas in chess are interconnected. Here is one example where White plays a completely different opening: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  Be7  5.Nf3  O-O  6.O-O  dxc4  7.Qc2  a6  8.a4  Bd7  9.Qxc4  Bc6  10.Bf4  Bd6  11.Qc1  Bxf4  12.Qxf4  Nbd7  . Quite often, the best idea for White is to play  13.Qc1  , which avoids any sudden attacks on the queen. White then plays Nbd2, Rd1, e3 keeping the pressure on c5.  Compare it now to what I got in the game and you can see that the ideas are pretty much interrelated. What I try to do in that other position is the same thing that I'm doing here. Ding Liren, actually, a great player from China, has done this maneuver in the Catalan quite a few times. When I found this idea in 1999 I was very proud because I had not seen it in other games and realized it was a great idea. }
21... Nf6
{ We can quickly see how Black's position will deteriorate quickly because he has no plans and no future for his pieces.   21...Qb6  ,  trying to play for c5 aggressively doesn't work. Following  22.e3  c5  ,  there is always this  23.d5  Nc7  24.Nd2  and Black didn't achieve anything, the c5-pawn is a liability. This is the kind of position that the computer assesses by +1, which means that White has an advantage that equals having an extra pawn. A position where your opponent has zero counterplay is much much better than having a position with an extra pawn for a lot of counterplay. }
22. e3 a5 { Stopping b4 for now. } 23. Rd1 Qb6 24. Nfe5 Rd8 25. Qc3 Ng7 26. Qb3
Qxb3 27. axb3
{ Black can't move the c8-bishop because of Nc5 and, at the same time, I'm threatening to play b4. }
27... Nf5 28. Nc4 Nd6 29. Nxa5
{ The game didn't last much longer, I just got a knight to c5 and the position collapsed. It all happened because I found a way just to create harmony in the position by maybe losing some time but establishing full control of the position. This is one of the patterns @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pp1npp1p/2p1n1p1/8/3P1Q2/3N1NP1/PP2PPBP/R4RK1 w - - 2 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Qc1  , which you can actually use in your game. Whenever you have a queen in the center, sometimes it is very useful to just bring it out of danger before bringing the pawns forward. }
29... Bf5 30. Nc5 b6 31. Nxc6 Rxa1 32. Rxa1 Re8 33. Na4 b5 34. Nc5 Nfe4 35. g4
Nxc5 36. dxc5 *


