[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/ppp1ppbp/1n4pB/8/1n6/2NP1NP1/PP2PPBP/R1Q2RK1 b - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11... Bh8 { How can I improve my position? } 12. d4
{ Just taking more space in the center. Black can never take because of the pin. }
12... Bxd4 { This is a mistake. } 13. Rd1 { White wins the bishop. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) FM to Strong IM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Irisberto Herrera â Puzzle #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/pp1nppBp/2p3p1/7n/3PQ3/3N1NP1/PP2PPBP/R4RK1 b - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

19... Nxg7
{ This particular moment is why I'm showing this game. Here, I played a move that showed my understanding has improved. What do we have in this position? We have White with a great center. Black doesn't have any active plans in sight. So now I have to come up with a plan. The only piece that I don't like in my position is the queen on e4. }
20. Qf4
{ Bringing back the queen to the queenside where we want to create our play. }
20... Ne6 21. Qc1
{ The queen completed its task and comes back where it belongs. Surprisingly enough, White's position improved drastically: e3-Rd1 followed by b4 and domination on the queenside.   Note that because the g7-bishop was exchanged, Black has no real counterplay, his central pressure is very little and the c8-bishop is out of play, with terrible squares for his knights. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) FM to Strong IM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Irisberto Herrera â Puzzle #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/pp1npp1p/2p1n1p1/8/3P4/3N1NP1/PP2PPBP/R1Q2RK1 b - - 0 21"]
[SetUp "1"]

21... Qb6
{ Trying to play for ...c5 aggressively doesn't work. How should White react? }
22. e3 { Protecting the d4-pawn. } 22... c5
{ Whenever Black plays this, we have a standard reaction. } 23. d5 Nc7 24. Nd2
{ Black didn't achieve anything, the c5-pawn is a liability. This is the kind of position that the computer assesses by +1, which means that White has an advantage that equals having an extra pawn.   A position where your opponent has zero counterplay is much much better than having a position with an extra pawn for a lot of counterplay. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) FM to Strong IM"]
[Black "Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now we are going to move to the time when I had already become a Grandmaster and a solid player. The chapter where I went from a talented FM to a strong IM is now finished.  What I've learned throughout this time is to think, respect my opponent, analyze my mistakes, and find beauty in some moves that are maybe not very exciting but necessary @@StartBracket@@rather than looking for tricks@@EndBracket@@.  All of this turned me into a Grandmaster with a lot of promise instead of being an FM or an IM, who is always looking for some tricks or exciting moves. }
1. -- *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Eduardas Rozentalis, Las Vegas 1999"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a game from the first World Cup I played, where I didn't manage to qualify for the Candidates. However, the former president of the European Chess Union, Boris Kutin, asked FIDE to provide a spot for me since I won the European Championship U20, which allowed me to eventually play. At that time, the Lithuanian GM was in his prime â a very solid and good player. }
1. Nf3
{ The RÃ©ti Opening, which was my favorite back then. I must admit that I was very nervous and I prepared a lot for this match together with my coach, Arshak Petrosian. It was the first time I could see the stars in action and also visit the United States, which made the whole experience a very interesting one for me. }
1... d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Nd7
{ A very typical way to play. Black plans to support ...e5, just as RÃ©ti's opponents used to face him back in the day. }
5. d3 { In those times, many Armenian players used this line a lot. } 5... Ngf6
6. Nbd2
{ 6.Qe1  was very common to play back in the day, in order to meet  6...e5  with  7.e4  Bd6  8.exd5  cxd5  9.Nxe5  . Now the purpose of Qe1 is clear: creating the pin on the e-file. White will have a nice pawn structure since Black's pawn on d5 is weak as well. }
6... e5 7. e4 dxe4
{ My game plan was to meet  7...Bd6  with  8.exd5  cxd5  9.c4  , which was a very popular idea. It might look a bit odd, as optically speaking, it feels as if White is creating weaknesses. However, after  9...O-O  10.cxd5  Nxd5  11.Nc4  Bc7  12.h3  Bh5  13.Re1  , White has a lot of activity. }
8. dxe4 Bc5 9. h3 Bxf3
{ A surprising, rare, and a bit passive decision. In most games, Black tries to preserve the bishop with  9...Bh5  @@StartBracket@@after  9...Be6  , White has  10.Ng5  , grabbing the bishop pair@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1n1ppp/2p2n2/2b1p2b/4P3/5NPP/PPPN1PB1/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qe1  I've played numerous games like this with White.  10...O-O  11.Nc4  Qc7  12.Nh4  .  The idea was to meet  12...Rad8  with  13.Bg5  , pinning Black's pieces.  13...h6  14.Bd2  .  Now ...Bg6 is not really working anymore and White is also threatening g4 sometimes. }
10. Bxf3
{ A@@EndBracket@@ I was surprised by Rozentalis' choice but taking  10.Nxf3  looks strange since the knight belongs to c4.  10...O-O  when  trying to bring the knight to f5 is not very dangerous.  11.Nh4  g6  and Black is perfectly fine.   B@@EndBracket@@ I was considering both  10.Qxf3  and the text move, but finally went for the less precise continuation. Better would have been to play  10.Qxf3  since anyway later on I will continue with h4 and Bh3, with a nice position. In other words, 9...Bxf3 is not recommended. }
10... O-O 11. a4
{ Preparing to place the knight on c4. The immediate  11.Nc4  requires some calculation.  11...b5  12.Ne3  g6  . Black is claiming that the bishop on c1 is passive and when it will get out, the strategy will be to exchange it, leaving White with a not-so-strong bishop on f3. }
11... a5 12. Nc4 Qe7 { En route to e6. } 13. Kg2 Rfd8 14. Qe2
{ White has a nice position with the bishop pair, but the future plan is a bit unclear. The bishop on f3 has to be rerouted, as it would be happier on b3 or h3. }
14... Nf8 15. c3
{ The position is a tad better for White, but nothing serious. } 15... h6
{ Black wants to continue with ...Qc7 and ...Ne6, and the immediate  15...Qc7  would have run into  16.Bg5  , threatening Bxf6 and followed by Bf3-g4-f5.   15...Ne8  is another idea, to go for ...Nd6 and exchange the knight on c4. }
16. h4 Qc7 17. Ne3
{ Since Black committed to ...h6, the knight has now a beautiful spot on f5. }
17... Qb6 18. Nc4
{ I wasn't very sure if after  18.Nf5  Ne6  19.Qc4  Qa6  , White has anything serious.  20.Qxa6  Rxa6  ,  with the queens off, it was not clear to me how will the c1-bishop come into the game. I don't really want to exchange the bishops  with  21.Be3  since that will yield Black a square  for the e6-knight. Therefore, I decided to repeat the moves once. }
18... Qc7 19. Ne3 Qb6 20. Qc4 Ne6
{ Black is preparing ...Qa6, and I believe my next move is a strong reaction. What would you play with White here?   20...Bxe3  is too greedy.  21.Bxe3  Qxb2  22.Rfb1  followed by Rxb7, emphasizes that the pawn grab was an error. }
21. Ng4
{ In an ideal world, Black plans to fortify the position with ...g6 and ...h5 when the knight on f6 becomes stronger.   21.Be2  is another possibility, preparing for a later Nf5. }
21... Nxg4
{ Just for illustrative purposes, after  21...Nd7  ,  White's plan consists of h5, b3, Ra2, Rd2, Rfd1, when the knight on d7 is tied to the defense of the pawn on e5. }
22. Bxg4 Rd6 23. b3 { Making space for the rook on a1. } 23... Rad8
{ Here I played a good move from a practical point of view, which I would like you to find. }
24. f4
{ A very surprising decision, exposing the 2nd rank, which provoked a visible reaction in my opponent's body language. What do you think was the best option for Black? }
24... exf4
{ The beginning of the end.   A@@EndBracket@@  24...Re8  is possible, but not a very human way to play.  25.fxe5  Rd7  with the idea of ...Rde7 and slowly recapture on e5.   B@@EndBracket@@ The best move in the position was  24...Rd2+  25.Bxd2  Rxd2+  26.Kh1  and this is the moment Black had to see from afar, which I hope you will discover without any help!  26...Bg1!  Threatening to deliver mate in one.  27.Be2  is now the only move.   27.Rxg1  Qf2  White is either getting mated or losing half of the kingdom.  27...Bf2  when Black has many threats, including ...Qe3, and White should act fast.  28.Rad1  ,  Black must find a way to hold the game.  28...Qe3   28...Rxd1  is not so easy and after  29.Rxd1  exf4  30.Bg4  Qe3  31.Qd3  , the rook will create havoc once it will reach the seventh rank.  29.Rxd2  Qxg3  30.Rxf2  Qxf2  .  Surprisingly, there isn't much White can do.  31.f5  is the best winning attempt.  31...Qxh4+   31...Nf4  loses on the spot due to  32.Qxf7+  Kh7  33.Qg8+  Kxg8  34.Bc4+  and the queen will leave the scene.  32.Kg1  Nf4  .  White is a rook up, but since the queen is out of play on c4, Black had enough counterplay to make a draw.   32...Ng5  is also good enough for a draw. We know that queen+knight is a strong combo and this is one more example to prove the theory. White is a rook up, but Black has a powerful duo, which easily secures the draw.  33.Bf1  Qg3+  34.Kh1  Qe1  35.Rh2  h5  .  White cannot improve the position any further, which has come to a deadlock. }
25. Bxf4 Nxf4+ 26. Rxf4
{ My opponent thought he will get enough counterplay in this position. } 26...
Rd2+ 27. Kh3 { The king is safe on h3. } 27... Bd6
{ If Black tries to disturb White's king by playing  27...Bg1  , then after  28.Qxf7+  Kh8  29.Bf5  , White has enough light squares available for the king to step on and the attack is also faster than Black's.  29...Rh2+  30.Kg4  Qe3  31.Qg6  Qe2+  32.Rf3  .  Black ran out of checks and the king on h8 is in the woods. White is winning from here on in many different ways, for instance,  23...Kg8  can be answered by  24.Re1  . }
28. Rxf7 Kh8 29. e5
{ 29.Raf1  is also winning.  29...Qe3  30.R7f3  Qe2  31.Rf8+  and the queen drops. }
29... Bxe5 30. Raf1 Bd6
{ The problem with  30...R2d5  is that after  31.Rf8+  Rxf8  32.Rxf8+  Kh7  33.Qe4+  , White will deliver mate.  33...g6  34.Bh5  Kg7  35.Qxg6+  Kxf8  36.Qf7  . }
31. Rxg7 Qe3 { This is the moment when I got a bit nervous. } 32. Bh5
{ 32.Rh7+  was the easiest way.  32...Kxh7  33.Qf7+  Kh8  34.Qf6+  Kg8  35.Qxd8+  with a winning position for White. }
32... Rf2
{ 32...Kxg7  doesn't require any calculation.  33.Qf7+  Kh8  34.Qf6+  Kh7  35.Bg6+  followed by mate in two. }
33. Rxf2 Qxf2 34. Rg6 Qf5+ 35. Kg2 Qxh5
{ Returning the favor, as this piece grab is a blunder.   After  35...Qc2+  36.Qe2  Qxe2+  37.Bxe2  Bf8  ,  the position is difficult for Black, but there are practical chances to survive.  38.Bc4  Bg7  39.Re6  .  A difficult defensive task ahead for Black, yet surely not an impossible one. }
36. Qd4+ Qe5 37. Rxd6 Qxd4 38. Rxd4 Re8 39. Rd6
{ From afar, it may look as if Black is getting active, but in fact, cannot avoid the loss of a second pawn. The position is resignable and that's what happened in the game too.   A sample line is  39...Kg7  @@StartBracket@@After  39...Re3  White is winning the second pawn by force.  40.Rxh6+  Kg8  41.Rd6  Rxc3  42.Rd8+  Kf7  43.Rd7+  followed by Rxb7,  with an easy win.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@4r3/1p4k1/2pR3p/p7/P6P/1PP3P1/6K1/8 w - - 3 40@@EndFEN@@  40.Rd7+  Kg6  41.Rxb7  Re3  42.c4  . Two extra pawns should be enough for a win, besides Black is having the a- and c-pawns weak as well.   A heavy blow for my opponent who was 70 points higher rated than me at the time, and he tried to defeat me in the second game by playing some offbeat 1.d4 @@StartBracket@@since he was a 1.e4 player@@EndBracket@@. After getting a slightly better position, my opponent offered a draw, which, as a 17 y.o. I declined and won the match 2-0. Everyone was impressed by my uncompromising attitude of turning down a draw offer, which would essentially mean winning the match and passing to the next round immediately.  I faced Jan Timman after Rozentalis, who was also playing very well in that period @@StartBracket@@150 points higher rated than me@@EndBracket@@, and I didn't manage to put up much resistance. At least, being an underdog and winning such a game with the unusual @@StartFEN@@@@EndBracket@@@@EndFEN@@  24.f4  idea, opening up the position and exposing the king, but understanding that White's attack is faster, is something to be proud of. I can conclude that the RÃ©ti Opening served me well over the years. :@@EndBracket@@ }
*


