[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Kidambi Sundararajan vs. Levon Aronian, Yerevan 1999"]
[Result "*"]

{ I would like to show you a game that I played in the World Championship U20, Yerevan  (which happens to be my hometown)  , against the Indian  (IM at the time, now an established GM)  Kidambi Sundararajan. This was the second round and I was very motivated to win, a spirit which can be easily seen by my off-the-beaten-path opening choice.  I should give a little bit more intel though: at the age of 15, I stopped playing junior events, except for the U20 World and European Championships, because my trainer, Arshak Petrosian  (my second coach after Melikset Khachiyan)  , believed that I needed strong opposition in order to improve my play. Playing the U16 and U18 events doesn't add much value, as most of the time in those tournaments, the victory is decided by who blunders last. From 1999 to 2002 I played very tough tournaments, which proved to be educational for me. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 Qc7
{ A line that Arshak Petrosian taught me as well, which is a bit passive but, nonetheless, I employed it many times.  5...O-O  is more popular and, objectively, a stronger move too. }
6. Nf3 Bxc5
{ The point of this variation is for Black to reach a Hedgehog type of position, despite being a couple of tempi down. Back then, this was a dangerous approach, but not as risky as nowadays when computers crush Black most of the time. }
7. Bg5
{ One of the most testing variations at that time was  7.g3  a6  8.Bf4  with the idea to meet  8...Qb6  with  9.O-O-O  . }
7... a6 8. e3 Be7
{ I played many games in this line, just trying to set up the Hedgehog structure. }
9. Bd3 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. a3
{ White's moves are natural, planning to plant a pawn on b4 next, which is typical for this pawn structure. In general, my opponent is a very solid player, making him very difficult to defeat, and I was happy to get this unbalanced position on the board, where he could potentially go wrong. }
11... b6 12. b4 Bb7 13. e4 Rc8
{ I could have also started by castling first, but I wasn't sure if I wanted to insert ...h6 or not. }
14. Rac1 O-O
{ 14...h6  is a natural move, with the idea of following that up with ...Ng4 and occupying the e5-square. If White retreats  15.Bd2  ,  we reach the position I meant, when I wasn't sure whether I wanted to have the pawn on h6 or not.  And if  15.Bh4  , then  15...g5  is typical.  16.Bg3  Nh5  Once Black gets rid of the bishop, ...Bf6 followed by ...Ke7 is a good and solid plan. }
15. Rfe1 Rfe8
{ The Hedgehog players know that those positions involve a lot of maneuvering and shuffling the pieces around, while the structure remains intact. That is the story of this game as well. }
16. Qe2 Qb8 17. Bb1 Nf8 18. Be3 Ba8
{ Preparing to play ...b5 at the right moment, while White tries to slowly push Black without committing to, for instance, a4, as that could be well met by ...d5. }
19. Nd2 { Now ...d5 doesn't look too good, as the a6-pawn is hanging too. }
19... Ng6 { Maybe I will be able to throw in ...d5 at some point. } 20. f4 Bd8
{ The typical setup: Black is trying to push ...b5, sometimes ...e5, or perhaps ...h5 followed by ...Ng4. Meanwhile, White tries to keep control over the position and play a4 when the time is right, with the idea of continuing with b5 or c5, depending on the circumstances. This is a very rich and interesting opening for sure. }
21. h3
{ A slight inaccuracy since I wasn't threatening any ...Ng4.  21.Rf1  could have been played instead. The idea is to follow it up with, perhaps, Nf3 and Bd2, rerouting the pieces a little bit.  It is a tough battle: Black has set up the position wonderfully, but there is no real threat. Black is prepared like a tiger for what will White throw in, but if the opponent doesn't risk anything, the Hedgehog's needles will have to be sparred for a better moment. }
21... Nd7 22. Rf1 Bf6
{ Suddenly, I am threatening to play ...b5. Also, the pawn on h3 creates new ideas: ...e5 followed by ...Nf4. }
23. Qd3 { White tries to stabilize. } 23... e5 24. g3
{ White's position starts to deteriorate.   A@@EndBracket@@  24.f5  is also not that great.  24...Nf4  25.Qc2  @@StartBracket@@After  25.Bxf4  exf4  , the bishop on b1 is completely out of play and  26.Rxf4  runs into  26...d5  . This is not a good position for White.@@EndBracket@@ Now, Black can even play @@StartFEN@@bqr1r1k1/3n1ppp/pp1p1b2/4pP2/1PP1Pn2/P1N1B2P/2QN2P1/1BR2RK1 b - - 2 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Bg5  , planning to continue with ...b5 when White's pieces are not placed harmoniously.   B@@EndBracket@@  24.fxe5  is what White should have tried, although I must admit it does look a bit counterintuitive. Black can even recapture with the bishop  24...Bxe5  and follow up with ...Nf6, enjoying the beautiful outpost on e5. Nevertheless, the position should be about equal, as White has Nd5 in return. }
24... exf4 25. gxf4 Bd8
{ I could have played ...Bxc3 instead, followed by ...Nf6, which is a smart plan, but I wanted to keep the game as complicated as possible. This decision reflects quite well my playing style at that time: not very precise, but keeping a lot of pressure at the same time. }
26. Nd5 Nf6 27. Ba2 Nh5
{ True to the shuffling regime... When I look at the position today, I honestly don't understand why I didn't take  27...Bxd5  28.cxd5  Rxc1  29.Rxc1  b5  , which looks very passive for White.  30.Rc6  Ne7  followed by ...Bb6,  or even  30...Nh5  ,  with the idea of bringing the dark-squared bishop to h4-g3 and enjoying a healthy position, especially since the light-squared bishop is stuck on a2. }
28. Rcd1
{ Preventing Black's threat of taking on d5 when the pawn would have been hanging on f4 at the end of the line. }
28... Qb7
{ A move I was quite proud of and also a very nice move visually. The position should be about equal since 27...Nh5 was imprecise, but my opponent didn't find the best moves either. }
29. Kh2
{ Best was  29.Bd4  Qd7  30.Qf3  Bxd5  31.Qxh5  which is a tricky line.  31...Bb7  or 31...Ba8, with a balanced game, as the bishop on d4 controls a lot of squares, meaning that White is out of danger.  @@StartBracket@@  31...Bxe4  is not possible in view of  32.f5  Nh4  33.Qg4  and the bishop is too loose on e4.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2rbr1k1/1b1q1ppp/pp1p2n1/7Q/1PPBPP2/P6P/B2N4/3R1RK1 w - - 1 32@@EndFEN@@  32.Kh2  b5  with an unclear position. }
29... Qd7 30. Qe2
{ White needs to attack the knight on h5, but here it is not working that well due to tactical reasons. }
30... Bxd5 31. cxd5 { 31.Qxh5  Bxe4  32.f5  Bxf5  and Black is winning. } 31...
Rc3 { Black is very active now, hinting at h3 indirectly as well. } 32. Qxh5
{ A@@EndBracket@@  32.Nb1  is bad due to  32...Nhxf4  33.Bxf4  Qxh3+  34.Kg1  Nxf4  35.Rxf4  Rg3+  and Black's attack crashes through.   B@@EndBracket@@  32.f5  Ne5  33.Nb1  Rxe3  34.Qxe3  does win an exchange but after  34...h6  ,  Black's pieces are so powerful that White's position is practically lost. Possible ideas are ...Nf6, ...b5 followed by ...Bb6, while the bishop on a2 is doing nothing. }
32... Rxe3 33. Rf3 Re2+ { A good career for the a8-rook! } 34. Kh1 Qa4
{ An inaccurate move. I saw a queen sacrifice and that was so tempting that I couldn't consider anything else. Truth be told, this is a problem sometimes for me, as I like the positions where I can sacrifice the queen for a rook and a piece.   34...Nh4  is much stronger.  35.Rg3  Rf2  with a winning position. }
35. Bb3
{ White doesn't have many options available and accepting the queen sacrifice is rather forced. }
35... Qxa3 36. Bc4 Re3 37. Nb1 Rxf3
{ 37...Qxb4  is another possibility,  38.Rxe3  Qxc4  and Black is still better. }
38. Nxa3 Rxa3 39. Qf5 Bf6
{ From afar, I assessed this position as being completely dominated by Black, especially given the control of the dark squares. }
40. Rc1
{ The 'well-known' move 40 blunder.   40.e5  is what my opponent should have played and after  40...dxe5  41.fxe5  Nxe5  42.Re1  , White has chances to survive. }
40... Nh4 41. Qg4 h5 42. Qd7 Rd8 { The queen can no longer keep an eye on h3. }
43. Qc7 Rxh3+ 44. Kg1 Bd4+ 45. Kf1 Re8
{ White is completely lost, given the open king and uncoordinated pieces. } 46.
Qd7 Rf3+ 47. Ke2 Rxe4+ 48. Kd1 Bf6 49. Qxd6 Nf5 50. Qxb6 Rd4+
{ My opponent resigned here since after  51.Ke2  Re3+  , the king will get mated on the kingside.  This was a game full of mistakes and dubious decisions for both sides, but that was typical for my play in those years when I had just become a grandmaster. I liked to shuffle my pieces and keep the game going, a strategy which, in time, contributed to my chess understanding.  I believe that many strong players improved this way, by learning how to maneuver in these types of openings like Hedgehog and King's Indian, which contain a lot of strategic risks. I am happy I went through this instructional phase thanks to my second coach, Arshak Petrosian. }
*


