[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Vladislav Nevednichy, Batumi 1999 "]
[Result "*"]

{ This game against Vladislav Nevednichy @@StartBracket@@representing Romania@@EndBracket@@ was played in the third round of the 12th European's Men's Team Chess Tournament, which was played in Batumi in 1999.It was my first team championship playing for the main team, after playing for the second team in 1996. The main reason for this was that a lot of other players had declined. I was rated 2518, quite humble to make it to the team, and seventeen years old. We didn't have any finances or anything, and I remember that we drove for more than 10 hours from Yerevan to Batumi in a van.Because there was no financial incentive, and nobody wanted to represent the team, our team consisted of Smbat Lputian, Artashes Minasian, Ashot Anastasian, myself, and our coach Arshak Petrosian @@StartBracket@@who was also my coach@@EndBracket@@. So a small team without any reserves, we were rated about 14th in the tournament but ended up winning because we were very united and in high spirits. I played well, scoring a +3. }
1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3
{ As you probably have already seen I used to play a RÃ©ti opening at the time. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O
{ I knew that my opponent, who I had played before, was really into tactics and all kinds of things like that. A sharp player, and of course he chose to play a King's Indian. }
5. d4 d6 6. c4 Nc6 7. Nc3 Rb8
{ My opponent was rated 20 points higher than me, but I was a bit worried to tell you the truth. First of all, because it's my first tournament playing for the team. And second of all because it's unpleasant to play against opponents who are always trying to play for a win with Black, and my opponent was someone like that.Here, he played  7...Rb8  which is a rare move for a Yugoslav line of the King's Indian.  7...a6  is normally played, and lately  7...e5  8.d5  Nb8  is also seen.Generally, the g3-King's Indian is a very solid opening for White, and I think that it is a pleasant line to play for White. You're never under the risk of getting mated as in other King's Indians. }
8. d5
{ This is what my coach showed me when we were preparing before the game. }
8... Na5 9. Nd2 c5 10. Rb1 e6
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 2 7@@EndFEN@@After the game, I started understanding the whole point of this  7...Rb8  .  I don't remember who told me, but normally in these lines when Black plays with  7...a6  ,  after  8.d5  Na5  9.Nd2  c5  10.Rb1  ,  Black cannot play for ...e5 here because the b6-square is a bit weak. So when I play b4, there is always a hole on b6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 2 7@@EndFEN@@While in this particular line, when Black plays  7...Rb8  8.d5  Na5  9.Nd2  c5  10.Rb1  e5  is a viable option, and if I go for  11.a3  ,  then Black can hide his knight  11...b6  12.b4  Nb7  and then, since his pawn is not on a6, there are no real issues when I take  12.bxc5  as the b6-pawn is no longer a weakness.   Therefore,  10...e5  would have been quite a normal move, but my opponent went for  10...e6  . }
11. b3
{ Looks very logical. Of course, I can try to take on e6  11.dxe6  and after  11...Bxe6  ,  there are moves like  12.Nd5  ,  but at this moment the rook is on b8, so it's a bit different. Black gets too much activity.   So  11.b3  is a very solid move. This whole line has mainly been revolving around the a5-knight, which is both a strength and a weakness. When Black manages to play ...a6 and ...b5 he is attacking the c4-pawn, when White's knight is kind of tied to the defense of the c4-pawn, but there are lots of ways to untie it. I will show you in a future example how to do it with White. }
11... exd5
{ This is maybe a bit too risky, but as I told you my opponent was the kind of guy who liked open lines and going for active play @@StartBracket@@and still does that@@EndBracket@@.  11...a6  is a normal move here when White can go for something like  12.Bb2  b5  13.Qc2  .   It's quite understandable that my opponent didn't go for 11...a6, as he had already played ...Rb8 earlier in the game. I guess that he didn't want to transpose into any of the earlier mentioned ...a6 lines, or that he maybe didn't know the ...e5 idea , which is the whole point of this line. }
12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5
{ I was quite happy with my position here but did not really understand what was happening. It's true that White has a pleasant position, as the d5-bishop is quite dominating.   I could also have taken with the pawn  13.cxd5  in an attempt to play against the knight on a5.  13...b5  14.Bb2  Bxb2  15.Rxb2  Qf6  ,  but I didn't really have a lot of experience in these lines and wasn't so sure if this type of position is good for me. Right now when I look at it I think that yeah, White is clearly better here because I can play  16.Qc1  with 17.e4 next move.I can always play Rc2, and the knight is still a weak piece. Black will at some point need to commit with ...c4 to bring his knight into the game through b7 and c5, as otherwise, the knight will not have any other prospects. Black could also try ...b4, ...Ba6, and then try to play for ...c4,  but I think this is less realistic. White is clearly better after @@StartFEN@@1rbq1rk1/pp3pbp/3p2p1/n1pn4/2P5/1P4P1/P2NPPBP/1RBQ1RK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.cxd5  as well. }
13... Kh8
{ A strange move. As I understood, he rejected  13...Nc6  , probably because of  14.Ne4  ,  but this wouldn't be the end of the world.  14...Nb4  15.Nxd6  .  I mean he has  15...Bh3  here. This is not that scary for Black, but I guess that visually the Ne4 and Bf4 ideas look very dangerous. White is threatening too many things. He went 13...Kh8, an understandable decision to stop this Ne4 and Bf4 idea. }
14. Ne4 { A good move. } 14... f5 15. Ng5 Qe7
{ Here I started thinking about the position, as I wasn't so sure how to proceed. Of course, White is clearly better, and with my dominating bishop on d5 and knight on g5, a move like e4 is very tempting. Just blow up the whole center and crush Black.At this moment in the game I cannot say that I was afraid of my opponent, but I was afraid to blunder something. The pressure was high. I started thinking, what is something practical that I can play to make sure that I will never lose this game, preventing all tactics. This is a kind of approach that I've used quite a lot throughout my career. You're not playing objectively, but rather playing against your opponent. Which of course is also objective. At the end of the day, we all have our weaknesses, and if you don't like something I will definitely try to do it for you.I knew that my opponent is excellent at pushing and playing for tricks, but isn't as good at passive positions. And therefore I played this idea, which might not be the best, but is very interesting. I would be very happy if you could find what I played here, or at least hint at what White can do here.   One of the best moves in this position is of course  16.h4  Nc6  when White can just take on c6.  17.Bxc6  bxc6  18.Bf4  would also be quite logical. If you found this idea it's correct, but I played something that is very original and requires some imagination.   Another move to play here is  16.Bf4  ,  but I wasn't so sure about  16...h6  17.Nf3  g5  and was a bit worried that things would not work out. }
16. Qd2 { Was what I played in the game. } 16... Nc6
{ Of course, a move like  16...b6  is out of the question. I mean, it just doesn't make any sense. The knight requires such a long path to come back. The whole idea behind the ...e6 idea was to bring the knight back, so ...b6 now will be illogical. }
17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. f4
{ A move that I've been very proud of. Let's try to understand the point of it. Black has two bishops, one of which is going to be exchanged no matter what. Black cannot really stop White from playing Bb2, so Black will be left with just the c8-bishop.And after f4, how does Black activate this bishop? He has to try and play ...d5 and ...dxc4. The main issue with this is that my knight will get very comfortable on the e5-square after being rerouted through f3.This means that ...d5 is not quite possible, because what is Black going to do after my knight reaches e5? Which is what 17.Bxc6 accomplishes. I get a position where the only way for my opponent to activate means that I get a lot of control. A knight on e5 cannot be challenged by anything, and therefore he has to sit still and can never activate.This was extremely unpleasant for my opponent. Imagine this, I think that my opponent was maybe ten to fifteen years older than me, and I'm this seventeen-year-old kid that is just torturing him. I'm not letting him play a game, he is just shuffling his pieces around and enjoying the position. And knowing myself, I will be very very proudly walking around and looking at my position. If I was playing against me at that moment, of course, I would be very annoying.   Let's take a look at why  18...d5  is not possible. The main problem here is  19.Bb2  d4  when I can just play  20.e3  or even 20.Rbe1 followed by e3 or e4 because the c5-pawn is also extremely weak.   20.Rbe1  could also be annoying. I want to play e3, and if you try to stop me with  20...Re8  ,  I can play either e4 or  21.e3  ,  which is probably more logical. And if you take  21...dxe3  22.Bxg7  Kxg7  23.Qc3+  Qf6  when I can simply take the pawn.  After retreating with the king,  23...Kg8  ,  I'll just attack the pawn with  24.Rf3  and grab it.  I can always, after opening up the center, just bring my bishop to a3 and capture the c5-pawn. If Black tries to take with either the pawn or queen, for example,  20...Qxe3  21.Qxe3  dxe3  22.Bxg7  Kxg7  23.Rfe1  Re8  ,  I can play  24.Nf3  and then bring the knight to e5.   I can also play  24.Rbd1  .  There are different ways to capture this pawn.  24...Rb7  25.Rd3  Rbe7  and the bishop is completely cut off from the game.  25.Nf3  Re4  ,  just taking the pawn and then slowly getting closer to the c5-pawn. }
18... h6 { Was what my opponent played in the game. } 19. Nf3 Be6 20. Bb2
{ I'm now accomplishing what I want. } 20... Rfe8 21. Bxg7+ Kxg7 22. Rbd1
{ Here I was very proud. Sitting next to my teammates, with a very nice position against a strong player where I don't risk losing at all. }
22... Rbd8 23. Qc3+ Qf6 24. Qa5
{ Am I trying to accomplish anything? Not really, I'm just shuffling my pieces. }
24... Qe7 25. h4
{ I think this move is much more psychological than anything. I wanted to make sure that ...g5 will never happen. And the bishop is always going to be passive. }
25... Bf7 26. Rfe1 Qe3+
{ This is also a kind of psychological move for him. At least he tries to give checks to show some activity. Because what is he supposed to do? Double on the e-file? It's easy for me to defend on e2, or even play e3 if I want to.Playing  26...d5  is never possible.  27.Ne5  and the queen cannot really both defend the c5-pawn and get rid of the knight on e5. If Black was in time to play  27...Qd6  and I play a ridiculously stupid move like  28.e3  , after which Black manages to take on e5,  28...Rxe5  29.fxe5  Qxe5  ,  then he is doing fine, and I probably have to force a draw by taking on d8.  30.Qxd8  Qxg3  when it's a perpetual.   @@StartFEN@@3rr3/p4bk1/2pq2pp/Q1ppNp2/2P2P1P/1P4P1/P3P3/3RR1K1 w - - 2 28@@EndFEN@@But I will never let him do that. I will always play something like  28.Kg2  and after some preparation, Nd3 will always be a problem for Black, as he cannot really protect the c5-pawn.So the activity is not really a relief but instead weakening Black's position because the position was very solid. Objectively, White is slightly better, but it's not enough to win the game. I don't really have big activation plans. Black will just protect the c5-pawn, continue to hope, and wait for me. }
27. Kg2 Rd7 28. Rd3 Qe4 29. Qc3+ Kg8 30. Kf2
{ It's not clear what I'm doing, but it's also not clear what he's doing. }
30... Qe7 31. Qd2 Red8 32. Rd1 Be6 33. Qa5
{ What I'm doing in this game is something I've done in maybe ten games. Winning by not really doing anything. It's a strange concept, but I have seen it done by Karpov, Kramnik, Capablanca, and maybe other strong players.Because when you're just shuffling your pieces around, your opponent slowly loses the sense of danger. And then in a single moment, he might actually blunder something. Because well, you were not really doing anything, and then suddenly you're winning due to some tactics.Let's see what happened here. }
33... Rc8 34. Qe1 Rcd8 35. Qd2
{ I've got the same position one tempo down because I'm enjoying myself too much. I'm doing a trick of winning the game without doing anything. }
35... Kh7 36. Re3 Qf6
{ This move is not very good. Black had to play  36...Qf7  and despite that Black's position is kind of passive, there isn't really anything wrong happening for Black. I can try to play with h5, or try to transfer my knight. It's passive, but not losing. }
37. Ng5+ { This is winning for White. } 37... hxg5 38. hxg5 Qf7
{ 38...Qe7  would have led to the same. } 39. Rh1+ Kg8 40. Qc3
{ The problem is that after  40...Kf8  ,  I can play  41.Rh8+  Ke7  42.Rxe6+  Qxe6   In case of  42...Kxe6  ,  it's a mate in one with  43.Qe3#  .  43.Rh7+  Kf8  is the only move.  44.Qh8+  Qg8  45.Qf6+  Ke8  46.Rh8+  .  I don't just win the queen, I win his whole structure. Both the g6 and f5-pawns are falling, after which the f4 and g5-pawns are promoting. }
40... Qg7 { Played out of desperation. } 41. Qxg7+ Rxg7 42. Rxe6 Kf7 43. Rf6+
Ke7 44. e4 { The easiest way to win. } 44... fxe4 45. Re1
{ After  45...d5  ,  I'm just taking on c6.  46.Rxc6  and everything is falling.   45...Kd7  46.Rxe4  and the rook enters on e6. As they said in the Soviet Union, the collection of the crop is starting. I'm starting to collect the pawns.   Therefore my opponent resigned after  45.Re1  .  Can I say that I played a brilliant game? No, not really. But it became brilliant because I knew that my opponent didn't like this type of strategy, and because I found this interesting  idea of @@StartFEN@@1rb2r1k/pp2q1bp/2np2p1/2pB1pN1/2P5/1P4P1/P2QPP1P/1RB2RK1 w - - 4 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Bxc6  and @@StartFEN@@1rb2r1k/p3q1bp/2pp2p1/2p2pN1/2P5/1P4P1/P2QPP1P/1RB2RK1 w - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18.f4  , completely locking out his bishop.It's a positional game I'm still proud of and a very important game to both my team and me personally. It gave me lots of confidence knowing that if I want to, I can actually make an aggressive player suffer a lot by playing against him and not being too objective about the position. }
*


