[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Smbat Lputian vs. Levon Aronian, Yerevan 2000"]
[Result "*"]

{ We come to the year 2000. I'm playing with Black against Smbat Lputian, who is one of our best players, in the fourth round of the Armenian Championship. I was kind of nervous, and I always wanted to play well in the Armenian Championship, but I have won it only once.At the time I was playing the Gruenfeld defense. I still flirt with the idea of playing the Gruenfeld, but it's much harder now because the theory has developed much further. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ This  7.Bc4  line is known as the Alekhine variation. It's a very interesting idea, where White is trying to avoid the pin of the f3-knight by bringing the knight to e2. This was very popular back in the day, and still is.The main issue is that once the knight is on e2, Black quite often puts the pawn on e5 after which the knight becomes a bit trapped there. So White will have to try playing with f4 to free up his knight, or transfer the knight somewhere. These are the drawbacks of this line for White. }
7... O-O 8. Ne2 Nc6
{ The  8...Nc6  9.--  e5  line was kind of popular at the time. It's not really working so well, but I was fond of it as I always liked these original ideas.   The normal move is  8...c5  which is far more logical. Black goes for ....Nc6, ...b6, and ...Bb7 and then tries playing against center @@StartBracket@@the e4- and d4-pawns@@EndBracket@@. }
9. O-O e5 10. Ba3
{ 10.Be3  is an option. Normally I would respond with  10...Qe7  11.f3  Rd8  Black has to try and force White to commit with d5.   The point of the opening, the ...Nc6-idea, is that Black is trying to keep the c7-pawn in order to put the knight on c5. For example, if White plays  10.d5  Na5  11.Bd3  b6  12.c4  then  12...Nb7  13.Ba3  Re8  What I will do next is exchange the bishops, after which the knight will be incredible on c5. It's a piece that cannot be driven out by pawns, so the c5- and d6-squares will be in Black's control. The queen and knight control the dark squares. }
10... Re8 11. d5
{ A dubious idea.   11.Bxf7  Of course there are many other options, like 11. Bd5, but they're all dubious.11. Bxf7 is a good move, and the only move that refuted this line.  11...Kxf7  12.Qb3+  When I was playing this game I was planning to play  12...Kf6  because there some game by Tukmakov who played this line with Black, and I think it's Topalov who also lost a game like it with White after playing  13.f4  here. This is what I've expected to get here.   Unfortunately, this line was later found to be completely unsound for Black.  13.Rad1  is just winning on the spot, because Black cannot do anything. If he takes on d4  13...exd4  14.Nxd4  the queen is so badly placed that everything works for White.  13...Bh6  14.fxe5+  Kg7  Is not really great for Black, but I was playing against a very experienced positional player. I wanted to create a messy position where both sides are looking for tactical ideas.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqr3/ppp3bp/2n2kp1/4p3/3PP3/BQP5/P3NPPP/R4RK1 w - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@If someone is going to play this line with Black, you probably have to opt for  12...Be6  13.d5  Na5  14.dxe6+  Rxe6  15.Qa4  which looks risky for Black, but is not directly refuted. It definitely is no fun for Black. After  15...c6  16.Rad1  Qc7  17.c4  Black is stuck with the a5-knight. The structure is less than ideal because of the e5-weakness, and the a5-knight will take a long time to come back into the game as ...b4 and ...Nc4 are prevented. This passive position is not recommended for Black. If White would exchange the bishops it would be one thing  17...Bf8  White will just play  18.Bb2  @@StartBracket@@or 18. Bc1@@EndBracket@@, threatening Bc3 and Bd2. The knight will move through c1 to d3, and it's a difficult position for Black.   But back in the day my opponent didn't know this and played  11.d5 }
11... Na5 12. Bd3
{ Here I committed a very educational mistake, and the reason why I'm showing this game is because I want to discuss what it means to have illusions. Something we're told from childhood where, when we face it, we understand that this is not that easy or good.The best move for Black would have been  12...b6  with the same idea I showed earlier. I'll bring the knight back  13.c4  Nb7  and then threaten ...Bf8, when Black is totally fine. }
12... Bf8
{ I thought that I was super clever in the game and played  12...Bf8  .  If he now takes  13.Bxf8  I can just take with the rook.  13...Rxf8  And I can always play for ...b6, but if I'm so inclined I can also play with ...c6. Let's say that White plays  14.Qd2  then maybe I can play  14...c6  15.c4  b6  when the bishop will come to a6. It's a more active way where I might exploit the fact that the knight on a5 attacks the c4-pawn.   What I was trying to do is that sometimes in these positions, after the bishop takes on f8, White is playing with  14.f4  which I wanted to meet with c6 and a quick attack against the center. If you're rerouting your knight to c5, White sometimes has time to start pushing and get an aggressive position. If I'm just doing some slow maneuvring  14...exf4  15.Nxf4  b6  16.e5  Nb7  then it's already looking very dangerous for Black.  17.e6  might come.  17...fxe6  and things like Nxg6 or  18.Bxg6  might already be dangerous for Black.  18...hxg6  19.Qg4  This isn't a 100% precise, but more or less in detail. I was trying to meet f4 with c6 and a quick attack on the center, not allowing him to play e5. }
13. Bb4
{ You might ask me, what about  13.Bb4  ,  attacking the knight. Are you going to play  13...b6  ? Of course I can, but you can see that this  14.Bxa5  bxa5  is a bit unhealthy with this weak structure.  15.Bb5  and now I also have to exchange the bishops,  15...Bd7  16.Qa4  which is far from ideal. }
13... c5
{ Was what I had in mind, and this is what happened in the game. I was wondering what my opponent, who with a rating of 2598 was a solid 2600 player, was doing. Is he giving away his bishop? }
14. Bxa5 Qxa5 15. a4
{ At this point I thought that my opponent was a patzer. I have two bishops, and I can do anything I want. But then I started thinking about my position, and the deeper I was getting into the position, the more I was understanding that I was the patzer, and not my opponent.Should I have had a knight on d6 it would have allowed me to play for c4, but I have this beautiful bishop on d6 with a blockade. White is never going to play for f4.   But what is my plan? It then occurred to me that I don't really have a square for the c8-bishop. Once I play  15...Bd7  he will immediately start attacking the b7-pawn.  16.Qb3  And if I somehow protect it  16...Qc7  he's going to exchange the bishops with  17.Bb5  And what comes next? Correct, the knight will go from c1 to d3, b2, and eventually c4. Or it will move to g3, after which White will play Rfe1 and bring the knight into play.And what can I do while he does this for several moves? Not so much, because I don't have a knight to support an attack with ...f5. So this whole f5-business is not going anywhere. White can just play f3. Okay, I can lock up the position, but the white knight will eventually reach c4.This was a positional realization that, what was told in my childhood about having two bishops and having a great blockading piece, has nothing to do with the reality. The reality is that White has better pieces because he can play Qc2, bring the knight from b3 and d2 to c4 while I will be passive. The c8-bishop doesn't have any squares, and ...f5 is not really an option.I have three pawns against his two on the queenside, but I can never play for ...a6 and ...b5 because is controlling the whole flank with his pieces. }
15... Bd6 { So I played  15...Bd6 } 16. Qc2 Rf8
{ I felt that if I'm going to lose this game, I would rather lose it by being active. I was really depressed at the moment, because I understood that I just got outplayer in the most primitive and simple way. My bishop on d6 is beautiful, but it's not doing anything. So I have to play fast. }
17. Kh1
{ White is not in a rush. He can always transfer the knight, so he plays a waiting move. }
17... f5
{ This move shows my psychological situation. I should have probably played something like  17...Qc7  with the idea to play ...Qe7 and only then aim for ...f5. White is slightly better and can play something like  18.Bc4  Kg7  19.a5  and bring the rook to b1, but my position is kind of solid.  19...Qe7  Nothing tragic is happening, and White will probably play something like  20.Ng1  followed by Nf3 and Nd2.   @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq2p1p/3b2p1/2pPp3/P3P3/2PB4/2Q1NPPP/R4R1K w - - 5 18@@EndFEN@@White might even try to play  18.Ng1  here, when  18...c4  is probably too risky.  19.Be2  Because once the knight reaches d2 you're going to regret this decision.   I might be able to wait.  18...Kg7  19.Nf3  h5  20.Nd2  When it's a slightly worse position for Black. However, it's kind of passive because I can't really get the a8-rook into play. Once I play  20...Bd7  White will threaten to exchange the bishops.  21.Bb5  I really don't want to exchange the bishops, because after they are exchanged the knight on c4 becomes very strong. I also don't know how to protect the b7-pawn in a good way. If I play something like  21...Rab8  22.Bxd7  Qxd7  23.Nc4  analyzing what's going to happen if I play passively.  23...b6  24.Rfb1  when he'll play Rb5 and Rab1 next, threatening a5. White has a clear plan, but I don't because ...f5 is not going anywhere.  24...f5  25.Rb5   or maybe  25.f3  first.  25...f4  is way to slow.  26.Rb5  g5  27.Rab1  g4  28.a5  The whole attack is not going anywhere without a knight on g5 or somewhere similar to threaten the king. I also don't have a light-squared bishop, with which @@StartBracket@@if my opponent didn't also have a light-squared bishop@@EndBracket@@ I could at least try to play for  28...g3  29.h3  and threaten to take on h3. Not meaning that it would be any good, but at least I would have this fantasy of creating a threat. But here it's just stupid because I cannot ever take on h3, and don't have any real counterplay.   That's how I explained my  17...f5 }
18. exf5 gxf5 19. f4 e4 20. Bc4
{ The problem remains the same, I can never bring my bishop out because it will be exchanged. White has the simple plan to bring his knight to e3. It will take a long time to bring the knight into play @@StartBracket@@Ng3-Nf1-Ne3@@EndBracket@@, but since I don't really have a direct plan White can do whatever he wants. }
20... Rf6 21. Ng3 Rh6 { At least trying to create something. } 22. Rf2
{ Here I realized that the ...Qd8 plan is not going anywhere. I'm still completely stuck with this whole queenside plan because of the same issues. }
22... a6 { At least I'm threatening some plan with ...b5 at the moment. } 23.
Ra2 Bd7 24. Nf1 Kh8 25. g3 Rg8 26. Rg2
{ It might look like Black has accomplished something, because he at least now has some activity. But little has been accomplished, because the knight is still coming to e3. Once the knight reaches this square I cannot really untie myself because of the weakness of the f5-pawn. I somehow managed to make a draw by bluffing around. }
26... Rh3 27. Qb3 Bc8 28. Rab2 Rg6
{ White had lots of good options in this position. Smbat didn't make the best decisions, because even though he was a very good player, and still is, he was blundering a lot of tactics and falling into time trouble a lot at that time. }
29. Qb6 Qxc3 30. Qd8+ Rg8 31. Qxd6 Qxc4 { Somehow things worked out for me. }
32. Rgf2 Re8 33. Ne3 Qd4
{ A couple of moves later we agreed to a draw, so I managed to kind of stabilize. Although I think that this position is still good for White because the bishop is stuck on c8. }
34. Kg2 Rh5 35. Rfe2 Rg8
{ This is what happened in the game. I kind of managed to trick him, but I don't really have good prospects here. The game ended in a draw after some play.The main lesson is that sometimes you can have a visually good position, but in reality there is no real future. You're just stuck without a plan. So it's not about visuals, but about understanding what the pieces can do together.@@StartFEN@@r1b1rbk1/pp3p1p/6p1/q1pPp3/P3P3/2PB4/4NPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - a3 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bd6  If we look back on this position without getting too emotional about the two bishops, we might wonder where my c8-bishop is going to go and what my plan is. Can I advance on the queenside or the kingside?I started realizing that Black doesn't have an active plan, while White's plan is very simple. He just reroutes and brings his knight to c4, and he has strong pressure on the b-file.The main difference is that he has a target, with a higher quality rook and position. He will double on the b-file and use more pieces than I will, because my active plans with ...b5 actually lead to a kind of blockade anyway.So we can conclude that this position is simply better for White, and that we should not try to go for this plan with ...Bf8. This is quite a difficult understanding, but I found it to be very useful to understand. In some positions two bishops without any knights are actually not doing anything, because in order to attack on the kingside in these King's Indian structures you definitely need a pair of knights. }
36. Rbc2 Qg7 37. Kf1 Bd7 38. Rxc5 Bxa4 39. Rc7 Rh6 40. Rxg7 Rxd6 41. Rxg8+ Kxg8
42. Nxf5 Rf6 43. Nd4 Rd6 44. Nf5 Rf6 *


