{ 2001 was a special year for me because I started working with a dear friend of mine, Gabriel Sargissian; he helped me take my game to a new level. Once my coach had already moved from Armenia, Arshak Petrosian, I understood that I had to improve myself and maybe find a good sparring partner. Gabi is a very positional player; he grew up with Karpov on his mind while I grew up with Alekhine.  I think this was a great combination, and soon enough, the results proved so.  This game I really wanted to win against him, because I had lost two games already and it was really making me upset. I was losing the games like a child; we exchanged some pieces, and slowly in the endgame, he dominated me.  This is still his style today; nevertheless this game, I was determined to change the trend. }
1. Nf3 e6 { I safely played e6 because I knew Gabi never plays e4. } 2. c4 Nf6
3. g3 d5 4. d4 dxc4
{ Around this time, since we were already working together, we've been trying to surprise each other in the opening.   In the Catalan, I was mostly playing with Bb7, but I had already analyzed this line since my previous coach Arshak Petrosian used to play this line with Na6-a6. }
5. Qa4+
{ Here Gabi of course surprised me with this move.  Nowadays, this check is rarely played -  5.Bg2  offers white more chances. }
5... Nbd7 6. Bg2
{ This looks like a normal Catalan but black is already doing very good. Normally white tries to pick up the c4 pawn either much earlier with the queen or to pick it up with a different piece. }
6... a6 7. Qxc4
{ 7.Nc3  is also a normal move.  7...b5  8.Nxb5  axb5  9.Qxa8  I'm not sure where this is leading to  9...Bb4+  but if I remember correctly there is some line like this  10.Bd2  Nb6  11.Qa7  . }
7... b5 8. Qc2
{ This move is more natural, but the other queen move is also possible. The disadvantage of the 5.Qa4+ system is that white loses too much time with the queen.   8.Qc6  Rb8   @@StartBracket@@  8...Ra7  9.Be3  Nd5  10.Qc1  c5  11.Nc3  Nxe3  12.Qxe3  cxd4â©²  @@EndBracket@@  9.Bf4  Nd5  10.Bg5  Be7  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  12.Nc3  Qb4  13.O-O  Nxc3  14.bxc3  Qd6= }
8... Bb7 9. Bg5
{ 9.O-O  c5  10.a4  Rc8  11.axb5  axb5  12.dxc5  Bxc5  13.Qd3  Qb6  14.Nc3  Bc6= }
9... c5
{ In such positions, Black must play c7-c5. We have a comfortable position and good development. }
10. O-O
{ This looks kind of passive, it is clear that white is just trying to equalize the position in fact.   10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.O-O  Rc8  12.Qb3  Qb6  13.Bxf6  Nxf6  14.Nc3  Ng4  15.e3  Bxe3  16.fxe3  Nxe3  17.Kh1  Nxf1  18.Rxf1  O-O  0-1 Donchenko,A-Rustemov,A Moscow 1999. }
10... cxd4
{ 10...Rc8  11.Qd2  Be7  12.Nc3  b4  13.Na4  c4  14.a3  a5  15.Rfd1  O-O  16.Qe1  Be4  0-1 Beaumont,C-Jonkman,H England 2000. }
11. Nxd4 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Rc8
{ Black has a very comfortable position, and we have already exchanged the most dangerous white piece, the g2-bishop. }
13. Qd1 h6
{ Now we are basically forcing white to take on h6.   13...Bc5  14.Nb3  O-O  15.Nc3  Be7  16.Rc1  Qb6  17.e3  Qb7+  18.Qf3  Qxf3+  19.Kxf3  Ne5+  20.Ke2  Nc4  21.Nd1  h6  22.Bxf6  Bxf6  23.Nd4  Rfd8  0-1 Zunker, D-Serper,G Moscow 1990. }
14. Bd2
{ Here he surprised me with this move Bd2, I thought this was way too risky for white and it truly is.  14.Bxf6  Qxf6!?   @@StartBracket@@  14...Nxf6=  @@EndBracket@@  15.Nc3  Bc5â©±  with a fine position for black.   15...Bb4  16.Ne4  Qe5  17.Qd3  f5â }
14... Qb6
{ The queen is very well placed on b6 - now the d4-knight is hanging and later on Black can use the diagonal. }
15. Nf3 Qb7
{ Here, I could even play  15...b4  my position is much better already. Instead, I went with  15...Qb7  and remained cautious because in our two previous encounters I played active moves true to my style, and I suffered the consequences as soon as I gave up squares for him to start manoeuvring in his Karpovian style. After  15...b4  I didn't like  16.Be1  followed by bringing the knight to d2-b3; I didn't want this. }
16. Ba5
{ White plays this strange move to develop with Nbd2.   16.Nc3  b4  17.Na4  Ne5â©± }
16... e5
{ This is also a cautious move; I'm trying to stop him from playing  17.Nbd2  because here I have  17...e4  18.Nd4  e3  and the kingside pawn structure is ruined.   16...Be7  17.Nbd2  O-O  â©± }
17. e3
{ 17.Nc3?  b4  After this move, the a5-bishop is locked in.  18.Qb3   @@StartBracket@@  18.Na4  Qb5-+  @@EndBracket@@  18...Qb8  19.Na4  Qb5-+ }
17... Nb8
{ Original play - Black loses two tempi, but the knight gets to c6, where it is excellent. }
18. Nd2 Be7 { 18...Nc6  19.Nb3â©± } 19. Nb3 O-O 20. Qe2 { 20.Kg1  Nc6â©± } 20...
Qe4
{ Probing the waters, if white goes  21.Nbd2!?  Qg4   @@StartBracket@@  21...Qa4  22.Bc3  @@EndBracket@@  22.e4  Nc6  23.Bb6â©± }
21. Bc3 Nc6 22. Rac1
{ 22.Nbd2  Qg4â©±   Now I saw the opportunity to play an interesting move, although objectively not the best. What do you think I played here? }
22... b4
{ Since I was avoiding this move in the entire game, maybe it is a bit difficult for you to guess that I played b4 now! }
23. Bd2 Nd4 { b4 doesn't make sense without this follow-up move. } 24. Nxd4
{ Forced otherwise  24.Qd1  is too passive  24...Nxb3   @@StartBracket@@  24...Rxc1  25.Nxc1  Nxf3  26.Qxf3  Qxf3+  27.Kxf3  Rc8â©±  @@EndBracket@@  25.axb3   @@StartBracket@@why does the move  25.Qxb3  lose on the spot?  25...g5  26.h3  h5-+  @@EndBracket@@  25...Rxc1  26.Bxc1  Rc8â }
24... exd4 25. Qxa6
{ An inaccuracy by my opponent.   When I was looking at this position from a distance, I thought that  25.Rxc8  is not good for him  25...Rxc8  26.Qxa6  In this way, white has one more tempo since the rook hangs on c8. But here I have many options  26...dxe3   @@StartBracket@@  26...Rc2  this doesn't work right now  27.exd4  Rxd2  28.Re1Â±  and I lose the bishop without any compensation for the pawn@@EndBracket@@.   @@StartBracket@@I also thought I had to settle with  26...Rc5  , which I thought was completely crushing, but it is not.  27.exd4  Rf5  28.Bf4  and again the same issue Re1 is coming and after  28...Rxf4  29.gxf4  Nd5  30.Re1  , and this is just leading to a draw because there is nothing better I can do besides giving a check on h5.@@EndBracket@@   26...Ra8  27.Qb6  d3=â   @@StartBracket@@  27...Rxa2  28.exd4  Nd5  29.Qb8+  Kh7  30.Re1  @@EndBracket@@  27.Bxe3  Ra8  28.Qb6  Rxa2â©± }
25... Rxc1 26. Rxc1 { I think everyone knows what I played next. } 26... g5
{ The brutal g5-g4 is a threat. } 27. h3 h5
{ I was very proud of this game because I felt I was all over the place with b4-Nd4-g5-h5, completely dominating the game with black, and I think here my opponent finally collapsed. }
28. Qb5
{ Here actually white has a move that I missed and can equalize the position, can you find it?   28.Qc6!  and I cannot play  28...Nd5  because of  29.Qc2  d3  30.Qc4  and my queen is getting pushed away, I'm a pawn down and I'm not winning a piece anytime soon. Therefore after @@StartFEN@@5rk1/4bp2/2Q2n2/6pp/1p1pq3/4PNPP/PP1B1PK1/2R5 b - - 1 28@@EndFEN@@ Qc6 I have to play  28...g4  29.hxg4  hxg4  30.Qxe4  Nxe4  31.Nxd4  Nxd2  32.Rc2  well black is a piece up but it is very difficult to win this position. }
28... Nd5
{ The end. After this move white cannot prevent the threat g5-g4, so he loses a piece.   28...g4  29.Qg5+  Kh8  30.hxg4  hxg4  31.Rh1+  Nh7  32.Qe5++- }
29. Rc4 g4 30. hxg4 hxg4 31. Rxd4 gxf3+ 32. Kh3
{ 32.Kh2  allows  32...Qh7+  33.Kg1  Qh3  34.Qf1  Qxf1+  35.Kxf1  Rd8-+   And  32.Kg1  allows  32...Qb1+-+ }
32... Qf5+
{ And here I played correctly with Qf5+ because  32...Qh7+?  33.Kg4â  and maybe white slowly comes back into the game. }
33. g4
{ 33.Kh2  Qh5+   @@StartBracket@@  33...Nxe3?  34.Qxf5  Nxf5  35.Rg4+  Kh8  36.Rf4  Rd8  37.Bxb4  Bxb4  38.Rxf5â©±  @@EndBracket@@  34.Kg1  Qh3-+  There are many winning moves here, can you find the one that I played? }
33... Nf4+
{ And white resigned.   33...Qf6  34.Kg3  Bd6+-+  Well, the reason that I won this game is because I spotted this opportunity with b4 and g5 to change the rhythm of the game; this completely shocked my opponent, who's a very strong positional player and he didn't expect to get attacked like that on both flanks.   Another reason is maybe that he was expecting me like in previous encounters to play nervously and start pushing prematurely, unlike this one where I controlled my aggression. }
*


