[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Arsen Yegiazarian, Yerevan 2001"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a game that I played at the Armenian Championship in 2001 against a dear friend of mine, Arsen Yegiazarian, who unfortunately passed away.  Arsen and I spent a lot of time together during tournaments; we analyzed together a lot. I have beaten him many times. Although he was a good player, he seemed always to get nervous when he played against me.   We spent a lot of time drinking together more than actually discussing chess. He had a lot of respect for me as a player. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ Not a bright move, in fact, you can only commit to Bc4 if Black already played ...d6,  3...e6  4.O-O  Nf6  , and now if I play  5.Re1  , everybody knows the tactical trick  5...Nxe4  6.Rxe4  d5  7.Bxd5  Qxd5  8.Nc3  Qd7  followed by ...b6 and ...Bb7 and Black is totally fine. }
3... d6 4. h3 Nf6 5. d3 e6 6. Bb3
{ Of course, a lot of my moves are not even necessary.  Lately, I have been playing this position quite a lot with White when my opponent plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.d3  Nc6  .  I never play h3 here.  5.O-O  Bg4  and as it turns out, after this  6.h3  Bh5  7.g4  Bg6  ,  the position is extremely dangerous for Black.  After  8.Nh2  ,  White is threatening to push f4-f5. The bishop on g6 is kind of uncomfortable. If Black commits with ...e5, then after Nc3 and f4, White is dominating the key d5-square.  I always loved playing something offbeat, as you have seen already in previous examples.   Another point why Bb3 is not necessary: we can just castle instead,  6.O-O  , and after  6...d5  , White always has  7.Bb5  . Although, in this position specifically, it is not great for White because we already played h3. If we look at this position without h3, for example, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/2p5/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  Nf6  5.d3  e6  , White can just go  6.a4  and after  6...d5  7.Bb5   Taking the pawn  7...dxe4  8.dxe4  never works, we have too much activity and Ne5 is coming.  7...Bd7  8.e5  and White can afford to part ways with his bishop as long as Black's bishop remains locked on c6.  8...Ng4  @@StartBracket@@Stockfish prefers  8...Ng8  followed by manoeuvring the knight via e7-f5@@EndBracket@@. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1b1ppp/2n1p3/1BppP3/P5n1/3P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Re1  . }
6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. c3 Bd7
{ Arsen plays a cautious move. The best option for Black here is to play  8...b6  or  8...b5  , to bring out the c8-bishop to b7.  Black has a lot of plans in this position if White plays slowly. After  9.Re1  Bb7  10.Nbd2  , Black can try to play for  10...b4  11.Nf1  bxc3  12.bxc3  d5  13.e5  Nd7  followed by ...d4 and opening up the bishop on b7. And if White goes  14.d4  , then Black is too fast with  14...Ba6  followed by ...Rc8 and ...Nb4. It is always concrete and you need to be careful with Black. If you allow White to play Ng3-h5 followed by the sneaky Qd2-f4, you can get mated quickly without committing any big mistakes.   Another way to play is  8...b6  9.Re1  Bb7  10.Nbd2  Ne5  . I think Sam Sevian has played something like this recently against me.  11.Nxe5  dxe5  12.Nc4  Nd7  13.f4  exf4  14.Bxf4  Bg5  and I couldn't find anything better than repeating with  15.Bd6  Be7  16.Bf4  . }
9. Re1 Ne5
{ A bit premature, Black is not threatening to play ...Nd3, unlike in the previous position that we just analyzed @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2bppp/1p1ppn2/2p1n3/4P3/1BPP1N1P/PP1N1PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@ White cannot commit with  11.d4  here because after  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  Nd3  , Black gets the bishop pair.  13.Re3  Nxc1  14.Rxc1  Rc8  and despite the fact that White has the center, in the long run, Black's position is definitely easier to play. }
10. d4 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 e5
{ I'm guessing he played ...e5 because he couldn't figure out what to do with his d7-bishop.  11...Bc6  allows  12.d5  , which is kind of annoying.  12...exd5  13.exd5  Bd7  14.Nd2  and in this type of structure with d5-d6 pawns staring at each other, the evaluation will depend on the position of the pieces. If the d7-bishop was on g6, then this would be a completely different story. }
12. dxc5 dxc5 13. a4
{ A solid move, common for these types of structures. If you've seen some of my previous games, you can already see that this somehow resembles a RÃ©ti structure where the d-file is the only open line, but my bishop is absolutely brilliant on b3.  What I need to do is to transfer the knight from b1 to e3 or g3 and then play for Nf5 at an opportune moment.   Unfortunately, the knight can't jump to f5 immediately, but slowly and surely it will get there; Black doesn't have any serious counterplay. }
13... Bc6 14. Nd2 Qc7 15. Nc4
{ If I didn't have a concrete idea in mind, then  15.Nf1  would also be possible. }
15... Rae8 16. g4
{ 16.Bg5  is perhaps possible, but I felt it was not achieving anything at the moment because I was not interested in exchanging the bishops after  16...Nd7  17.Bd2  . Here, I had to calculate stuff like  17...Kh8  18.Ne3  f5  19.Nxf5  g6  .   My point behind g4 is that I want to push the knight out with g5, and also more importantly I have a vicious trick in mind. What is White threatening if Black plays @@StartFEN@@4rrk1/ppq1bppp/2b2n2/2p1p3/P1N1P1P1/1BP2Q1P/1P3P2/R1B1R1K1 b - g3 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...b6  for example?  17.Nxe5!  Qxe5  18.Bf4!  and the queen is almost trapped after  18...Bxe4  19.Qg3  . }
16... Nd7
{ Therefore, Arsen, or how we used to call him the 'Chef' because he was the coach of 90% of the Armenian players from my generation, played the move ...Nd7. }
17. h4
{ A tricky move! Now, if Black takes  17...Bxh4  , I'm going to play  18.g5  and the bishop is going to suffer a lot. }
17... Kh8 18. Ne3
{ Pure psychological intimidation. Right now I don't think I would ever play a move like this again, I would just go  18.Qg3  and Black is tied down to the defense of the e5-pawn.  18...Nb6  is not possible because of  19.Qxe5  . @@StartFEN@@4rr1k/ppqnbppp/2b5/2p1p3/P1N1P1PP/1BP3Q1/1P3P2/R1B1R1K1 b - - 2 18@@EndFEN@@  18...f6  is quite passive. I can lazily play for  19.f3  followed by g5 and an attack on the black king. }
18... g6
{ An inaccurate reaction. Black can just take the pawn now!  18...Bxh4  . In the game, I thought that taking the pawn is impossible and it will lead to mate after Kg2 and Rh1, but in reality, it is nothing but a mirage.  19.Nf5  Bd8  20.Kg2  g6  and here all of these  21.Rh1  illusions don't work after  21...gxf5  22.Qxf5   @@StartBracket@@Chessable note: There's a forced perpetual here with  22.Rxh7  Kxh7  23.Qxf5  Kg8  @@StartBracket@@  23...Kg7  24.Bh6+!  is mate soon@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@3brrk1/ppqn1p2/2b5/2p1pQ2/P3P1P1/1BP5/1P3PK1/R1B5 w - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24.Qg6+  Kh8  25.Qh6+=.  @@EndBracket@@  .  22...Nf6  and Black gets to attack e4. }
19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. Bxd5 Kg7 21. a5
{ Here once again, I don't know why but I was focused on provoking my opponent to take the pawn on h4, which is of course kind of intimidating but ultimately unnecessary. My position is better; I can play  21.h5  Nb6  22.Bb3  c4  23.Bc2  followed by Kg2, Rh1, and it isn't easy to understand how Black can stop the incoming kingside attack. }
21... Bxh4 22. Kg2 Nf6 23. Bb3 h5
{ But Arsen missed something here. I hope you won't miss it as well! What is wrong with ...h5? }
24. Rh1
{ What happens after  24...hxg4?  I have the beautiful  25.Bh6!Kxh6  26.Qxf6  and mate is coming. @@StartFEN@@4rr2/ppq2pk1/5npB/P1p1p3/4P1pb/1BP2Q2/1P3PK1/R6R b - - 1 25@@EndFEN@@ He has to move his king  25...Kg8  but it doesn't really matter because after  26.Qe3  , everything is falling apart. The bishop on h4 is lost.   Of course, he cannot play  24...g5  either for many reasons, but mainly I can just take  25.Rxh4  gxh4  and again  26.Bh6  Kxh6  27.Qxf6  Kh7  and I have a lot of beautiful checks followed by mating the black king. Let me show it to you:  28.Qf5  Kg7  29.Qg5  Kh7  30.Qxh5  Kg7  31.Qg5  Kh7  , and the rook comes to deliver the mate  32.Rh1! }
24... Nxg4 25. Rxh4 f5 26. Bg5
{ Now, of course, I have many options.  26.Qe2  is possible, but Black can play  26...f4  , and after  27.f3  Nf6  followed by ...g5-g4, the position becomes difficult, especially since I have a bishop stuck on c1.   My solution  26.Bg5  was much more elegant. Of course, Black can no longer play for ...f4, the best for him would have been  26...fxe4  27.Qxe4  Rxf2  28.Kg3  Rf5  . There are different ways for me to play, but the best would be  29.Rxg4  hxg4  30.Be3  and I get a risk-free big advantage.  30...Rf3  is met with  31.Kg2  and the bishop on e3 is controlling all of the entry squares. From a practical point of view, this is lost for Black. }
26... c4 27. Bc2 fxe4 28. Qxe4 Rxf2+ 29. Kg3 Rf5
{ But here, I have a very strong move that I want you all to find. } 30. Rxh5
{ We need to calculate what happens after  30...Nf2  . Although this move seems annoying, there's a very elegant solution  31.Bh6+  Kh8  32.Qxf5!  gxf5  33.Kxf2  , and Black doesn't have enough pieces to cover the incoming mate threats with the a1-rook coming to g1. }
30... Ref8
{ Now I have to find another difficult move. What do you think I should play here? }
31. Rf1
{ Crushing! Please note that we can't take the knight with  31.Kxg4  because after  31...Rf4+!  32.Bxf4  Rxf4+  33.Qxf4  gxh5+!  we can safely resign.   And if you thought  31.Qxg4  is possible, then you are also wrong  31...e4+  32.Kg2  gxh5  33.Qxh5  Rh8  and the black queen joins the game via h2, Black is winning.  But if you found Rf1 then bravo! }
31... Qf7
{ 31...gxh5  32.Rxf5  Rxf5  33.Qxf5  and the  33...e4  doesn't do anything anymore because we can just cover with the bishop or the queen. }
32. Qh1
{ There are different ways to win, but since I thought the game was aesthetic, I tried to find the most artistic way to finish the game. }
32... gxh5
{ 32...Rxf1  and Black gets checkmated after  33.Rh7  Kg8  34.Rh8  Kg7  35.Qh7  . }
33. Rxf5 Qc7 34. Qxh5
{ My dear friend and coach Arsen resigned.  I think I was being a bit too adventurous with sacrificing the pawn on h4, but in the end, it worked out because my opponent got really low on time trying to figure out the complications in the position.  Generally, if you have a good position like this one @@StartFEN@@4rr1k/ppqnbppp/2b5/2p1p3/P1N1P1PP/1BP2Q2/1P3P2/R1B1R1K1 w - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@ it is clear that White is better. You don't need to sacrifice a pawn or do something like that; just play something safe like  18.Qg3  and the position is clearly better for White. }
*


