[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Giorgi Bagaturov, Batumi 2002"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a game that I played in the European Championship in 2022 against GM Giorgi Bagaturov. It was a turbulent event for me with lots of wins and lots of losses. But a couple of games that I played here actually gave me a lot of confidence because I was playing in a positional matter.So I would like to share this game with you, which was a showcase of my improvement. Maybe not improving in big steps, but more being able to understand the beauty in simple moves. }
1. d4
{ I don't think that I have shown a game with  1.d4  so far. I was already working a lot with Gabriel Sargissian, and we decided to play lots of  1.d4  with White, and  1.e4  e5  with Black. It was a change of repertoire that slowly gave me results and started changing the way I played chess.  Being an e4-player from childhood, I could already see lots of tactics, and after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  and 2.g3 I had also learned to maneuver. Hence, I needed something in the middle, which was what  1.d4  did for me.My opponent was and still is, a very solid player. }
1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 { This is the Queenâs Indian Defense. } 4. g3 Bb7
{ 4...Ba6  is far more popular. When I think about this move I always wonder what kind of genius you have to be to come up with a move like this. To me, this is absolutely absurd. The level of understanding of chess.I think that it was Nimzowitsch who came up with this move in the 20s.  4...Ba6  is basically saying that any move you play with White here, be it  5.Qc2  ,  5.Qb3  ,  5.Qa4  ,  5.Nbd2  , or  5.b3  it is actually worsening your position. In most of these lines, Black moves the bishop back to b7.  5...Bb7  ,  which means that in the position after 4...Ba6, White's pieces are ideal.And when I think of it, it actually impresses me so much. I get really emotional thinking about the fact that someone sat there, understanding that this position for White is actually better than what it can become.   I mean, just look at this  5...Bb4+  6.Bd2  and  6...Be7  line with a similar idea. Someone understood that the bishop is better on c1 than on d2. And quite often you will see White play something like  7.Bg2  c6  8.O-O  d5  when White tries to play for Bc1 @@StartBracket@@or Bc3@@EndBracket@@ and Bb2 to bring the bishop back. This is absurdly deep for humans, with even the computer confirming  that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p1pp1ppp/1p2pn2/8/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ba6  is the best move. }
5. Bg2 Be7
{ For me, it's important to share the beauty that I see in the game with all of you because I think that this is something that is not being talked about enough. It is something that we already see as a common thing, we accepted that ...Ba6 is obvious.If we take just five seconds and think about this whole concept we'll understand that this is insane. This is as deep as Beethoven's String Quartet or Mozart's Piano Concertos. A revelation, and depth in the development of a human being, which is an achievement in our field. These things can put the game of chess a bit further, closer to culture and philosophy than just any kind of game. }
6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Bd2
{ This is more or less a solid way to approach the opening. Quite often we're told that knights are worse than the bishops and that we shouldn't give up our bishops. But everything is relative to what you're going to get for it.For example, here a move like  8.Bd2  when you can of course take the bishop with  8...Nxd2  immediately gives me the center.  9.Qxd2  ,  I will get to play e4 and your bishop on b7 will become a passive piece. Therefore, 8...Nxd2 doesn't really give Black two great bishops. Technically, Black has the advantage of the two bishops, but the bishops are worse here than White's two knights. }
8... f5 { This was the theory back then. } 9. Rc1 Bf6 10. d5
{ I knew that it's possible to play  10.d5  and then slowly try to play a3 and b4. I didn't know much more than that, but this is something I knew. }
10... Na6
{ A decent move.   One possible move for Black would have been  10...c5  ,  which looks strange, but Black is slowly preparing to take on c3 and d5.   If you try to immediately go for  10...Bxc3  11.Bxc3  exd5  12.cxd5  ,  it's clear that the c7-pawn is a bit backwards.  12...c5  dxc6  .  Once the position opens the white pieces are far better developed.   A move like  10...c5  is a slower approach and quite possible. I looked this up after the game, and I remember that my old notes mention that  11.Bf4  is interesting. The idea is  11...Bxc3  12.Rxc3  Nxc3  13.bxc3  trying to establish control over the dark squares. My notes said  13...Na6   13...exd5  as is normal in these types of structures, leads to disaster after  14.Ng5  because the pin is pretty crazy, and White becomes too active.  14.Bd6  Rf6  15.Ne5  with clear compensation. I don't know if this works out, but it does look very interesting. White is trying to play g4 or e4 and open up the position. There are lots of tactics, which is something I always liked. The vicious tricks, as I call them. }
11. a3 c6
{ Now of course I don't want to sacrifice any pawns so I took on c6. } 12. dxc6
{ The reason why I took  12.dxc6  and not on e6 is a practical one. I want to make my opponent think for a little longer. It's quite useful when you see that  12...Bxc6  gives me nice play after  13.b4  .   I thought that if I play  12.dxe6  ,  he will immediately recapture.  12...dxe6  . But if I play  12.dxc6  , he might think that I'm making a mistake and that  12...Bxc6  might be an extra option. That way you win a bit of time, sometimes even two to three minutes, by giving your opponent these silly choices. I'm sharing all my brilliant tricks with all of you, including a bit of practical wisdom. }
12... dxc6 13. b4
{ What I'm doing has so far been quite normal. I'm trying to at some point play c5 to lock up his b7-bishop. If I manage this, even with a sacrifice, it would make sense if I can stop Black from playing ...c5. }
13... c5
{ My opponent played  13...c5  immediately, which is a very good move.   13...Nxd2  is also possible.  14.Nxd2  Qe7  ,  but I think that I can maybe already try  15.c5  here. It might be a bit risky, and I definitely can, but otherwise, I can try to play  15.e4  here to open up the position.If I play something slow, I think that Black manages to play ...c5 to easily equalize. I will definitely have to immediately try something because after a move like  15.Qc2  Black is fine. }
14. Nxe4 fxe4
{ 14...Bxe4  is also possible, but is a more passive move because I can always play something like  15.Bf4  or  15.b5  Nc7  16.Bf4  and create some threats against the knight.   So  14...fxe4  is more direct and a clearly better move, and it is what my opponent played. }
15. Ne1 cxb4 { This was a good move. } 16. axb4
{ This position is very concrete. Black is not in time to play against White's weaknesses. The fact that White's pieces are on the first rank and not really developed yet plays a role. If my e1-knight would have already been on c3, the position is lost for Black because the e4 and e6-pawns are very weak.   At this moment my opponent had to think. What is the problem of White's pawns, and which pawn is more vulnerable? I have these pawns on b4 and c4 that needs to be attacked, and the best way for him to do so would be with  16...Qd6  when I will have to play  17.b5  .   I cannot really play  17.Nc2  because of  17...Rad8  and because of the bishop being attacked.  18.Be3  Qc7  I'm losing on c4  19.Qe1  Qxc4  which leads to a disaster.  And after  17...Nc5  ,  Black has comfortable play because he has protected his main weaknesses @@StartBracket@@e4 and e6@@EndBracket@@ with the c5-knight. Following  18.Bf4  Qxd1  19.Rxd1  a6  ,  Black doesn't have any big problems. It's an equal position, where I of course keep my trumps because I also don't have any major weaknesses in the position. }
16... Rc8
{ My opponent committed a positional blunder which allowed me to improve my position. }
17. Bh3
{ Immediately underlying the problem. Black can no longer play  17...Qd6  because I have this tactical idea  18.Bf4  Qxd1  19.Bxe6  and then capture the queen after which I have an extra pawn. }
17... Qe7 { What do you think I played next? } 18. Ng2
{ I can't really play  18.Nc2  because of the hanging c4-pawn.  With  18.Ng2  ,  I'm bringing the knight to e3 or f4 through Ng2. This Bh3 and Ng2 idea is extremely good for me, and White has a clearly better position after it. }
18... Rcd8 19. Qe1
{ If I play now  19.Qc2  ,  he will take on b4  19...Nxb4  and get some counterplay. }
19... Be5
{ Here I played a move that I'm very proud of, and I think that these kinds of moves are good to make. Once you learn to play like that you'll become a good player and will slowly improve. I want all of you to tell me which move I played here.   If you thought that the answer is  20.c5  â  No, not really. It looks tempting, and I'm playing for some tactics, but it's not a big deal.  20...bxc5  21.bxc5  Nxc5  22.Bb4  Bd6  ,  and Black gets chances for a draw.   If you believe that it is  20.Ne3  ,  you have found a normal move, but you have to come up with a concept here. What do I want to do? Which pieces do I want to exchange, or which pieces do I want to activate? Right now, we have a problem. Our b4-pawn is hanging, and playing  20.b5  is anti-positional.  20...Nc5  .   But at the same time, we want to activate our pieces.  20.Ne3  is a possibility, but there is a better idea. Ne3 does not accomplish what I want to.What I want to do is remove his only active piece in the position. Make his other pieces understand that there is no future in there, just move along and find another target for yourself. The active piece is of course the bishop on e5.If we play something like  20.Bc3  ,  the same problem appears.  20...Bxc3  21.Qxc3  Nxb4  .  Black just takes on b4, and I don't want that. }
20. Rb1
{ I played this good move. Nothing dramatic is happening to my position, Black doesn't really attack c4, so I can afford to play slow.I'm just preparing Bc3, and if you retreat after that, then my bishop becomes way too powerful on the diagonal. And if you don't retreat, I remove your only active piece. }
20... Rc8
{ The position is already quite unpleasant for Black. He should probably have tried to play something like  20...Qf6  ,  but it's clear that I have accomplished a lot here. I can play  21.Nf4  and Black cannot really take on f4 because of  21...Bxf4   And after, for example,  21...Rd6  ,  he has to really watch out for tactics.  22.c5  bxc5  23.bxc5  Nxc5  24.Bb4  ,  so he might lose some material on the spot  24...Bxf4  25.Bxc5  and because of the pins and weak position of his pieces, the position is unpleasant.  22.Bxf4  and I'm better.   Another way I can also play after  20...Qf6  is  21.Ne3  when I'm threatening to play Ng4.  But  21.Nf4  is probably stronger  because of the c5 ideas. }
21. Bc3 Qf6
{ In hindsight, it would probably have been better for Black to play  21...Bd6  when after  22.Ne3  ,  the position is a bit passive for Black.   But there are more chances.  22...Rfd8  to continue playing and not allowing White to immediately activate here. b4 is still hanging, so I probably need to play something like  23.Rb3  and then Qb1. It's a big advantage for White, but White still needs to slowly untie.   In the game, after  21...Qf6  , I just took. }
22. Bxe5 Qxe5 23. Ne3
{ The real problem with the e5-bishop disappearing is my e3-knight becoming a monster. You cannot touch it with pawns, you cannot touch it with the rooks, you cannot even touch it with the knight.In order for the knight to come and try to attack my e3-knight, Black needs to spend 5 moves @@StartBracket@@...Nc7-e8-d6-f5@@EndBracket@@, which is too much. The position is too open, and these weaknesses @@StartBracket@@the pawns on e4 and e6@@EndBracket@@ will not allow Black to do that. Therefore, White is already winning.   After a simple move like @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/pb2q1pp/np2p3/4b3/1PP1p3/6PB/3BPPNP/2R1QRK1 w - - 7 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Rb1  , you can actually get such a nice position because once you address the main problem in the position, the weaknesses begin appearing and the position will collapse. }
23... Nb8 24. Qd2
{ What I had in mind was to meet  24...Nc6  with  25.Qd7  .  I don't want to let my opponent get any activity, and at the same time I'm also threatening some tactical ideas like Qb2. After you exchange the queens, I can again take on e6 with check. Black's position is completely hopeless. }
24... Rfe8
{ I found the most elegant move here, which I hope you will also find. How does White immediately benefit from the passivity of Black's pieces? }
25. c5
{ I'm now also threatening to play Nc4 and the knight can enter on d6. I'm getting my pawn on the dark squares, and will then try to remove his only good piece, the queen on e5. }
25... bxc5 26. bxc5 Bc6
{ It didn't really matter if he played  26...Bc6  or  26...Ba8  . } 27. Qd6
{ The queen is Black's only active piece. What is going to happen after its disappearance? Everything is going to be up for grabs, which is what happened. }
27... Qxd6
{ After  27...Nd7  28.Ra1  Rc7  ,  I have a gazillion ways to take advantage of his passive position. I can play  29.Ra5  here and then bring in another rook. It's an almost losing position.  29.Rfb1  is also good enough. }
28. cxd6 a5
{ At least he tried to get his pawn somewhere. Black doesn't have any trumps or ideas in the position. }
29. Rfc1 Nd7
{ Unfortunately for Black, if he tries to activate his knight to c6, there is nobody left to protect e4. There are all these issues, the position is just structurally losing. }
30. Rc3 Kf7 31. Rbc1 Ne5
{ And then I just used the fact that his bishop is pinned. } 32. Bg2
{ And Bxe4 is coming. Black is slowly losing his weaknesses. The problem is that once you lose these weaknesses, my pieces will be super dominant on those squares. As the game shows, the bishop on e4 is going to cut the board in half. }
32... Bd7 33. Bxe4
{ I'm threatening f4, to push the knight away because the knight doesn't have many squares. }
33... Rxc3 34. Rxc3 Rc8 { Of course, everything wins here for White. } 35. Rxc8
Bxc8 36. f4 Nd7
{ 36...Ng6  is about the same. I still have  37.Nc4  a4  when I can just bring my king and easily win the game. }
37. Nc4 Ba6
{ After  37...a4  ,  I can play  38.Bc6  and if you play  38...Nc5  ,  there are many moves to win. The easiest is probably  39.Kf2  .  The knight will go to a3, and the king can move to e3 and d4.  39...Ba6  40.Na3  is fairly easy, but 37...a4 would at least have been more resilient.   Chessable note: Perhaps an easier winning plan could be @@StartFEN@@2b5/5kpp/2BPp3/2n5/p1N2P2/6P1/4P2P/6K1 w - - 2 39@@EndFEN@@  39.e4  ,  intending to give extra support to the pawn on d6 with a subsequent e5 followed by the king's march towards the center.  39.Kf2  looks good as well, but after  39...Ba6  , White has to play  40.Ne5+   40.Na3  runs into  40...Bb7  and the d6-pawn falls.  For instance,  41.Bb5  Ne4+  solves Black's problems.  40...Kf6  41.g4  , planning to mate the king rather than promote. An illustrative line is  41...h6  42.h4  and if Black gets promoting ideas with  42...a3  , White has something stronger in return.  43.g5+  Kf5  44.Ke3  a2  45.Be8  and mate can't be stopped. }
38. Nxa5 Bxe2 39. Kf2 Bg4 40. Nc4 Kf6 41. Ne5
{ My opponent resigned.The reason why this game went wrong for Black was that he should have tried to attack the weakest pawn, instead of playing a natural move like @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb4pp/np2pb2/8/1PP1p3/6P1/3BPPBP/2RQNRK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Rc8  ,  which was a really bad decision.Black should have played  16...Qd6  immediately whenever he could to quickly activate his pieces and at least get some squares under his control before I get fully active.   @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb4pp/np2pb2/8/1PP1p3/6P1/3BPPBP/2RQNRK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@Once he missed this idea of  16...Rc8  17.Bh3  Qe7  18.Ng2  Rcd8  19.Qe1  ,  the position became difficult.  19...Be5  .  Here I showed patience. I was not looking to immediately crush him with c5 ideas. I played  20.Rb1  ,  which was an extremely good decision that allowed me to take full control over the game.After his mistake, my play was very good and simple, which quite often is the way to go. If your position is strategically good, you shouldn't rush. It's your opponent who should try to create some counterplay. I don't really have weaknesses, Black has weaknesses. He has doubled pawns, both of which are isolated, and he has to play very fast while I can afford to play slowly. }
*


