[SetUp "1"]

16. axb4
{ This position is very concrete. Black is not in time to play against White's weaknesses. The fact that White's pieces are on the first rank and not really developed yet plays a factor. If my e1-knight would have already been on c3, the position is lost for Black because the e4 and e6-pawns are very weak.At this moment my opponent had to think. What is the problem of White's pawns, and which pawn is more vulnerable? I have these pawns on b4 and c4 that need to be attacked. What would be the best way for him to do so? }
16... Qd6 17. Nc2 Rad8
{ Showcasing the downside of Nc2 â the bishop is being attacked. } 18. Be3 Qc7
19. Qe1 Qxc4 { I'm losing the c4-pawn, which leads to disaster. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Giorgi Bagaturov â Puzzle #7"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pb4pp/np2pb2/8/1PP1p3/6P1/3BPPBP/2RQNRK1 b - - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

16... Rc8
{ My opponent committed a positional blunder which allowed me to improve my position. How did I do that? }
17. Bh3 { Immediately underlying the problem. } 17... Qd6
{ Black can no longer defend like this because I have a tactical idea. } 18.
Bf4 Qxd1 19. Bxe6+ Kh8 20. Rxd1 { And I have an extra pawn. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Giorgi Bagaturov â Puzzle #8"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/pb4pp/np2pb2/8/1PP1p3/6PB/3BPP1P/2RQNRK1 b - - 2 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

17... Qe7 { What do you think I played next? } 18. Ng2
{ I can't really play  18.Nc2  because of the hanging c4-pawn.  Hence,  18.Ng2  ,  I'm bringing the knight to e3 or f4 through Ng2. This Bh3 and Ng2 idea is extremely good for me, and White has a clearly better position after it. }
18... Rcd8 19. Qe1
{ If I now play  19.Qc2  ,  he will take on b4  19...Nxb4  and get some counterplay. }
19... Be5
{ Here I played a move that I'm very proud of, and I think that these kinds of moves are good to make. Once you learn to play like that you'll become a good player and will slowly improve. I want all of you to tell me which move I played here.   If you thought that the answer is  20.c5  â  No, not really. It looks tempting, and I'm playing for some tactics, but it's not a big deal.  20...bxc5  21.bxc5  Nxc5  22.Bb4  Bd6  ,  and Black gets chances for a draw.   If you believe that it is  20.Ne3  ,  you have found a normal move, but you have to come up with a concept here. What do I want to do? Which pieces do I want to exchange, or which pieces do I want to activate? Right now, we have a problem. Our b4-pawn is hanging, and playing  20.b5  is anti-positional.  20...Nc5  .   But at the same time, we want to activate our pieces.  20.Ne3  is a possibility, but there is a better idea. Ne3 does not accomplish what I want to.What I want to do is remove his only active piece in the position. Make his other pieces understand that there is no future in there, just move along and find another target for yourself. The active piece is of course the bishop on e5.If we play something like  20.Bc3  ,  the same problem appears.  20...Bxc3  21.Qxc3  Nxb4  .  Black just takes on b4, and I don't want that. }
20. Rb1
{ I played this good move. Nothing dramatic is happening to my position, Black doesn't really attack c4, so I can afford to play slow.I'm just preparing Bc3, and if you retreat after that, then my bishop becomes way too powerful on the diagonal. And if you don't retreat, I remove your only active piece. }
*


