[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Rufat Bagirov, Batumi 2002"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was also played in the Individual Chess Championship, in Batumi 2002. I played a positional game and I was happy to see that my playing style was not limited to creating complications. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Ragozin Variation was named after GM Viacheslav Ragozin, who was Botvinnik's coach. GM Alexandrov employed this opening before it was adopted more broadly. I used to play it as Black too since it's a very interesting, strategic weapon. }
5. Bg5 Nbd7
{ 5...h6  is the main response for Black these days, or they go into the Vienna with  5...dxc4  , as I do quite often myself. }
6. cxd5 exd5 7. Qc2
{ This is one of many of Kramnik's opening concepts. The idea is that after  7.e3  c5  8.Bd3  @@StartBracket@@or  8.dxc5  Qa5  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1n1ppp/5n2/2pp2B1/1b1P4/2NBPN2/PP3PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qa5  9.O-O  c4  10.Bf5  O-O  ,  the position gets sharp. I've played this position with both colors. }
7... O-O
{ With the pawn still on e2, White has  7...c5  8.dxc5  Qa5  9.Bd2  and only then play e2-e3, playing against the bishop on b4.   Preventing Bd2 with  7...h6  8.Bh4  c5  9.e3  Qa5  weakens the f5-square after, for example,  10.Bd3  O-O  11.O-O  c4  12.Bf5  when Black doesn't have ...g6. }
8. a3 { 8.e3  c5  transposes to 7.e3. } 8... Bxc3+
{ 8...Be7  9.e3  transposes to the Queen's Gambit Declined @@StartBracket@@Exchange Variation@@EndBracket@@ with the extra tempo a2-a3 for White, which can be useful when starting a minority attack on the queenside â one of White's main ideas in this variation. }
9. Qxc3 h6
{ I've played  9...c6  in this position, as I prefer to keep ...h6 in reserve. }
10. Bh4 c6
{ 10...c5  is also possible, but it's very concrete. After  11.e3  ,  the main question is if ...g5 followed by ...Ne4 works for Black:  11...g5  12.Bg3  Ne4  13.Qc2  Qa5+  14.Nd2â  , such positions can also arise from the Nimzo-Indian Defense. }
11. Nd2
{ Black is trying to play ...Qe8 and ...Ne4.   White has to play accurately so that the game won't water down. For example, after  11.e3  Qe8  12.Nd2  Ne4  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Bg3  Qd8  ,  the knight is coming to d5 and there's not much life left in the position. }
11... Qe8
{ The same idea  11...g5  12.Bg3  Ne4  doesn't work as nicely for Black anymore since the knight can simply be traded.  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.h4  and White easily gets the initiative. }
12. f3
{ I'm slowly trying to bring out my pieces, without allowing any counterplay. }
12... Qe6
{ 12...Qe7  was a better move, to keep ...c5 in the wings.  13.e3  Re8  14.Bf2  c5  15.Bd3  cxd4  16.Qxd4  Ne5  Black gets some activity. }
13. e3 b6
{ I knew that there was a game from Karpov that went  13...Nb6  . Black played some strange moves and after  14.Bf2  Nh5  15.g4  Nf4  16.O-O-O  Ng6  17.Bd3  ,  White was much better but the game eventually ended in a draw @@StartBracket@@Karpov-Milov, Buenos Aires 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
14. Be2 Re8 15. Bf2
{ White has the two bishops and if I manage to castle and bring the bishop to c2 @@StartBracket@@Bd1-c2@@EndBracket@@, I will be slightly better. Black has to act now. }
15... c5
{ 15...a5!  16.O-O  Ba6  17.Bxa6  Rxa6  .  Black slowly tries to play for ...c5. White is still slightly better, I can still play for b2-b4, but it's not such a big deal.   15...a5!  is a big improvement over the game. Exchange your bad pieces when you can, you may not get a second chance... }
16. O-O Bb7
{ 16...a5  is too late now.  17.b4  Ba6  18.b5  Bb7  19.Rfe1  and Black didn't manage to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
17. b3
{ A pretty good move. Black is trying to stop e3-e4.   After the normal continuation  17.Rfe1  Rac8  18.Nf1  , I have to take into account that Black can play  18...c4  . He gets some counterplay after  19.Ng3  b5  20.Bd1  Qb6  21.Bc2  a5  when Black is in time with ...b4. }
17... Rac8 18. Rfe1
{ I'm trying to bring my knight to f5 @@StartBracket@@Nf1-g3-f5@@EndBracket@@, supported by the bishop on d3. }
18... cxd4
{ Black can't play for ...b4 anymore. After  18...a6  19.Nf1  c4  20.bxc4  dxc4  21.e4  ,  my center is too strong. }
19. Qxd4 { The d4-square is mine. } 19... Qc6 20. Nf1 Qc3 21. Rab1
{ I was enjoying this type of slow play. } 21... Nf8
{ After  21...Qxd4  22.exd4  Nf8  23.Ne3  Ne6  24.Nf5  ,  I have the two bishops, I got rid of the weak e3-pawn and my knight is well placed on f5. }
22. Qxc3 Rxc3 23. Ng3
{ Now the position is difficult for Black: I'm threatening to play Bb5 and Nf5-d4. It may appear as if Black played solidly in this game, but he missed his chance to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...a5 and ...Ba6, or he should have played for ...c5 earlier. He was simply too passive. }
23... g6 24. Bb5
{ Once you have missed your chance to exchange a certain piece @@StartBracket@@the light-squared bishops@@EndBracket@@, you might be stuck with it for the whole game. }
24... Rec8 25. Ne2 R3c5
{ 25...Rc2  doesn't achieve much:  26.Nd4  Ra2  27.Ra1  and the b5-bishop is still dominating. }
26. a4 Ne6 27. Bg3
{ The best player is joining the game.  Boris Gelfand is a big fan of Lionel Messi. He noted that in the first 10 minutes of his matches, he is not creating any chances at all, instead, he is studying the structure of the opposing team, and only after 15 minutes, does he become dangerous â he already knows what is happening.  The same applies to my dark-squared bishop here.   I didn't see any reason to commit to  27.e4  R5c7  28.e5  Nd7  29.Nd4  Ndc5  when Black's knight solidly blockade the center. }
27... a6 28. Bd3 a5 29. h4
{ A very strong prophylactic move.   Generally speaking, I do want to play  29.Nd4  , but the problem is that my bishop doesn't find a good square after  29...Nxd4  30.exd4  Rc3  31.Bf1  Nh5  32.Bd6  Ng7  . Black will continue to harass my bishop with ...Nf5. }
29... Nd7
{ With  29...h5  included, the same sequence  30.Nd4  Nxd4  31.exd4  Rc3  32.Bf1  works perfectly for White: there is no ...Nh5 anymore. }
30. h5 g5
{ 30...gxh5  31.Nd4  and now that I permanently have access to the f5-square, I'm completely winning. }
31. Nd4
{ Black's position is lost â his bishop will never see the light of day. }
31... Nxd4 32. exd4 Rc3 33. Bf5 Rd8 34. Rbc1 Rxc1
{ 34...Rxb3?  35.Rc7  wins material after  35...Bc8  36.Rec1  . } 35. Rxc1 Nf6
36. Bc7 Re8 37. g4 { Threatening Be5. The game is effectively over. } 37... Bc8
38. Bd3 Re3 39. Be5 Be6
{ 39...Rxd3  is one of those well-known tricks:  40.Rxc8+  Kg7  41.Rc6  Rxf3  42.Rxf6  Rxf6  and Black is in zugzwang after any move, for example  43.Kg2  . }
40. Bf5 Ne8
{ 40...Bxf5  41.gxf5  Ne8  42.Kf2  Rxb3  43.Rc8  followed by f6 and Bd6+ wins the knight. }
41. Bxe6 fxe6 42. Rc6 Kf7 { 42...Rxb3  43.Rxe6  Kf7  44.Rxh6+- } 43. Rxb6 Rxf3
44. Kg2 Rc3 45. Rb5 Ke7 { 45...Nf6  46.Rb7++- } 46. Rxa5
{ The remaining moves weren't necessary. } 46... Rxb3 47. Ra7+ Kf8 48. a5 Rb2+
49. Kf3 Ra2 50. Ke3 Ra3+ 51. Kd2 Rf3 52. a6 Ra3 53. Kc2
{ Conclusion: You can play solid openings but you always need to have some kind of counterplay. You can't stay passive all game and hope for the draw â this is a losing strategy.   One way of creating counterplay was @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/p2n1pp1/1pp1qn1p/3p4/3P4/P1Q1PP2/1P1NBBPP/R3K2R b KQ - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15...a5  16.O-O  Ba6  followed by ...c5.  @@StartFEN@@2r1r1k1/pb1n1pp1/1p2qn1p/2pp4/3P4/PPQ1PP2/3NBBPP/R3R1K1 b - - 2 18@@EndFEN@@  18...cxd4  was a remarkably poor decision too: Black was extremely passive in the endgame and after I managed to bring my knight to f5, he was lost. }
