[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Sergei Movsesian, Bundesliga 2002"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is one of the games that gave me confidence, played in 2002 against Sergei Movsesian, who was much higher rated than me at that point. Thanks to my coach, Arshak Petrosian, and his advice, I've always tried to improve my chess by facing stronger opposition.  Guided by my trainer, when an opportunity came to play in the Bundesliga, money was not what mattered most. On the contrary, I thought that it would be better for me if I could play on the first board and be paid less, a scenario not so easy to achieve when there were three other higher-rated and more experienced players on the team.  Luckily, the very nice person and head of the Wattenscheid team, Ulrich Wolf, believed in me immediately, and I got the chance to play on the top board for that wonderful club, where I had to deal with tough encounters. As I was facing very strong players all the time like Movsesian, Almasi, and Beliavsky, I also had to step up my game and cut my teeth in those clashes. }
1. c4
{ At that time I was playing mostly  1.c4  or  1.d4  , and I knew that Movsesian is a King's Indian player, an opening that would have probably appeared on the board since he was going to try and get a complicated but fighting game against me. }
1... Nf6 2. Nc3 c6 3. e4 d6
{ Movsesian is inviting me to play d4, which happens to be the best move as well, but I had different plans, similar to the ones employed by Ara Minasian against me, and worked like a charm. I'll return to this later on. }
4. Nf3 g6 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O e5
{ Very natural for the King's Indian. } 8. h3 Nbd7 9. d3
{ Normally, everybody goes  9.d4  here, but I wanted to try out the same strategy adopted by my friend, GM Ara Minasian. I thought that could work beautifully on someone who is unaware of it, so let's see it first in order for you to be able to compare.  I was Black against Minasian and that game went @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  Nf6  2.Nc3  c6  3.e4  d6  4.g3  e5  5.Bg2  Be7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  Nbd7  8.d3  .  I don't remember the exact moves, but I just want to show you White's idea.  8...Re8  9.h3  Bf8  10.Rb1  a6  11.b4  b6  12.Ne1  b5  .  After  13.a4  , I got a really bad position.  13...bxc4  14.dxc4  Nb6  15.b5  .  In the game, I took on c4, after which White got complete control over the position thanks to the strong outpost on d5.  To recap: instead of pushing d4, White has the idea of placing the pawn on d3 and going for b4 instead, planning to further meet ...b5 with a4. You might be surprised, but I won 6 games with this idea, which I casually learned in a game against my friend. I took this knowledge and applied it successfully in events where the stakes were higher than the one against my compatriot. }
9... Ne8
{ Since the structure is similar, I was ready to meet  9...a6  with  10.b4  b5  11.a4  , trying to get the same idea in. }
10. Bg5
{ I found this idea during the game, to play  Be3  ,  Qd2  , and  Ne2  and I will show you one more example of applied knowledge. It is from a completely different opening, but I just want to emphasize how interchangeable information can be. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.c3  Nf6  4.Be2  g6  5.O-O  Bg7  6.d3  O-O  7.Be3  Nc6  8.Nbd2  e5  9.a3  h6  10.h3  Nh5  .  This is what most players do and both Korobov and Wojtaszek employed this idea recently against me.   10...Nh7  â the bishop on e3 is luring Black to play ...f5, which I believe is a weakening reaction.  11.b4  f5  12.exf5  gxf5  13.Nb3  f4  14.Bd2  b6  15.Nh2  .  I got this type of structure often in blitz games when Black's life is not so simple. Of course, you can use a bit of imagination since the positions were not precisely what we have on the board. My intention is to reveal the thought process behind my strategy and the spirit of my play.  11.b4  b6  12.b5  Na5  13.Re1  ,  anticipating ...Nf4.  13...Nf4  14.Bf1  Ne6  15.c4  f5  16.Nb1  .  I just wanted to provoke ...f5, to weaken Black's structure and get complete control over the d5-square. Once again, disregard the exact moves or the engine's evaluation, it's all about the ideas that you can learn from one game and apply in another. }
10... f6 11. Be3
{ With my Bg5-Be3 maneuver, I am inviting Black to push ...f5, which I believe will weaken Black's structure. }
11... f5 12. Qd2 Qf6 13. exf5 gxf5 14. Ne2
{ Trying to get d4 in, followed by Nh4 and f3. Sergei was burning a lot of time on the clock at this moment, trying to find a way to complicate the game in order to win it, as he was the higher-rated player. I could sense his disbelief in my d3 planning, not knowing that actually, this was going to be my main weapon against the King's Indian at that time. }
14... Nc7
{ Not the best reaction.  14...Nc5  was preferable, rerouting the knight via e6 to f4. However, after  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.d4  Ne4  17.dxe5  Nxd2  18.Bxd2  dxe5  , Black has to be ready to play for equality, a concession that probably was not on Movsesian's radar since he was trying to play for a win. }
15. d4 e4
{ Once again, Black had the same idea of  15...Ne6  , but still has to reckon with  16.d5  cxd5  17.cxd5  Nec5  18.Ng5  , planning f4. Black has to react fast.  18...h6  19.Ne6  Nxe6  20.dxe6  Nb6  21.Bxb6  axb6  22.Qxd6  Bxe6  .  Black has good pieces and plans to throw in ...e4, with an equal position. Following  23.Bd5  Bxd5  24.Qxd5+  Qf7  , it is perhaps easier to play with White, but objectively, the game should end in a draw. }
16. Nh4 { And I've just got what I was looking for. } 16... d5 17. Bg5
{ A bit of a cautious move. I should have tried to play  17.f3  or  17.Nf4  Nb6  18.b3  , but I wasn't sure if the pawn is hanging or not, so I tried to stop this ...Nb6 idea from the first place. }
17... Qe6
{ Probably, Movsesian was worried about my f3 idea, but from this moment on, the game was very smooth for me.   I was ready to meet  17...Qf7  with  18.c5  when White does keep some advantage. @@StartBracket@@After  18.f3  e3  , the position becomes balanced.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppnn1qbp/2p5/2Pp1pB1/3Pp2N/6PP/PP1QNPB1/R4RK1 b - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Ne6  19.Be3  Black is a bit stuck here, while I am simply planning to go f3 and open up the f-file. Black cannot really stop White's plan and after, for instance,  19...b6  20.f3  , we get a sharp and probably balanced position. }
18. Bf4 { A strong reply. } 18... Ne8 19. cxd5 cxd5 20. Rac1
{ White just occupied the open file, while Black is still not fully developed and there is f3 in the pipeline too. }
20... Nb6
{ 20...Nef6  21.Bh6  and after the exchange of bishops, Nf4 followed by f3 will start asking the black king some very tough questions. }
21. b3
{ We have a coach in Armenia whose students always place their knights on b6 or b3 and after ...b6 they start thinking about what to do next. The same applies here: b3 is a very natural move, depriving the b6-knight of any squares. }
21... Bd7 22. a4
{ Taking control of the b5-square and preventing any ...Bb5 incursion. } 22...
Bc6 23. f3
{ I am never going to take on e4, but what is my plan then? Yes, g4 is coming when my knight will receive a beautiful outpost on f5. }
23... Nf6
{ Trying to stop g4, as Black will have the intermediate ...exf3 and g4 will be hanging. }
24. Be5 Nh5
{ Preventing Nf4. Black cannot play  24...exf3  since after  25.Nf4  Qd7  26.Bxf3  Ne4  27.Bxe4  fxe4  28.Nh5  , White gets a deadly attack. }
25. g4 fxg4 26. hxg4 Bh6 27. Qe1
{ Black is hoping for  27.g5  Bg7  when the knight's position is secured on h5. }
27... Ng7
{ It is rather obvious that taking an exchange backfires.  27...Bxc1  28.Qxc1  Ng7  29.Qg5  .  White's initiative can no longer be slowed down by Black. }
28. Rc3
{ It is not clear what Black is going to do, while I have an easy plan: take on g7, bring the knight to f5, then Nf4, fxe4 â everything is coming my way. }
28... exf3 { Trying to minimize the damage. } 29. Rcxf3 Rxf3 30. Rxf3 Nd7
{ 30...Qxg4  is not working due to  31.Rg3  .  All the pieces are joining the attack in one united effort, which is not so surprising given the status of Black's pieces on the queenside, playing the spectator's role. }
31. Bxg7 Bxg7 32. Nf5
{ In order to challenge the very strong knight on f5, Black could try to reroute the pieces with ...Nf6, ...Bd7, but there's just not enough time for it. }
32... Re8
{ My opponent tried to put up resistance by sacrificing the queen.   A@@EndBracket@@  32...Nf6  33.Re3  Ne4  34.Nf4  Qf7  35.Nxd5  or  35.Bxe4  followed by Nh5. White has way too many threats and Black's position is beyond repair.   B@@EndBracket@@  32...Kh8  was the toughest defense but after  33.Qf2  , preparing Nf4,  33...Bh6  is a sad necessity.  34.Nf4  Bxf4  35.Rxf4  and Black's problems are still there. Given the passive bishop on c6 and White's active pieces, this position is objectively lost for Black. }
33. Re3 Qxe3+
{ What else?  33...Qg6  runs into  34.Ne7+  and if @@StartFEN@@4r1k1/pp1n2bp/2b1q3/3p1N2/P2P2P1/1P2R3/4N1B1/4Q1K1 b - - 3 33@@EndFEN@@  33...Qf7  White is winning anyway with  34.Nd6  . }
34. Nxe3 Rxe3 35. Qf2 { Activating the queen. } 35... Rxb3 36. Qf5
{ Black's position is falling apart. The rest is just a matter of technique. }
36... Re3 37. Bxd5+ Bxd5 38. Qxd5+ Kf8 39. Qxd7 Rxe2 40. Qf5+ Ke7 41. Qxh7 Kf8
42. Qf5+ Kg8 43. d5 Bd4+ 44. Kf1
{ My opponent resigned since after  44...Rf2+  , getting the queen back is nice, but at the end of the day, I'll receive another one by promoting one of the pawns.  45.Qxf2  Bxf2  46.Kxf2  with a winning pawn endgame.  I wanted to show you this game to illustrate how random intel can be applied in a different game or even structure, as knowledge is empowering. By continuously learning new things, you can make further progress. Even if we are talking about a simul, I always try to play something that I don't know and perhaps use the fresh ideas in another game.  In fact, I found many ideas when I was simply having dinner alone. You will be surprised how many plans and solutions you can find if you want to find them. Of course, you might argue that I am a professional and I understand what is good or what is wrong in a certain position, but you can use the computer too or a coach, to discover which ideas are viable and which ones are not. In this game, it became apparent that my opponent didn't know how to react against the  d3  idea, which is why the game went so easy for me. }
