[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Luke McShane, Goa 2002"]
[Result "*"]

{ I am going to show you my game against Luke McShane, an extremely talented player from England, and one of the few people that left chess when he was actually very good at it. He won the World Championship U10 in Duisburg  (where I also played)  , a title which brought him to television and got to face Kasparov, followed by a scholarship, and then... he didn't play for many years. This was his comeback to tournament life, an event that had a completely different story for me.  It was my last U20 and one year before that I moved to Germany where I was wondering if it wouldn't be better to go and study instead. As my coach bluntly put it, my 2580 rating at the age of 20 was nothing special since that wasn't enough to bring me into the top 100. While for McShane this tournament marked his return to chess, for me was a farewell and I decided to simply enjoy it.  We were in Goa, where I was going out with my friends every night and appreciating the feeling of playing the competition in a relaxed manner. And suddenly, I started winning almost every game, which brought my hope back! Winning the U20 World Championship back in the day meant a lot, as the winner would receive invitations to other strong events, and that, eventually, changed my fate.  I cherish the days I've spent in Goa not only because I won the tournament but also because I simply had a wonderful time. This game was played in round 6 and my preparation was to spend my time in the swimming pool... I knew he was going to play the King's Indian and that went well for me. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 Rb8 8. d5
Na5
{ This is also what I played against Nevednichy, a game we've checked previously. }
9. b3
{ For this encounter, I wondered why not go for the text move instead of  13.Nd2  . }
9... c6
{ 9...Ne4  is not possible in view of  10.Nxe4  Bxa1  11.Bd2  with a double attack.   Against  9...c6  or  9...c5  I just wanted to take on c6 and play the game without getting too nervous. This was the 5th or 6th U20 tournament that I played, where I finished 2nd or 3rd, but never managed to win the event, in order to get the invitations for strong tournaments that I was hoping for. Probably that is why I was so relaxed as I sort of gave up on my ambitions to win it all costs and focused on enjoying chess regardless of the result. And it worked like a charm. }
10. dxc6 Nxc6
{ Later on, after seeing this line, the players shifted towards  10...bxc6  , which probably makes more sense.  11.Bd2  c5  12.Qc1  .  I played a couple of games like this, with ideas like Rd1 and Bh6, but Black keeps more chances for counterplay in this structure. }
11. Bb2 Qa5 12. Qc1
{ A useful move, preparing Rd1 and Nd5, which is a typical idea. } 12... Bg4
{ I thought my opponent might consider  12...Qh5  , which supports both ...Bh3 and ...Bh6, and I remember I wanted to reply with  13.Qg5  . However, had I thought a bit longer, probably I would have discovered an idea that is typical for White. I am not sure if you know it, but if you don't, then try to find it.  13.h4  ,  preventing Black's plans since ...Bh3 is no longer possible, while after  13...Bh6  14.Ng5  is a very annoying move, almost trapping the queen. }
13. Rd1
{ Surprisingly, this position is already difficult for Black and that happens in many of those types of English openings. I'll show you one example: @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5  5.Bg2  cxd4  6.Nxd4  Nc6  7.Nc3  O-O  8.O-O  d6  9.Nc2  and now let's try to compare it with the position  after @@StartFEN@@1r3rk1/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/q7/2P3b1/1PN2NP1/PB2PPBP/R1Q2RK1 w - - 4 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Rd1  , where it is clear that White achieved much more. Here, my bishop is not developed yet, the queen is obstructing the rooks that would prefer to be on the semi-open d-file.   With ...Bg4, Black was probably planning to simplify after  13.h3  with  13...Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Nd4  15.Rd1  @@StartBracket@@  15.Bg2  would run into the tactical shot  15...Qxc3  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1r3rk1/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q7/2Pn4/1PN2BPP/PB2PP2/R1QR2K1 b - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Nxf3+  16.exf3  .  Of course, White keeps the advantage, but during the game, I thought that, perhaps, after  16...Rfd8  , Black could hope to equalize with the help of the ...e6 and ...d5 plan. }
13... Rfc8 { A logical continuation. } 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. Bxg7
{ 15.Rxd5  is also totally fine, but I always like to give my opponents options that will lead to burning more time on the clock while choosing the move. }
15... Kxg7 16. Rxd5 Qc7 17. Qb2+
{ This was my plan all along, to offer Black a choice between ...f6 or go ...Kg8. I am not claiming that ...f6 is a mistake, but when the position becomes difficult @@StartBracket@@and it already is@@EndBracket@@ the natural response would be to seek counterplay. Since there is none in this position, that will translate to Black spending more time on the clock, which is to my advantage. }
17... f6
{ We have a solid type of position, where Black doesn't have weaknesses, and I would like you to find the strongest continuation for White. It is all about the rooks and their activity here. Is there a piece that should and could be improved for White?  Right... the a1-rook needs to come into play but where to? The d1-square is a good choice indeed, but there is an even better placement for the rook: e3! The rook on e3 will be very difficult to deal with for Black, especially given the target on e7. }
18. Rc1
{ Material-wise, Black is doing just fine, but, as surprising as this will sound, the position is in fact practically lost. Kasparov said it nicely: strengthening the position is inevitable. There is nothing Black can really do @@StartBracket@@unless our opponent is a computer and able to defend better than most of us@@EndBracket@@, while White will continue to improve the position.   A move like  18.c5  dxc5  19.Rxc5  will end in a draw since Black is totally fine and will exchange rooks on the d-file. }
18... b6
{ A@@EndBracket@@ Another way to protect the pawn on  e7  is to bring in a blocker  18...Ne5  , but now White has  19.Nd4  and the e6-square is weak.   B@@EndBracket@@ Trying to take  18...Bxf3  in order to follow it up with ...Ne5, then  19.exf3  must be considered when White will have the f4 option.   C@@EndBracket@@  18...Bd7  19.Rc3  and f Black is trying to get rid of the e7-pawn with  19...e6  20.Rd1  , then the d6-pawn becomes vulnerable. }
19. Rc3 Qd7
{ Perhaps, better would have been to bring the bishop to f7/g8 with  19...Be6  and try to barricade with ...Rd8, ...e5, but the position would still be ugly.  20.Rd1  ,  stronger than Rd2, to keep the square available for the knight. White has also ideas of h4-h5, but at least Black has some play and ideas, compared to the one-sided fight we had in the game. }
20. Re3 Kg8 21. Nd4
{ I could have also tried  21.h4  , but since I was relaxed, I went for the zen move, Nd4. }
21... Nxd4 22. Rxd4 Re8 23. b4
{ Since the pawn on c4 is not a weakness, I thought I could make use of Ra3 in the future, while c5 is also an idea. }
23... Qc8 24. h4
{ There is no more ...Bd7 due to h5. But what else?! Black is on the ropes already. }
24... Bd7 25. h5 Bc6 26. Bf1
{ Here, I was winning by force and had to calculate only two moves, but instead, I played the lazy move, deciding to avoid the bishop trade. Since the position is so good for White, I can do whatever I want: f3, Kf2, playing for Rg4, is one idea, while Black can only sit and wait.   26.hxg6  hxg6  27.Qc2  Kg7   27...f5  28.Bxc6  Qxc6  29.Rg4  Kf7  30.Rxg6  Kxg6  31.Re6+  Kg7  32.Qxf5  and mate is coming, while @@StartFEN@@1rq1r1k1/p3p3/1pbp1pp1/8/1PPR4/4R1P1/P1Q1PPB1/6K1 b - - 1 27@@EndFEN@@  27...Kf7  28.Rh4  Kg7  29.Bxc6  Qxc6  30.Rg4  is also winning.  28.Bxc6  Qxc6  29.Rg4  g5  30.Qf5  .  Sacrifices start profiling on the horizon.  30...Qc8  31.Rxg5+  fxg5  32.Qxg5+  Kh7  @@StartBracket@@  32...Kf7  33.Rf3+  Ke6  34.Qf5  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1rq1r3/p3p2k/1p1p4/6Q1/1PP5/4R1P1/P3PP2/6K1 w - - 1 33@@EndFEN@@  33.g4  .  Once again, the rook on e3 rules the board. }
26... Qf5
{ Black tried to get active, an option which I've seen the moment I played Bf1 and knew it doesn't work. }
27. Rh4 gxh5 { 27...g5  28.Bh3  wins the queen. } 28. Bh3 Qg6 29. b5 Ba8 30.
Bd7 Kf8
{ During the game, I thought he will play  30...e5  31.Bxe8  Rxe8  .  If Black has time for ...f5 and coordinate the pieces, there might be some hope for counterplay. But after  32.Rd3  f5  @@StartBracket@@  32...e4  33.Re3  . The rook is the knew knight, blocking any possible counter chances. White is winning.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@b3r1k1/p6p/1p1p2q1/1P2pp1p/2P4R/3R2P1/PQ2PP2/6K1 w - - 0 33@@EndFEN@@  33.Qa3  and the pawns start falling. }
31. Bxe8 Kxe8 32. Qb3
{ Not the only move in the position, but sufficient. I want to bring my queen to d3, while also creating a small trap. This is Svidler's school: improve your position by setting traps as well. }
32... Rc8 { 32...Kd7  33.c5  bxc5  34.Qe6+  with mate to follow soon. } 33. Qd3
Rc7 34. Kh2 { One more little trick around the corner... } 34... Kd7
{ Falling for it. A bit more resilient is  34...Kd8  , but we can see that Black has no attacking chances and is down in material as well. White is winning with almost any move and  35.f3  is one of them, planning to add pressure on the h5-pawn next. }
35. g4 Rc5
{ 35...hxg4  36.Qxg6  hxg6  37.Rh7  . Black is losing the pawn on e7 since  37...Ke8  38.Rh8+  wins the bishop, while after @@StartFEN@@b7/p1rkp2R/1p1p1pp1/1P6/2P3p1/4R3/P3PP1K/8 b - - 1 37@@EndFEN@@  37...Kc8  38.Rexe7  ,  White wins easily. }
36. Qxg6 hxg6 37. gxh5 gxh5 38. Ra3
{ Without the queens on the board, Black's position falls apart. } 38... a5 39.
bxa6 Rg5 40. f3 Kc7
{ Of course, it was not necessary for him to continue playing, but sometimes people have to get used to the idea of losing the game. }
41. Rh3 Re5 42. e4 Kb8 43. a7+ Kc7 44. Rg3 Rg5 45. f4 h4 46. Rxg5 fxg5 47. fxg5
{ I think Black's problems started to appear from the early decision to take on c6 with the knight, @@StartFEN@@1rbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2Pp1np1/n7/2P5/1PN2NP1/P3PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nxc6  , after which the position became difficult.  Also, more stubborn would have been to bring the bishop back from g4 to e6 and f7:  @@StartFEN@@1rr5/p1q1p1kp/1pnp1pp1/3R4/2P3b1/1PR2NP1/PQ2PPBP/6K1 b - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Be6  .  Once my rook got to e3, hitting the e7-pawn,  @@StartFEN@@1rr5/p2qp1kp/1pnp1pp1/3R4/2P3b1/1PR2NP1/PQ2PPBP/6K1 w - - 2 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Re3  , Black lost control of the position and I easily converted. }
