bxc6 { Taking with the pawn makes more sense. } 11. Bd2 c5
{ To illustrate the strategic danger in the position, a careless move like  11...Bb7  would run into  12.c5!  dxc5  @@StartBracket@@  12...d5  brings no relief, as after  13.Bf4  Rc8  14.Qc1  , White's position plays by itself, with multiple ideas  like Rd1, Be5, or Bh6. Black is  under pressure.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/pb2ppbp/2p2np1/n1p5/8/1PN2NP1/P2BPPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Na4  and Black's structure disintegrates.  I played @@StartFEN@@1rbq1rk1/p3ppbp/3p1np1/n1p5/2P5/1PN2NP1/P2BPPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qc1  in a couple of games here, with ideas like Rd1 and Bh6, but Black keeps more chances for counterplay in this structure. }
