17... f6
{ We have a solid type of position, where Black doesn't have weaknesses, and I would like you to find the strongest continuation for White. }
18. Rc1
{ It is all about the rooks and their activity here. Is there a piece that should and could be improved for White? Right... the a1-rook needs to come into play but where to? The d1-square is a good choice indeed, but there is an even better placement for the rook: e3! The rook on e3 will be very difficult to deal with for Black, especially given the target on e7.  Material-wise, Black is doing just fine, but, as surprising as this will sound, the position is in fact practically lost. Kasparov said it nicely: strengthening the position is inevitable. There is nothing Black can really do @@StartBracket@@unless our opponent is a computer and able to defend better than most of us@@EndBracket@@, while White will continue to improve the position.   A move like  18.c5  dxc5  19.Rxc5  will end in a draw since Black is totally fine and will exchange rooks on the d-file. }
