[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Igor Khenkin, Bundesliga 2003"]
[Result "*"]

{ My opponent in this game, Igor Khenkin, is a very solid and very strong GM. This game is a nice example of how I lure my opponents into complications. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 e6
{ My opponent is generally well booked up. I decided to play an offbeat line. }
5. Qb3
{ 5.Qd3  is also interesting when after  5...Nbd7  6.g3  the play transposes to the Catalan Opening, which I enjoy playing.   However, by now Black players have discovered that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p4/2PP4/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b6  is a better reply â it completely neutralizes 5.Qb3. }
5... dxc4 { This is the main move. } 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qd3
{ 7.Qb3  followed by g3 is more in the Catalan spirit, but Qd3 also supports e2-e4, which turns out to be more important. }
7... Nbd7
{ This move was almost considered to be the only one, back then. 7...a6 is more popular now.   Against  7...a6  ,  8.g4  Nxg4  9.Rg1  is a very interesting and modern approach. In return for the pawn, White gets the half open g-file, making it hard for Black to develop his f8-bishop. }
8. e4 b4 9. Na4 Bb7
{ Some years earlier, the game Kortschnoj-Ivanchuk went  9...Qa5  10.b3  c5  11.Bg5  Bb7  12.Bxf6  gxf6  13.d5  O-O-O  14.Be2  f5  15.exf5  Nb6  16.Nxb6+  Qxb6  17.O-O  Rxd5  18.Qe3  Rxf5  19.Ne5  Rg8  20.g3  Bg7  0-1 Kortschnoj-Ivanchuk, Lvov 2000.   I wanted to improve over this game with @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p2n1ppp/4pn2/q1p5/Np1PP3/1P1Q1N2/P4PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Be3  . }
10. e5
{ This position is very interesting and I analyzed it in the early 2000s. White has many options:   The move  10.Nd2  Be7  11.Nb3  O-O  12.f3  leads to a simple structure. White is trying to stop ...c5 and thus play against the bishop on b7. I thought it was too risky for White after  12...e5  with active counterplay. Perhaps the bishop could be activated with ...a5 and ...Ba6.   10.Be3  is the move I played against Gurevich. After  10...Qa5  11.b3  Be7  12.Nd2  I was slightly better but the game ended in a draw.  I will leave it here as a reference:  12...O-O  13.f3  c5  14.Nxc5  Nxc5  15.dxc5  Bxc5  16.Nc4  Qc7  17.Bxc5  Qxc5  18.Qd6  Rfc8  19.Be2  Ne8  20.Qxc5  Rxc5  21.Kf2  Ba6  22.a3  bxa3  23.Rxa3  Bxc4  24.Bxc4  Nd6  25.Bd3  e5  26.Rha1  Kf8  27.Ra6  Rd8  28.R6a5  Rc3  29.Rd5  Rxb3  30.Rxa7  f6  31.Bc4  Rb7  32.Rxd6  Rb2+  33.Kg3  Rxd6  34.Rf7+  Ke8  35.Rxg7  Rd7  36.Rxd7  Kxd7  37.Bg8  h6  38.Bh7  Ke7  1/2-1/2 Aronian-Gurevich, Khanty-Mansiysk 2005. }
10... Nd5 11. Bd2
{ This move frees the c1-square for the rook, making it harder for Black to achieve ...c5. Again, my opponent knows the opening theory well and is generally a very solid player, but he can also be very cautious. Therefore, I wanted to create chaos! }
11... Qa5
{ 11...c5  is too soon here.  12.Nxc5  Nxc5?  loses a pawn because  13.dxc5  Bxc5  14.Qb5+  wins the bishop.   Black can try to play for quick development with @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pb1n1ppp/4p3/2NnP3/1p1P4/3Q1N2/PP1B1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bxc5  13.dxc5  O-O  but in this case,  14.Ng5  is very strong. }
12. b3 Be7 13. Nb2 N5b6
{ Black should prefer quick development with  13...c5  . After the semi-forced  14.Nc4  Qc7  15.Rc1  , he can sacrifice a pawn with  15...Nc3!  16.Bxc3  bxc3  17.Rxc3  O-O  . The bishop pair tends to easily compensate for the pawn deficit, especially in open positions. Looking at this position now, I don't think White has anything. In fact, I would already prefer Black. }
14. Qe4 Qd5 15. Qg4 g6 16. Nd3
{ I also spent much time on  16.Bc4  Nxc4  17.bxc4  . Black is forced to play  17...f5  . At first, I thought I was better after   @@StartBracket@@In case of  17...Qa5  18.a3Â±  Black could easily lose the b4-pawn and other than that, my center is very strong.@@EndBracket@@  18.Qxg6+   @@StartBracket@@Black also gets enough play after  18.exf6  Nxf6  19.cxd5  Nxg4  20.dxe6  â  although White is a pawn up, Black has the better pawn structure and the bishop pair. His b7-bishop can be activated with ...c5 or simply ...Ba6@@EndBracket@@.  18...hxg6  19.cxd5  exd5  ,  but the position is balanced. Black's knight is coming to e6.   19...cxd5  20.Rc1  too easily gives White the superior structure. }
16... h5 17. Qf4 a5
{ Black could also play  17...c5  18.Rc1  Rc8  , which was more practical from Black's point of view.  19.Be2  O-O  20.O-O   20.Qh6  is too direct. There is no way to crush Black after, for example,  20...cxd4  .  20...cxd4  21.Bxb4  Bxb4  22.Nxb4  Qa5  23.Qxd4  Bxf3  24.gxf3  Qxe5  is about equal. White has a pawn majority on the queenside and a strong bishop, but a weak kingside pawn structure. }
18. Rc1 Rc8
{ 18...Ba6  was one possibility, but my opponent had set his mind to ...c5. }
19. Nc5
{ So I tried to stop ...c5.   19.Be2  c5  20.O-O  c4  Black gets active. }
19... Nxc5 20. dxc5
{ This is an interesting idea. I sacrificed to activate my pieces. } 20... Bxc5
{ It's easy to see that  20...Nd7  doesn't work. After  21.Be3  21...Nxc5   @@StartBracket@@  21...Bxc5  22.Bc4  Bxe3  23.fxe3  Qc5  24.O-O  looks extremely suspicious for Black: the knight is coming to g5 and f6/d6. Black's b7-bishop is really out of play now@@EndBracket@@.  22.Bxc5  Bxc5  23.Bc4  ,  Black's pieces are misplaced. }
21. Ng5 Rc7 22. Ne4 Be7 23. Be3
{ 23.Nf6+  is possible too, but Black is solid after  23...Bxf6  24.Qxf6  Rg8  . It's not that easy to put Black in a passive position now.  25.Bg5  doesn't work because of  25...Qe4+  26.Be2  Rd7  and Black isn't getting mated anytime soon. }
23... Nd7
{ 23...c5  24.Nf6+  Bxf6  25.Qxf6  Rg8  26.Rd1  Nd7  27.Bb5  Qxg2  looks too dangerous for Black. }
24. Rd1 g5
{ I had to make a big decision at this moment and in hindsight, I don't think I took the right decision. Back then, I undervalued the queen.   Black can't take on e5:  24...Qxe5  25.Rxd7!  Qxf4  26.Rxe7++-  . }
25. Nxg5
{ I thought that the position after  25.Qf3  Nxe5   25...Qxe5  26.Bd4  simply loses material.  26.Nf6+  Kf8  27.Qg3  Bxf6  28.Rxd5  cxd5  29.Bxg5  Bg7  ,  was totally unclear. Black has a rook, knight, and pawn for the queen. But now it's clear to me that White is completely winning. Although it's not easy to convert, my advantage is beyond dispute. I'm doing great after  30.Bf4  f6  @@StartBracket@@Chessable note: Stockfish prefers the untangling  30...Rc3  31.Qh4  Rc8  as a better defense@@EndBracket@@. @@StartFEN@@5k1r/1br3b1/4pp2/p2pn2p/1p3B2/1P4Q1/P4PPP/4KB1R w K - 0 31@@EndFEN@@  31.Qe3  . }
25... Bxg5 26. Qxg5 Qxe5 27. h4 c5
{ I thought my opponent had to take  27...Qxg5  ,  which gives me a positional advantage after  28.hxg5  c5  29.Rh4  . But as it turns out, Black doesn't have to take on g5 at all. }
28. Rxd7
{ I'm not claiming this is a good move, but at least, it's interesting. We were approaching the time trouble phase and I wanted to stir it up. I didn't want to allow my opponent to cruise towards a draw by exchanging many pieces.   I should have played  28.Rh3  when after  28...Bd5  29.Qxe5  Nxe5  30.Bg5  the position is balanced. I do have the initiative, but I am a pawn down. After  30...Ng6  31.Bb5+  Kf8  32.Bf6  Rg8  ,  Black has counterplay with ...Nf4. }
28... Qxg5 29. Rxc7 Qd5
{ 29...Qg6!  equalizes immediately. Now I'm the one who should make a draw.  30.Rxb7  Qb1+  31.Ke2  O-O  32.Rd7   I think my opponent had missed that  32.Kf3  is bad because of  32...Qg6  , when I don't have a good way of meeting the threat of ...Qg4.  32...Qxa2+  33.Ke1  . I analyzed  33...a4  34.Rh3  axb3  35.Rg3+  Kh8  , when most likely, the game will end in a draw by repetition after something like  36.Bg5  f5  37.Bh6  Rg8  38.Bg7+  Rxg7  39.Rgxg7  .   The same applies to  29...Qe5  , which is also a good move. I calculated  30.Rxb7  Qa1+  31.Ke2  O-O  32.Rd7  . I'll bring my forces out and force the draw. }
30. Bb5+ Kd8
{ After  30...Kf8  ,  the king is too exposed because of the typical maneuver  31.Rh3  . Black's king is getting too much attention. Rg3 and Bh6 are coming. }
31. Rxc5 Qe4
{ I also thought about  31...Qxg2  32.Bg5+  Qxg5  33.Rxg5  Bxh1  34.Bc4  . This position is pleasant for White. I will capture on a5 and then b4 and h5 will be weak. Perhaps it's not a winning advantage but I'm pushing for the win without risking anything. }
32. Ke2
{ A normal move, enabling Rd1.   I also considered  32.Kd2  because having my king on a dark square could prove to be beneficial. After  32...Ke7  33.f3  Rd8+  34.Ke2  Qg6  35.Kf2  ,  I can't possibly be worse and I have two strong bishops. I'd say Black's position is blunder-sensitive. }
32... Qg4+
{ A mistake.   Much stronger was  32...Bd5  , to give the black queen more squares @@StartBracket@@on the 5th rank@@EndBracket@@. It's a very solid move but after  33.Rd1  Ke7  34.Rd4  Qe5  , I still slightly prefer White. Practically, this position is much easier to play. }
33. Kd2 Rg8
{ A blunder.   Black had to get his king in safety with  33...Ke7  . After  34.Rc7+  Kf6  I can capture the bishop, but Black has  35.Rxb7  Rd8+  36.Rd7  Rxd7+  37.Bxd7  Qxg2  38.Rd1  Qe4  . It looks like White has a decisive material advantage, but in fact, the position is a draw: the h4-pawn will be lost and White has no threats at all. Black has a fortress. }
34. Rhc1 { Black can't stop Rc7-d7+. } 34... Qe4 35. Rg5
{ This move immediately finishes the game.   Of course not  35.Bg5+??  . The bishop is much stronger than the rook.  35...Rxg5  36.hxg5  Qxg2  and Black wins. }
35... Ke7 { 35...Rg6  36.Bd3  wins material. } 36. Rxg8 Qd5+ 37. Bd3 Ba6 38.
Bg5+ f6 39. Rc7+ Kd6 40. Bf4+ e5 41. Rd8+
{ This hectic game shows how I was becoming more and more confident as a chess player. I felt I was already much stronger than 2580: I calculated well, was outplaying my opponents and learned the ability to take games into my territory.    @@StartBlockQuote@@You must take your opponent into a deep dark forest where 2+2=5, and the path leading out is only wide enough for one. - Mikhail Tal@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
*


