[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Dmitry Svetushkin, Istanbul 2003"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played in the European Individual Chess Championship of 2003. I knew my opponent very well. Economically, we were facing difficult times in Armenia in the 90s â sometimes we would have no heating and no electricity. That's why I spent some time in ChiÈinÄu, Moldova with my family, where my coach organized matches against Moldavian players.  Dmitry was a very interesting person, with a very solid playstyle but a jovial character. Sadly, he passed away in 2020. }
1. e4 c5
{ This move already surprised me. I had prepared some ideas against the Caro-Kann, which he normally played. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Nc6 4. Nc3 Nge7
{ This transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  c5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  e6  4.e4  Nc6  , where I studied  5.Be2  . The Russian GM Sergey Rublevsky played like this and it's very playable. After  5...d5  6.cxd5  exd5  7.e5  Nd7  , I intended  8.Bb5  , but Dmitry played @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  . I didn't know this was playable.  During the game,  4...g5  seemed interesting to me. After  5.d4  g4  6.d5  gxf3  7.dxc6  fxg2  8.Bxg2  dxc6  @@StartBracket@@  8...bxc6  9.e5  is also very interesting.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3p1p/2p1p3/2p5/2P1P3/2N5/PP3PBP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qxd8+  Kxd8  10.e5  .  White has tons of compensation for the pawn, mainly because of the bad c8-bishop.  I will now show you another novelty so that you can understand how opening ideas are born.  Against MVL, I won a nice game with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  c5  2.Nc3  Nc6  3.Nf3  e5  4.e3  Nf6  5.d4  e4  . A very typical position.  6.d5  exf3  7.dxc6  bxc6  8.e4  fxg2  9.Bxg2  . This position is very similar to the one at hand. }
5. d4 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Qe3
{ 8.Qd3  is also a typical move in this structure. } 8... b6
{ My opponent played very quickly, which made me believe this was a well-known position, but it wasn't. My theoretical knowledge was not that broad. }
9. Bd3
{ When we are unfamiliar with a position in the opening, we shouldn't try to find new ideas â simply play moves that you know from similar positions. In this case, Black is trying to control the dark squares with ...Bc5, ...d6, ...e5, and then possibly ...Nd4. We know that the bishop is coming to c5, attacking my queen â where should my queen go? I want to move my queen to g3, so  9.g3  is not an option.   9.Qg3  is also interesting, to immediately attack the g7-pawn. The problem is that  9...Nb4  is hard to meet. The complications after  10.Bf4  Nc2+  11.Kd2  Nxa1  12.Nb5  don't work for White because of  12...Bb4+  followed by ...O-O. }
9... Bc5 10. Qg3 Qf6 { Black is trying to neutralize my queen with ...Qg6. }
11. Bf4
{ 11.O-O  was another interesting option, but I wasn't so sure what would happen after  11...Qg6  12.Qh3  h5  . I'm too late with f4-f5. }
11... Qg6
{ 11...O-O  12.e5  is a disaster for Black.   11...e5  is also too dangerous:  12.Nd5+-  . And it's too early to initiate complications with @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/p2p1ppp/1pn1pq2/2b5/2P1PB2/2NB2Q1/PP3PPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 5 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bd4  12.Nb5  Bxb2  13.Nc7+  too. }
12. Nb5 { I'm trying to force my opponent to exchange queens. } 12... Qxg3
{ If Black castles,  12...O-O  13.e5  is strong. @@StartBracket@@Or I could simply play  13.Qxg6  fxg6   13...hxg6  14.Bd6  Rd8  15.f4  is pleasant for White. Black needs his king on e7 to guard the dark squares.  14.Bg3  . Black's structure is compromised.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p2p1ppp/1pn1p1q1/1Nb1P3/2P2B2/3B2Q1/PP3PPP/R3K2R b KQ - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qxg3  14.hxg3Â±  and I have a strong initiative in the queenless middlegame. }
13. hxg3 Ke7
{ Here I started thinking for quite some time, I'd estimate 30 minutes. I found an extremely interesting idea but I had to make sure that the resulting, unbalanced position - that would arise on move 20 - was at least not worse for me. }
14. a3
{ It's unclear if I would have achieved anything at all after normal moves like  14.e5  Bb7  15.Be4  Na5  16.Bxb7  Nxb7  17.Rd1  . }
14... a6
{ The critical move. After  14...a5  e5 gains in strength, now that ...Na5 and ...Bb4+ are no longer possible.  15.e5  Bb7  16.Be4  . }
15. b4 axb5 { 15...e5  16.bxc5  exf4  17.Nc7  is clearly terrible for Black. }
16. bxc5 e5
{ From Black's perspective, it looks logical to fight for control over the dark squares. The best continuation for Black was  16...bxc4  17.Bd6+  Kf6  18.Bxc4  Ba6!  when many pieces come off the board. The game is headed for a draw after  19.Bxa6  Rxa6  20.cxb6  Rxb6=  .   16...bxc5  hands White two connected passed pawns and the bishop pair:  17.cxb5  Nd4  18.a4  with a strategically winning position for White. }
17. cxb5
{ 17.Bg5+  f6  18.Be3  bxc4  19.Bxc4  bxc5  20.Bxc5+  seems pleasant for White since he has the bishop pair, but I have bad news: White is slightly worse after  20...d6  21.Be3  Be6  . The a3-pawn is weak and Black has the @@StartBracket@@semi-@@EndBracket@@open a- and b-files for his rooks.   17.Be3  bxc4  18.Bxc4  bxc5  19.Bxc5+  d6  20.Be3  Be6  is very similar and still very pleasant for Black. }
17... Nb4 { This move looks crushing, both bishops are hanging! } 18. Bc4
{ A very original concept â everything is under control! } 18... Nc2+
{ 18...exf4  was probably better. After  19.Kd2  Black has the accurate  19...Na6!  @@StartBracket@@  19...fxg3?  20.axb4  Rxa1  21.Rxa1  gxf2  22.Ra7  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/3pkppp/np6/1PP5/2B1Pp2/P5P1/3K1PP1/R6R w - - 2 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Bd5  @@StartBracket@@  20.bxa6  fxg3=  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/3pkppp/np6/1PPB4/4Pp2/P5P1/3K1PP1/R6R b - - 3 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Nxc5  21.Bxa8  Nb3+  22.Kc3  Nxa1  23.Bd5  fxg3  24.fxg3  d6  25.Rxa1  .  The position has simplified a great deal. White still appears to have some pressure in the endgame arising after  25...Bd7  26.Kb4  Rc8  27.a4  Rc5  , but actually, the position is more or less a draw: I can't play a4-a5 because the b5-pawn would be hanging. }
19. Kd2 Nxa1 20. Bxe5
{ This is the position I had to assess when deciding on @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/p2pkppp/1pn1p3/1Nb5/2P1PB2/3B2P1/PP3PP1/R3K2R w KQ - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.a3!?  . Perhaps I don't have the advantage, but I liked the unbalance. }
20... bxc5
{ A@@EndBracket@@  20...Ra4  was an interesting alternative.  21.Bd5  Bb7!  This is the tactical justification of 20...Ra4. After  22.Bd6+   22.Bxb7  Nb3+  was Black's point. White loses material.  22...Kd8  23.Rxa1  Bxd5  24.exd5  Rd4+  25.Kc3  Rxd5  26.Kc4  Rd2  .  White clearly has the initiative, but the drawing margin is large.   B@@EndBracket@@ My threat is not just to recapture the knight. If he plays something like  20...Rxa3  , I intended to play  21.Bd6+!  when the bishop on d6 is cutting the board in half, but surprisingly, Black is surviving.  21...Kf6   Both  21...Kd8  22.cxb6  Ra4  23.Bc7+  ,  not allowing the king to c8.  23...Ke7  24.Bd5  , and...   21...Ke8  22.cxb6  Ra4  23.Kc3  Bb7  24.Bd5  give White a dominating advantage.  22.e5+  Kg6  23.cxb6  Ra4!  24.Rh4  Rxc4  25.Rxc4  Nb3+  26.Kd3  Na5  27.Rg4+  Kf5  28.Rxg7  .  Later I found that @@StartFEN@@2b4r/3pkppp/1p6/1PP1B3/2B1P3/r5P1/3K1PP1/n6R w - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Bxa1  gives White the advantage, although Black keeps drawing chances after  21...bxc5  22.Bxg7  Rg8  23.Rxh7  Ra4  .  Black will play ...d6 and ...Be6, but I'm pleased to have the bishop+2 pawns in return for the rook. }
21. Rxa1 f6
{ A@@EndBracket@@ He should have played  21...d6  . The tempi are far more important than the pawns.  22.Bxg7  Rg8  23.Bb2  Be6  24.Bd3  .  I clearly have the initiative, but my pawns aren't connected yet. Black can try to blockade them with ...Bb3, there is still a lot to play for.   B@@EndBracket@@ After  21...Bb7  ,  Black has no counterplay.  22.f3  ,  a3-a4 is easily achieved now.  22...f6  23.Bc3  Rhd8  24.Kc2  .  With this move, I am keeping the bishop pair so that my pawns can start marching.   24.a4  is inaccurate because of  24...d5  25.exd5  Bxd5  26.Bxd5  Rxd5+  27.Kc2  c4  28.Bb4+  Ke6=â  .  24...d5  loses by force:  25.exd5  Bxd5  26.Re1+  Kf7  27.Bxd5+  Rxd5  28.Kb3+-  and the pawns are unstoppable. }
22. Bc3 Ra4 23. Bb3 { This position is quite good for White. } 23... Rxe4 24.
f3 { The rook is trapped. } 24... Re6
{ Black has to return the exchange. He hopes to save the game in an opposite-colored bishop endgame, but White wins easily. The pawns are easily promoted after  24...Re5  25.Bxe5  fxe5  26.Re1  d6  27.f4  Be6  28.Bc2  Ra8  29.a4+-  too. }
25. Bxe6 dxe6
{ On  25...Kxe6  ,  I intended  26.Re1+  Kf7  27.a4  d5  28.Ba5  , when Black will be forced to play ...c4 after Bb6. Then the king will come to d4 and the queenside pawns will be too mighty. }
26. Kd3
{ This move is always useful. I'm threatening Kc4 @@StartBracket@@attacking the c5-pawn@@EndBracket@@ and preventing ...Bd5. }
26... e5 27. a4 Kd6
{ After the game, we discussed  27...Rd8+  . We both saw that after  28.Kc4  Be6+  29.Kxc5  Rc8+  30.Kb4  Rc4+  31.Kb3  ,  Black has no good discovered check. White wins after, for example,  31...Rg4+  32.Ka3  Rxg3  33.a5  . }
28. Ba5
{ Now that the bishop on d5 can't be protected by pawns anymore, I had an opportunity to make him completely passive. I'm preventing ...Rd8+ and after Rd1+, Black's king has to move back to the e-file. }
28... Bd7 29. Kc4 Be6+ 30. Kc3 Rb8
{ He had to play  30...Bd5  31.Bb6  Re8  32.Rc1  e4  , but I can play  33.Kb2  c4  34.a5  and the pawns are marching. }
31. Rd1+ Ke7
{ The rook endgame after  31...Bd5  32.Bc7+  Kxc7  33.Rxd5  Kb6  34.Rd6+  is a trivial win for White too. }
32. Bc7 Ra8 33. a5 Ra7 34. b6 Rxa5 35. b7 Ra3+ 36. Kd2 Ra2+ 37. Ke1 Bc4 38. Rb1
{ In conclusion, my opponent made many inaccurate moves in this game. It clearly showed that I didn't know the theory too well, but I was creative and had many interesting ideas too. This is how I learned how to pose my opponents practical problems, which my rival didn't manage to overcome in this game, and indeed, it's not an easy task. }
