[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Ivan Sokolov, Hoogeveen 2003"]
[Result "*"]

{ After I won the World Junior U20 Championship, I was invited to Hoogeveen. Back then, it was a tradition to invite: a former world-class player, the best Dutch player, the U20 World Champion, and a wildcard.  In 2003, it was an exceptionally strong tournament because we had Judit Polgar, a legendary player and one of my all-time favorites. Ivan Sokolov, the best Dutch player at the time, was rated around 2695, and of course, Anatoly Karpov, a former World Champion who, of course, was an exceptionally special opponent to me at that moment. Before that, I had never played a classical game against a World Champion, and in Hoogeveen, I got the chance to play two games.   A long story short, this was the first time in my career that I felt: oh my god I get to be part of something that seemed impossible to my peers. People said you'll get to 2600, but not much more; I heard that talk a lot. But now, I have the opportunity to show what I'm actually capable of.  I remember I arrived at Hoogeveen maybe one day before the tournament. A cute and nice hotel in the forest. To tell you the truth, at that time I was working too much. My theoretical knowledge was not that great because I was mainly training with Sargissian, and we had some personal misunderstandings, so I had to work on my own for almost a year. I was feeling very intimidated having to play against such legends, so I was working for 6-7 hours trying to compensate for my weakness in preparation.   Before this game, I remember analyzing Sokolov's games and decided that c4 was the way to go against him. }
1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4
{ Here, he surprised me with ...Bb4, a move that I have seen before, but I wasn't sure how to react to it.  I feel that generally, this is a good strategy: when you are playing against somebody young, try to play something that is out of fashion, and this is what Sokolov does. }
3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2
{ Magnus made this line with  4.e4  here, kind of popular lately and he won a very important game against Fabi in the World Championship match. }
4... O-O 5. Nf3 { Not a very good move. } 5... Re8
{ The main difference where this line works is where Black plays  5...Nc6  instead of ...Re8. Because now after  6.O-O  e4  7.Ng5  Bxc3  8.bxc3  Re8  , I get one tempo to get rid of the e4-pawn with  9.f3  and the knight gets to come back safely.   Since Black played  5...Re8  , Ng5 after ...e4 is not good anymore because Black can just play ...h6 and the knight has to retreat. }
6. O-O e4 7. Ng5
{ A mistake. But somehow, I managed to convince myself that they do play Ng5 in these positions, and probably there has to be a reason for it. This happens with young players a lot. Instead of looking at the position, concentrating, and finding the right ideas, they start assuming that this is how they normally play, so their moves are automatically good. Of course,  7.Nd4  or  7.Ne1  is to be preferred.  7.Nd4  Nc6  8.Nc2  Bxc3  9.dxc3  h6  is a possible position.  Also after @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pppp1ppp/5n2/8/1bP1p3/2N3P1/PP1PPPBP/R1BQNRK1 b - - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ne1  Bxc3  8.dxc3  , they play  8...h6  , which is a very important move, and I'd like to talk a little bit about these types of positions. We get this typical Rossolimo structure, and the main problem in this Reversed Rossolimo with an extra tempo for White is that the bishop on c1 doesn't really have prospects, and you have to exchange it whenever you can. For example, if Black plays  8...d6  , then we immediately play  9.Bg5  Nbd7  10.Nc2  h6  11.Bxf6  Nxf6  12.Nd4  followed by Ne3, Qc2, and we try to poke at the e4-pawn.  It is kind of strange when you think about it, that a bishop can be a bad piece in an open position, but with ...h6 played, where are we supposed to develop the c1-bishop? It is not good on f4 because there is always ...g5. On e3 it occupies the knight's square, and fianchettoing is stupid because it'll just be staring at the white pawns.  This is the main challenge@@StartBracket@@the bishop saga!@@EndBracket@@ of this position, and this is why normally, a prepared White player would not play 5.Nf3and we are better off avoiding these positions. I'm not saying it is lost for White, but Black gets a lot of easy play. }
7... Bxc3 8. bxc3
{ I should also mention sometimes that this Ng5 business is useful in these structures with  8.dxc3  h6  9.Nh3  Nc6  when White tries to play for  10.f4  exf3  11.exf3  d6  12.Nf2  . The knight is well-placed on f2, but this is only good for equality of course. Now, what you are trying to do is to play h3-g4-f5 and the e4-square is under your control, unlike when the knight is on c2. }
8... h6 9. Nh3 Nc6 10. Nf4 d6
{ Black is slightly better and I don't have any concrete ideas. Of course, if after  11.d3  my opponent takes, then life is good, but he can just play  11...Bf5  and slowly bring his queen to d7. I can't play d4 because the c4-pawn becomes too weak. Eventually, I'll have to play  12.Nd5  and after  12...exd3  13.exd3  Ne5  is very annoying. }
11. Nd5 Bf5
{ A mistake, which allowed me to finally free up my pieces. Had he played  11...Bg4  instead, then I would have an unpleasant position for the foreseeable future. I guess he didn't like  12.h3  Bh5  and some  13.Nf4  , but this doesn't really change the general assessment of the position. Okay, White will get two bishops after  13...Qd7  14.Nxh5  Nxh5  , but the same issues persist. Black will never take on d3 and allow White to open up the position. Black is even ready to sacrifice the e4-pawn to keep the position blocked. }
12. f3
{ Finally, I have some active ideas, I'm threatening  12...--  13.Nxf6  Qxf6  14.fxe4  . }
12... Nxd5 13. cxd5 exf3 14. Rxf3 Ne7 15. d3
{ Here, I also had the option of playing  15.Rf2  , which is a sophisticated option, and the better move. The rook doesn't belong on f3.  15...Qd7  16.Qf1  another point is that here I didn't commit the e-pawn and I retain the option of playing e4 if I want to.  This is more or less a Checkers kind of question, as Ivanchuk was explaining to me. In Checkers, you prefer to keep your pawns on their starting squares in order to have the tempi you need later on. }
15... Bd7 16. Rf2 Ng6 17. Rb1
{ And here I started really getting deep in thought. Let's look at the position from a general point of view:  We have two bishops with White. We have the majority in the center.  
And then I started thinking about  17.c4  , which looks like the most obvious move, but what happens after  17...c5  , a strange move, right? Then he starts playing for ...b5! If I play  18.e4  , then my bishop becomes extremely stupid. He will just put his knight on e5 and he will have a great outpost for it.   What if I play  17.Rb1  and after  17...b6  , I go now for  18.c4?  What I'm trying to achieve here is to bring my bishop to b2 and increase the pressure over g7. If I manage to do it quickly, let's say after  18...Rc8  19.Bb2  c6  20.Qd2  , I'm already threatening to play Rf1 and after ...f6, I might even take with a rook on f6! }
17... b5
{ What do you think I did here? It is all about pawn structures and switching plans. }
18. d4
{ Once again I started thinking, I don't want to play  18.e4  because after  18...c6  , I really don't like my bishop on g2.  Now, I completely changed my plan with d4. I understood that he wanted to put his knight on e5 and then meet d4 with ...Nc4. What I'm claiming is that while you move the knight from g6 to f6 via f8-h7, I will manage to create something.  And now the struggle begins. }
18... Rc8 19. Bd2
{ I had this kind of inner thought: I really want to put my queen on d3 where it looks safe, but how am I going to stop ...c6? So I realized that maybe the way to stop ...c6 is to put my queen on b3, x-raying the f7-pawn. }
19... a6 20. Qb3
{ The problem with this is that it allowed a really nice maneuver for Black. What do you think it is? }
20... Bg4
{ Difficult concept actually, the main issue here for Black is not the position of the knight, but rather the fact that he has to stop my active plans. In order to do that, he needs to activate the bishop and the queen, and this is what he did. }
21. e3 Qd7
{ And now his intentions are crystal clear, he wants to exchange the bishop from h3, and if I refuse by retreating to h1, only then does he start activating his knight because Rbf1 is no longer possible. }
22. c4 Bh3 23. Bxh3 Qxh3 24. cxb5
{ I realized that he played really well and the position is about equal. But here he committed a blunder. }
24... Rb8 { What do you think he missed here? } 25. Qc2
{ Yes! With a double attack on a6 and c7, here he started panicking. } 25...
Qd7 { What do you think I played now? } 26. Rbf1
{ Of course, I can take on a6, but this is even stronger. } 26... Nh8
{ One more precise move is required here. Can you find it? } 27. Qc6
{ I'm just trying to get this good endgame and since the knight is on h8, I started thinking about its future.   Where is this knight going to? f7 of course. Nevertheless, whenever Black plays ...Nf7, I will play h4 immediately, and then Black will have to spend even more time playing ...h5 and ...Nh6 â this simply takes way too much time.   More importantly, the c7-pawn is extremely vulnerable. Once I get my rook on the 7th rank, and once c7 falls, d6 will follow it soon after. }
27... Qxc6 28. bxc6 Rb5 29. Rf5
{ A greedy move, I think, from a practical point of view. It was better to play  29.a4  and after  29...Rxd5  30.Rb1  , I'm giving up the pawn, but the rook on d5 will take a zillion moves to come back into play. After  30...Ng6  31.Rb7  Rc8  32.Ra7  , I will capture the a6-pawn and slowly bring my king to f3. This should be an easy win. }
29... f6 30. a4 Rb3
{ Better than  30...Rb2  because anyway I don't care about the threat I'll attack the c7-pawn with  31.Ba5  , allowing me to bring the rook back from f5.  31...Rc8  32.R5f2  Rb3  33.Re1  Nf7  34.h4  followed by Ree2-b2. }
31. Ba5 Rc8 32. e4 Nf7
{ Another blunder. He had to play  32...Ra3  to at least create some counterplay.  33.e5  looks crushing, but it is not  33...Nf7  34.exf6  g6!  followed by taking on a4. It is still a difficult game for Black, but it is not completely winning for White. }
33. R5f3 Rb2
{ Of course, Black can't afford to exchange the only active piece he has. After  33...Rxf3  34.Rxf3  Ng5  35.Rb3  Nxe4  36.Rb7  , it is finito, I just take and promote. }
34. h4 { We restrict the f7-knight. } 34... Ra2
{ I think you are capable of finding the winning idea here. There are other ways, of course, but let's see what I played in the game. }
35. Rb3
{ If you said: don't think too much, just put a rook on the b-file, then you are right. This is what I did in the game. }
35... Rxa4 36. Bxc7 Rxc7 37. Rfb1 Re7
{ This was move 37, I had 10 minutes, and my opponent was in severe time trouble and in my mind I had already put 1-0 on the scoresheet. My mind was already somewhere else, 'what am I going to talk about in the press conference? I didn't know the opening but this was a good game, yes, I'm very happy to be here...' contemplating and congratulating myself on my great achievement, and I see that I'm completely winning, but then I started seeing some ghosts.   It is actually pretty good I realized that I had this issue early on. I get too complacent and very happy when I have good positions early on in my career. I wouldn't have won half of the number of tournaments that I ended up winning if I didn't work on this issue early on.   I still have this same problem today, as they say, the 'deer in a flashlight effect'.   Here, I have two easy ways to win: a simple one with  38.Rc3  . You don't have to be a genius to put the behind the passed pawn.  38...Rxd4  39.c7  Rxc7  40.Rxc7  Ne5  41.Rbb7  and that is it. I take on g7, and the game is finished.   Another slightly more difficult way to win is  38.Rb7  Rxe4  31.Rc1  Raxd4  32.c7  Rc4  33.c8=Q  Rxc8  34.Rxc8  Kh7  35.Rxf7  .  What do you think I did? I spent 7 minutes and then I played a move that makes zero sense. }
38. e5 Rxd4 39. Rb8+
{ I'm already completely panicking, feeling like I'm going to lose on time.  Here was the last chance for me to win the game, but I had to find the very tough  39.e6  and after  39...Rxd5  40.Rc3!  Nd8  41.Rb8  Rc5  42.Rxd8  Kh7  43.Rxc5  dxc5  44.h5  , White is winning. The line can continue  44...c4  45.Kf2  c3  46.Rd3  Rxe6  47.Rxc3  Re8  48.c7  Rc8  49.Ke3  Kg8  , but my king is too fast.  50.Kd4  Kf7  51.Kd5  Ke7  52.Kc6  finito. }
39... Kh7 40. exf6 gxf6 41. R8b7
{ I was still thinking he needs to play  41...Rde4  and then I will take  42.Rxe7  Rxe7  43.Rb7  , but of course, all of this is nonsense. }
41... Re2 42. Rxf7+ Kg6 43. Rf8 Rdd2
{ We agreed to a draw because of the perpetual check.  To say I was heartbroken is not enough. You're playing your first tournament, your opponent is almost 2700, you get a bad position out of the opening where you manage to trick him and get an easy win out of it where you have 10 minutes and he has barely a minute. To squander all of that for a psychological blunder, completely zone out of the game, of course, was not a good feeling.  Nevertheless, these types of mistakes are important. You start learning how to control your emotions. I spent a day trying to understand what happened, and then I thought I should just move on and not worry so much about winning.   Long story short, I found a lot of excuses to explain my blunder and in the end, the tournament was a decent success.   Let's just say that I didn't end the tournament on a bad note as you will see in the next game, which is one of my most memorable games@@StartBracket@@together with this one despite the result!@@EndBracket@@. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Ivan Sokolov â Puzzle #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqr1k1/pppp1ppp/5n2/8/1bP1p3/2N2NP1/PP1PPPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

7. Ng5
{ A mistake. But somehow, I managed to convince myself that they do play Ng5 in these positions, and probably there has to be a reason for it. This happens with young players a lot; instead of looking at the position, concentrating, and finding the right ideas, they start assuming that this is how they normally play, so their moves are automatically good.  Of course, @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pppp1ppp/5n2/8/1bP1p3/2N2NP1/PP1PPPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nd4  or  7.Ne1  are to be preferred, but why is  7.Ng5  an error? }
7... Bxc3 8. bxc3
{ I should also mention sometimes that this Ng5 business is useful in these structures with:  8.dxc3  h6  9.Nh3  Nc6  when white tries to play for  10.f4  exf3  11.exf3  d6  12.Nf2  .  The knight is well-placed on f2, but this is only good for equality of course. Now what you are trying to do is to play h3-g4-f5 and the e4-square is under your control, unlike when the knight is on c2. }
8... h6 9. Nh3 Nc6 10. Nf4 d6
{ Black is slightly better and I don't have any concrete ideas here. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Ivan Sokolov â Puzzle #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/ppp2pp1/2np1n1p/8/2P1pN2/2P3P1/P2PPPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. Nd5
{ Black can now confine White in an unpleasant position for the foreseeable future. How? }
11... Bg4 { Playing against White's liberating idea: f3. } 12. f3
{ White is still trying to free up the pieces by concrete means, but the cure is worse than the disease. Nevertheless, after  12.h3  Be6  ,  it is still hard for White to disentangle. }
12... exf3 13. exf3
{ 13.Bxf3  doesn't work either.  13...Bxf3  14.Rxf3  Nxd5  15.cxd5  Ne5  .  White is behind in development, the light squares are weak, and the structure is also suffering. }
13... Bf5 14. d4 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Na5
{ White's structure is the culprit for the positional issues. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Ivan Sokolov â Puzzle #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/ppp2pp1/2np1n1p/3N4/2P1p3/2P3P1/P2PPPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11... Bf5 { A mistake, which allowed me to finally free up my pieces. } 12. f3
{ Finally, I have some active ideas, I'm threatening @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/ppp2pp1/2np1n1p/3N1b2/2P1p3/2P2PP1/P2PP1BP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nxf6+  Qxf6  14.fxe4  . }
12... Nxd5 13. cxd5 exf3 14. Rxf3 Ne7
{ Here, I had a different choice than  15.d3  , which was played in the game. }
15. Rf2
{ A sophisticated option and the better move. The rook doesn't belong on f3. }
15... Qd7 16. Qf1
{ Another point is that here I didn't commit the e-pawn and I retain the option of playing e4 if I want to. This is more or less a Checkers kind of question as Ivanchuk was explaining to me. In Checkers, you prefer to keep your pawns on their starting squares in order to have the tempi you might need later on. }
