[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Establishing as a GM"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Anatoly Karpov, Hoogeveen 2003 "]
[Result "*"]

{ This game with the white pieces was played against Anatoly Karpov, right after the disappointing  (but educational!)  game with Ivan Sokolov, so I was really heartbroken. I tried my best to play a solid game and recover from the Sokolov disappointment, and you can see that in my opening choice â mainly because in round 3 of this tournament he put real pressure on me by making me defend my Vienna variation, forcing me to find only moves to survive that game. I knew that he was really serious in this tournament because of that novelty he pulled out on me in round 3. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ I chose to play the Qc2 Nimzo. In fact, when I was mentioning that I was spending 6-7 hours a day analyzing, I was looking a lot at what to play with White, because with Black, more or less, I had this fixed repertoire: 1.e4 e5, against 1.d4 the Nimzo, and if my opponents were playing 1.Nf3 I was going for Vienna.  I've already played the Qc2 Nimzo against Polgar in this tournament, I didn't have a good position, but slowly I was getting the hang of it. }
4... c5 5. dxc5 Bxc5
{ A rare move. Usually, Black is waiting for the a2-a3. That's why the text move may lead to a loss of tempo.   The main line and the line that I analyzed before this game starts with  5...O-O  . I knew that people play like this, and I had a feeling Karpov will try to surprise me. }
6. Nf3 O-O 7. Bg5 { So far, very logical. } 7... Be7 8. Rd1
{ I think I was trying to kind of bring the game into something that I already knew. I am still not sure if I am going to play with e4 or not, although e4 is a good move already. }
8... h6 9. Bh4
{ You can see that I was a bit shy. I think nowadays after a move like ...h6 it is like a piece of cloth to a bull. I will play  9.Bf4  d6  and  10.g4  , which is in fact very strong and dangerous for Black to play ...h6 so early on. }
9... b6
{ Maybe instead of ...b6 he should have tried  9...d6!?  10.e4  Nbd7  . As you will see later on in the game, he didn't manage to get good squares for his pieces. }
10. e4 Bb7 11. Be2 a6 12. O-O Ne8
{ Now you can see that Black cannot play  12...d6  because I am playing  13.e5!  But I knew at that time that Karpov is the kind of player who can play quietly since he's very experienced, and he doesn't mind a passive position. I knew I shouldn't get too relaxed. }
13. Bg3
{ Objectively stronger was  13.Bxe7!  Qxe7  14.Qb3  Qd8  15.c5  b5  16.a4Â±  . In the game, I considered @@StartFEN@@rn1qnrk1/1b1p1pp1/pp2p2p/8/2P1P3/1QN2N2/PP2BPPP/3R1RK1 w - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15.e5  , and I wasn't so sure that he will not come out of this passive position. I've seen him too many times carving his way out slowly by reshuffling his pieces on the 7th and 8th ranks and exchanging the right pieces at the right time. }
13... d6 14. e5 Qc7 { So far, all of this is very natural. } 15. exd6 Nxd6
{ Of course, it is easy to see that  15...Bxd6?  is not working for Black.  16.Rxd6  Nxd6  17.Rd1  and the pin is just too strong.  17...Rd8  18.Qd2+-  . }
16. Rd4
{ At this moment I thought for some time, and I think I found an excellent move which I think you should try and find.  What we are trying to do is to double our rooks and create threats down the d-line. But if we start with  16.Rd2  , then there is  16...Qc6  and Black is generating some threats with ...Nxc4.   If we do something like  16.Ne4  , it is a normal move, but not completely crushing after  16...Bxe4  17.Qxe4  Nxe4  18.Bxc7  b5â©²  .   Nevertheless, the move that I found basically decided the game. With Rd4 I am luring Black to play ...Nc6 and after @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/1bq1bpp1/pp1np2p/8/2PR4/2N2NB1/PPQ1BPPP/5RK1 b - - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nc6  , I just go  17.Rd2  and Black doesn't have the ...Qc6 resource anymore.  17...Rad8  18.Rfd1  and if Black tries to double up on the d-file with  18...Rd7  , then  19.Na4!  Now there are too many threats and the rook will get trapped on d7 after  19...Rfd8  20.c5! }
16... Qc6
{ The next move will show you the whole point of Rd4. Can you find it? } 17.
Bd3
{ Now, Black doesn't get any good squares for the d6-knight. If you try to develop with  17...Nd7?  , I can win a piece with  18.Bxd6  Bxd6  19.Be4+-  . }
17... Ne8 18. Bh7+
{ A useful intermediate check. The pawn on f7 will be undefended, which may become important in the near future. }
18... Kh8 19. Be4 Qc8 { What do you think I played now? } 20. Na4
{ Black will not be able to coordinate his pieces anymore. Thanks to Rd4, I forced his pieces out of their natural position. }
20... Bc5
{ There is no easy way to defend the b6-pawn. After  20...Nd7  , I can just take on d7.  21.Rxd7  Qxd7  22.Nxb6  and that's it. }
21. Nxc5 bxc5 22. Bxb7 Qxb7 23. Rd2
{ Despite the material balance, Black's position is very tough. White controls the important d-file, while Black has numerous weaknesses in his camp, and his pieces are badly placed. }
23... Nf6
{ Trying to bring out the pieces somehow. He should have played  23...Nc6  24.Rfd1  Ra7  and maybe this is more resilient, as with a knight on c6, Black can hope to play ...Nd4 at some point. }
24. Rfd1 Qc8
{ 24...Nbd7  doesn't help the cause.  25.Ne5  Nxe5  26.Bxe5  and White is dominating. }
25. Bd6 Re8 26. Ne5 Kg8
{ And here, I found the most elegant way to win, can you tell me what I played? Of course, the position is completely helpless for Black, but this is the easiest. }
27. Be7 { Threatening Rd8.  27...Nc6  is met with  28.Bxf6  gxf6  29.Nxf7! }
27... Qc7 28. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Now, his only hope is to meet  29.Ng4  with  29...Qf4  . So what do you think I did? }
29. Qe4 { White's attack is irresistible. } 29... Ra7 30. Ng4 Kg7 31. Qe3 Rh8
{ The final blow? } 32. Rd8
{ This nice move crowns an excellent game.  32...Rh7  33.Qf3  f5  34.Qc3++-  .   This game gave me a lot of optimism and made me very proud to crush a World Champion and a brilliant player like Karpov in such a manner that he didn't really get to play anything at all throughout the game â an extremely pleasant feeling to beat him like that.  I remember that we spent about an hour and a half analyzing the game, and in the analysis, I was able to prove that I'm a good player, as I continuously found good moves. Whenever you are playing against Karpov, you won't only be tested during the game, but also in the post-mortem! }
*


