{ With the Karpov game, I want to conclude this chapter.   As I think of everything, this first volume represents the things I've learned from my career and some of the interesting games I played. Some of them are very tragic, as you've already seen, but at the same time very educational.  Part 1 of the course can be titled 'Coming close to the Elite,' from FM level to strong Grandmaster level.  In Part 2, I plan on giving an overview of myself as an already established player trying to get to the top.  I hope you enjoyed this first part, while the second one will come out next year. I don't know how early, maybe as a Valentine's gift, you never know.  I also hope that Part 1 will be educational and that you'll be able to solve all of the puzzles I gave to you. You will see that becoming a strong player requires you to make a lot of mistakes.  Good luck! }
1. -- *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Boring Positions"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Andrei Istratescu, Novi Sad 2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 Nd4 5. Bg2 Nxf3+ 6. Bxf3 Bb4 7. Qb3 Bc5 8.
d3 h6 9. O-O O-O 10. Bd2 Re8 11. Rac1 Rb8 12. Qa4 d6 13. b4 Bd4 14. e3 Bxc3 15.
Bxc3 Bh3 16. Bg2 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qd7 18. Qxd7 Nxd7 19. e4 c6 20. Rfd1 Rbd8 21. d4
Nb6 22. c5 exd4 23. cxb6 dxc3 24. bxa7 Ra8 25. Rxc3 Rxa7 26. Rxd6 Rxe4
{ We have an interesting topic to discuss, one that I call 'boring positions'. Joking aside, I don't believe that chess has dull moments. There are, of course, difficult or complicated positions, and each one of them has its own hidden resources.  Understanding them would eventually make us better players, as we can always find something to calculate or evaluate unless there is a dead draw in front of us when nothing else can be done but shake hands. Many positions that I thought are kind of lifeless, turned out to be very interesting.  The first example is my game against Andrei Istratescu, European Team Championship, Novi Sad 2009. At a first glance, it may appear that it will take only two more moves and the players will agree to a draw, but I just tried to keep the game going. }
27. Rd8+ Kh7 28. Rd7 { Obviously, Black has many options here. } 28... Rxb4
{ The move played in the game reveals White's concealed resource. In case of  28...Rxa2  , I was still planning to employ the same idea,  29.Rf3  , just as after ...Rxb4. }
29. Rf3
{ Planning to double the rooks on the seventh rank since f6 can simply be taken with Rxf6 . }
29... Rxa2 30. Rfxf7 Rg4 31. Rxb7
{ Is this a dead draw? Absolutely. However, it is a position where I am not risking anything as White, and I can just continue playing. What happens here  (I have been in similar situations too)  is that at some point, emotions start to interfere with your judgment. While the opponent is trying to make progress, your thoughts might get overheated since, apparently, everything and anything should bring home a draw, so then why are we still playing?!  Losing your temper because your opponent is playing a seemingly boring and drawish position happens to the best of us, and this is the moment when mistakes begin to infiltrate. It's pure psychology and I think that I lost way more of those drawish games than the ones where I was actually lost but managed to save or turn around. It's a good thing to learn from other people's errors. }
31... Rg6 32. Kh3
{ There are different methods to defend, but what Black can do here is get a 3 vs.2 pawn structure on the kingside, which would be a dead draw. }
32... h5
{ My opponent decided to play more actively, which is also completely fine, while  32...Ra8  33.f4  Rg8  is also an option. Just that after  34.f5  , Black should avoid placing the rook on a passive position with  34...Rg5  , and go for  34...Rd6  instead. }
33. f4 Rf2 34. Rbc7
{ Now Black has to make a decision. Everything seems perfectly placed, but... The point I am trying to send across is that even if you are just a tiny bit better, you can still put a lot of pressure on your opponent. That's exactly what Magnus does and is very good at it. He just wants to keep the game going and see whether mistakes will appear, which happens more often than not.   I discarded  34.f5  Rg5  35.f6  because of  35...Kh6  36.Rxg7  Rxf6  37.Rh7+  Kg6  and there is no pawn gain from this sequence. }
34... Rd2
{ After  34...Kg8  35.Rf5  , Black needs to decide what to do with the h5-pawn.  35...h4  36.g4  can prove quite dangerous, as the h4-pawn became weak. Still, Black should probably hold, for instance, after  36...Rf6  , since the position doesn't look that scary. }
35. f5 Rg4 { Now  35...Rg5  doesn't work that well due to  36.Kh4  . } 36. Rxc6
Rf2
{ This is the moment White was looking for: Black succumbed to the tension and the last move is a blunder. Can you tell me why is ...Rf2 a wrong call?   Black could have made a draw by playing  36...Rd5  instead. However, I am still not risking anything and can continue playing. Of course, objectively the game should end in a draw as Black can just keep the rook on the fifth rank, and when  37.f6  comes, Black will have  37...Rf5  38.Rcc7  Kh6  . Despite the fact that Black lost a pawn, the position is still a draw.  39.Rxg7  Rxg7  40.fxg7  Rg5  . The pawn endgame is a draw and if  41.Rc6+  Kxg7  42.Kh4  Re5  , Black can just sit and wait, nothing will happen. }
37. Rg6
{ Black is already lost since the rooks cannot be exchanged and the g7-pawn will fall. }
37... Kh8 38. Rfxg7 Rxg6 39. Rxg6 Rxf5 40. Kh4 Kh7 41. Rg5 Rf2 42. h3
{ White wins the h5-pawn and the game. This is just a little example, which shows that from such a dry initial position, you can actually still extract a point by just continuing the game. }
*


