[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Boring Positions"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Vasyl Ivanchuk, Nalchik 2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nf6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Bg5 Qc7 7. e3 b6 8. Bd3
Bb7 9. O-O Nc6 10. Rc1 Rc8 11. Be2 Be7 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Nd5 exd5 14. Bxf6 Bxf6
15. cxd5 Bxb2 16. Rc2 Be5 17. dxc6 dxc6 18. Bxa6 Rd8 19. Qf3 c5 20. Bb5+ Kf8
21. g3 g6 22. Rd1 Kg7 23. Rcd2 Rxd2 24. Rxd2 Rd8
{ One more example of the same 'boring' theme. This excerpt is taken from my game against one of my favorite players of the modern era, Vasyl Ivanchuk, which was played in an important tournament, the FIDE Grand Prix 2009.  The connection with Ivanchuk is special to me, as I love his chess, but at some point in our careers, he had an overall +8 score against me! And then I started to understand that my Nemesis is incredibly precise in slightly better positions. However, as happens often, our strengths can prove to be our weaknesses as well. He is not so precise in defending slightly worse positions.  If you look at the diagram at hand, the position looks pretty lifeless. We have opposite-colored bishops and nobody can seriously consider that White could ever win this. Nonetheless, I thought I should just play and not offer a draw. White is not risking anything, my bishop is a tiny bit better than the black one  (from c4, it attacks the f7-pawn)  , while the bishop on e5 is obstructed by my pawn on g3, so why not continue playing? }
25. Rxd8 Qxd8 26. Kg2 h5
{ I remember that by this point, my opponent was getting a bit annoyed, which is a typical reaction in completely drawn positions. When this happens, the player on the worse side of things tries to force the draw and get it over with, instead of sitting tight and waiting.  On such occasions, we cannot make progress unless we get help from our opponent by starting to create unforced weaknesses. Here, ...h5 was not necessary, Black could simply wait for further developments. }
27. Qe4 Bc3 28. Qb7 Bf6
{ A dream scenario for me would be if Black will become tight to a passive position. So let's imagine  28...Ba5  29.Bc4  Qe8  , which looks like moves coming from a simul and not a proper classical game, but I am trying to make a point.  30.e4  Kf8  31.e5  . In this case, I could actually say that I do have winning chances since I can start rolling my pawns: f4, h3, g4 and continue pushing. Once the f-pawn reaches f6, the position is probably winning for White. This is what I would love to get, but of course, Black wouldn't allow me to do so. }
29. Bc4 Qe7
{ The b6-pawn is not hanging since  30.Qxb6  loses the bishop to  30...Qe4+  , which is far from ideal. }
30. Qd5
{ I remember that Ivanchuk was having a very bad tournament and was trying to win every single game by playing crazy chess. In the press conference, they asked Chuky as we dearly call him: what do you think is the problem? 'I am a drug addict' was the answer and everyone was flustered. And he continued: 'I am addicted to winning, I don't care about all those draws.'  Then I was asked how I feel when facing an opponent that is in bad shape, and whether I feel sorry for him since he is one of my favorite players. To which I responded that wolves are actually true gentlemen. When they see that their friend is sick, they eat them, so I had to do it. :@@EndBracket@@ Moving away from anecdotes, Chuky was playing too fast, taking no more than 1 minute per move, which started giving me hope. }
30... h4
{ The problem in this position is that Black can always offer a queen exchange since the resulting opposite-colored bishop endgame should be a draw. There are simply too many drawing resources. }
31. e4 hxg3 32. hxg3 Bd4
{ 32...g5  is one of the ways to achieve a draw and get a little bit active as well.  33.f4  gxf4  34.gxf4  Bd4  and now after  35.e5  , there is always the sacrifice  35...b5  36.Bxb5  Qh4  when Black gets counterplay. But this is just a sample, there are way too many drawish choices for Black. }
33. f4 f6
{ My hopes just got a boost after this move. Black is trying to liberate the pieces from defending the pawn on f7 and place the king on h6 but is now running into tactical ideas.   33...Qf6  would have been the easiest.  34.Kf3   After  34.Qd7  , Black can simply wait with  34...Bb2  since Kf3 is met by a check on c3, while  35.e5  is answered by  35...Qf5  . And if @@StartFEN@@8/3Q1pk1/1p3qp1/2p5/2B1PP2/6P1/Pb4K1/8 w - - 3 35@@EndFEN@@  35.Kh3  , Black has  35...g5  .  34...g5  , the pawn grab doesn't lead anywhere, but also  35.e5  is well met by  35...Qf5  . }
34. Kf3 Kh6 35. Qg8 g5 { 35...Qg7  36.Qc8  threatening Qh3. } 36. e5 fxe5
{ If you can find the win for White, that would be good.   36...Qg7  was the only move to hold.  37.Qe6  Qg6  , Black has to bring the queen to deliver the saving checks.  38.Qh3+  Kg7  39.Qd7+  Kh6  40.exf6  Bxf6  .  It is not that easy to draw though, it requires precision. After  41.Bd3  Qg8  , White cannot exploit Black's passive position.  42.fxg5+  Bxg5  43.Qd6+  Kg7  44.Qg6+  Kf8  and Black is holding. This was a stretch already, as Black allowed too many things to happen.   Chessable note: After  36...Qg7  , White can still win, nonetheless!  37.fxg5+!  fxg5   37...Qxg5  38.Qxg5+  is similar to the main line as White can liquidate into a winning opposite-colored bishop endgame.  38.Qe6+  Qg6  . Should White exchange queens or is it too risky to land in an opposite-colored bishop endgame?  39.Qxg6+  , yes, we can!  39...Kxg6  40.Ke4  . Black is unable to prevent the e6-pawn from promoting and also keep an eye on the b6-pawn, which will eventually fall. }
37. Bd3 e4+ { Black has to protect the h8-square as well. } 38. Bxe4
{ Threatening mate in one. } 38... Qg7 39. Qe6+ Qf6 40. Qd7
{ White is winning since Black cannot escape from being mated. The only reason I won this game is because I was not risking anything and continued playing, without worrying that the position is colorless. }
