35... g5 { How should White exploit the vulnerable position of Black's king? }
36. e5 { Opening the diagonal for the light-squared bishop. } 36... fxe5 37.
Bd3 e4+
{ 37...Qg7  is a huge mistake, because of  38.fxg5+  , winning the queen or giving checkmate.  38...Qxg5  39.Qh7  . }
38. Bxe4 Qg7
{ Defending against checkmate. Now that the e-pawn was given back, Black's bishop protects the queen. }
39. Qe6+ Qf6 40. Qd7
{ And White is winning since Black cannot escape from being mated. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Boring Positions"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Vasyl Ivanchuk â Puzzle #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6Q1/4q3/1p3p1k/2p1P1p1/2Bb1P2/5KP1/P7/8 b - - 0 36"]
[SetUp "1"]

36... Qg7
{ Chessable note: In the video, Aronian gives @@StartFEN@@6Q1/4q3/1p3p1k/2p1P1p1/2Bb1P2/5KP1/P7/8 b - - 0 36@@EndFEN@@  36...Qg7  as the only move to hold. Following  37.Qe6  Qg6  , Black has to bring the queen to deliver the saving checks.  38.Qh3+  Kg7  39.Qd7+  Kh6  40.exf6  Bxf6  . It is not that easy to draw though, it requires precision. After  41.Bd3  Qg8  , White cannot exploit Black's passive position.  42.fxg5+  Bxg5  43.Qd6+  Kg7  44.Qg6+  Kf8  and Black is holding. This was a stretch already, as Black allowed too many things to happen.  However, White can still win in the initial diagram. How? }
37. fxg5+ fxg5
{ 37...Qxg5  38.Qxg5+  is similar to the main line as White can liquidate into a winning opposite-colored bishop endgame. }
38. Qe6+
{ The hasty  38.Qxg7+  only helps Black to bring the king closer. Following  38...Kxg7  39.Ke4  Kf8  40.Kd5  Ke7  , Black is in time to put up a tough defense. For instance,  41.g4  is well met by  41...Kd7  and White cannot break through, while @@StartFEN@@8/4k3/1p6/2pKP1p1/2Bb4/6P1/P7/8 w - - 4 41@@EndFEN@@  41.e6  is answered by  41...g4  when White has a soft pawn on g3 and Black escapes with a draw. }
38... Qg6
{ Should White exchange queens or is it too risky to land in an opposite-colored bishop endgame? }
39. Qxg6+ { Yes, we can! } 39... Kxg6 40. Ke4
{ Black is unable to prevent the e6-pawn from promoting and also keep an eye on the b6-pawn, which will eventually fall. }
*


