[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Boring Positions"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Peter Svidler, Linares 2006"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5 Ne4 5. Bh4 c5 6. cxd5 Nxc3 7. bxc3 Qxd5 8.
e3 cxd4 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. cxd4 e6 11. Rb1 Be7 12. Bxe7 Kxe7 13. Bd3 Nc6 14. Nf3
b6 15. Ke2 Bb7 16. Rhc1 Rhc8 17. g4 h6 18. h4 Na5 19. g5 hxg5 20. hxg5 Rxc1 21.
Rxc1 Rc8 22. Rxc8 Bxc8 23. Ne5 Bb7
{ This is a game from 2006, played in Linares against Peter Svidler, who was higher rated than me at this point. The tournament is a special one for me, as it was my first super tournament win. Prior to this win, I finished first in the World Cup, which is also one of my greatest achievements, but winning the Wimbledon of chess occupies a special place in my memory.  I was White and we can argue that Black's pieces have slightly less activity, but in reality, without any weaknesses and White not having any serious plan, the game should end peacefully. Once I start pushing e4, f4, and then Ng4, e5, the pawn on d4 will become weak. Exchanging the bishops should also end in a draw if Black has activated the knight, while trading the knights is no better, as White doesn't have an entry point for the king.  Had the b6-pawn been on c7, that would have been a completely different picture. Nonetheless, just like in the previous examples, I just played, without thinking too much about the dryness of the position at hand. }
24. a3
{ I agree, it doesn't look very impressive, but I just wanted to keep the game going. }
24... Nc6 25. Ng4 Nb8 26. Kd2 Bc6
{ Perhaps, the reason behind the text move is that my opponent didn't want to calculate  26...Nd7  27.Bb5  Bf3  28.Nh2  Bd5  when I could go for the knight vs. bishop endgame with  29.Bxd7  Kxd7  30.Ng4  and try to irritate Black by attacking the pawn on f7. Objectively, this should be a dead draw after, for instance,  30...b5  or  30...Ke7  first,  31.Kc3  a5  32.Ne5+  b5  . White doesn't have a plan to improve the position. After  33.f3  , there is always  33...f6  and even if I would manage to put  the pawn on e4, there is no breakthrough. }
27. Kc3 Nd7 28. f4 a5 29. e4
{ Svidler started to get a bit nervous and his next move is the first indication that something was off. }
29... b5
{ Black's move already creates certain issues.   The easiest way to achieve a draw is by playing  29...f5  30.exf5   30.gxf6+  Nxf6  31.Nxf6  @@StartBracket@@After  31.Nf2  Nh5  , f4 is a weakness and  32.Nh3  Nf6  is just a draw.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@8/4k3/1pb1pNp1/p7/3PPP2/P1KB4/8/8 b - - 0 31@@EndFEN@@  31...Kxf6  and the white king cannot enter.  31...exf5  31.Ne5  Nxe5  32.dxe5  Bd7  . Black can simply wait since White doesn't have access to the c5-square.  33.Kd4  Bc6  and there is no way for White to force Black to commit with ...b5. }
30. Bc2
{ I am not really doing much and Black could simply wait with  30...Bb7  . Just as I mentioned in the previous examples, a typical error that occurs for the defensive side in those rather equal positions is to seek the draw immediately. Losing patience signals the first opportunity to be on the lookout for mistakes.   Still, if White tries to profit from the newly available square on c5 with  30.Ne5  Nxe5  31.dxe5  , the position continues to be defendable. A sample line is  31...Be8  32.Kd4  b4  33.axb4  axb4  34.Kc4  Ba4  35.Kxb4  Bd1  . Even after exchanging many pawns,  36.f5  exf5  37.exf5  gxf5  38.Bxf5  , there is no magic idea to win this endgame. }
30... f5 31. exf5 { Svidler thought he had it all covered but miscalculated. }
31... exf5
{ The only way to draw the game was by recapturing with the g-pawn  31...gxf5  , which looks rather odd as it hands White a passed pawn.  32.Ne5  Be4  is already very dangerous since Black has to be very precise and calculate all the possible trades.  33.Bxe4   How about  33.Nxd7  Kxd7  34.Bd1  , which could be potentially dangerous? Still, after  34...Ke7  35.Be2  Bc6  Black holds since White has no entry point, but why allow all of this when there were different and easier ways to draw?  33...fxe4  34.Nc6+  @@StartBracket@@I cannot go into the pawn endgame as after  34.Nxd7  Kxd7  35.Kd2  b4  , White is the one to lose the game.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@8/3nk3/2N1p3/pp4P1/3PpP2/P1K5/8/8 b - - 1 34@@EndFEN@@  34...Kf7  35.Nxa5  Nb6  , the knight is coming to d5 and the f4-pawn will fall. }
32. Ne5 Nxe5 33. dxe5
{ Now, the king has a clean route to c5 when Black will lose the b5-pawn. }
33... b4+
{ From afar, Svidler thought that after sacrificing the pawn, the resulting position is a dead draw. }
34. axb4 axb4+ 35. Kxb4 Bd7 36. Bb3 Bc6 37. Kc5
{ Around this point, my opponent realized there is a problem. } 37... Be8
{ After  37...Bf3  , White can bring the king to c7, but then how to continue? What is Black's weakness in this position?  38.Bg8  White is hinting at the vulnerable g6-pawn.  38...Be2  39.e6  , planning to attack the pawn from f7 since from h7, there is no real way to put Black in zugzwang.  39...Bf3  40.Bf7  Be4   40...Bh5  41.Kd5  Bf3+  42.Kd4  Bh5  43.Ke5  and Black is lost. The bishop is tied to the defense of the g6-pawn, while the king cannot allow White to enter. Sadly, it is Black to move and one of the two threats will be executed.  41.Bxg6  Kxe6  42.Bh5  Bg2  43.Be2  , White is bringing the bishop to c4, with a winning position.  43...Kf7   43...Bh1  44.Bc4+  Ke7  45.Kd4  , threatening to enter and win the f5-pawn. Black cannot prevent it with  45...Kd6  since  46.g6  allows me to promote.  44.Bd3  Kg6  45.Kd4  Bb7  46.Ke5  Bc8  47.Bb5  Zugzwang.  47...Kg7  @@StartBracket@@  47...Bb7  48.Be8  and the pawn is lost.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2b5/6k1/8/1B2KpP1/5P2/8/8/8 w - - 12 25@@EndFEN@@  48.Bc4  Kg6  49.Be6  . The pawn on f5 is falling anyway. }
38. e6
{ Instead, I could have played for the same Bg8, e6, and Bf7 idea, but the text move puts Black in zugzwang immediately. The bishop has no squares and the king must throw in the towel.   Let's try to understand what happened in this game. I played some normal moves, continued playing, did nothing spectacular, and just pushed a little bit. Black could have drawn the game immediately with @@StartFEN@@8/3nkp2/1pb1p1p1/p5P1/3PPPN1/P1KB4/8/8 b - - 0 29@@EndFEN@@  29...f5  but played  29...b5  instead. Furthermore, after @@StartFEN@@8/3nkp2/2b1p1p1/pp4P1/3PPPN1/P1KB4/8/8 w - - 0 30@@EndFEN@@  30.Bc2  , instead of patiently waiting with  30...Bb7  , he went for the commital  30...f5  .  I believe that Svidler got nervous mainly because of the ...b5 decision, which indicated that he wanted to achieve a draw proactively, which is a dangerous strategy.  The biggest risk in the positions where there is no real danger is trying too hard to get out of it. I have been on both sides of the coin, being too active and drowning, or seeing my opponents making the same mistake. It's like being in a swamp, the more you struggle, the deeper you sink in. }
*


