[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 1 â The Umbrella"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/8/7R/3k2P1/5p2/r7/5K2 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We are going to have a look at a couple of rook endgames that excite me, and prove to the nonbelievers that with just a few pieces on the board, there can be a lot of action! In this first example â White to play and draw.  However, obtaining half a point requires surgical precision, while punishing White for any mistake is also a special sight. Let's think together: what is the threat in the position?  Black is threatening to bring the king to e3 and if that is answered by a check on e5, the king will infiltrate via f4 and g3. It becomes apparent that without the pawn on g4, White would have an easy draw since the resulting endgame is the theoretical Philidor position.   Therefore, White could play @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/7R/3k4/5p2/r7/5K2 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Rb5  Ke3  2.Rb3+  Kf4  3.Rb8  and this would be sufficient for a draw, as Black cannot escape the checks.  Unfortunately, with the g4-pawn on the board, Black can use it as an umbrella against White's checks.  @@StartFEN@@1R6/8/8/8/5kP1/5p2/r7/5K2 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kg3  means game over since  4.Rb1  Rh2  is always a problem.  With the f-pawn, we cannot afford to have the first rank defense, which would be available had Black had the pawn on the g-file instead @@StartBracket@@there is no ...Ri2, to threaten a lethal check anymore@@EndBracket@@. White has to solve this issue and there are three logical moves for  that: Rh6, Rh7, and Rh8. Our job is to understand what is right and what is wrong. }
1. Rh7
{ A very elegant and spectacular solution!   A@@EndBracket@@ Let's see first what happens if White tries to defend with  1.Rf5  @@StartBracket@@pushing the pawn is not an option as ...Ke3 creates an immediate mating threat, which makes things even worse@@EndBracket@@.  1...Ke3  2.Kg1  Ra1+  3.Kh2  f2  Black will promote next since  4.Kg2  is met by  4...Rg1+  .  This is a straightforward and easy win.   B@@EndBracket@@  1.Rh8  Ke3  2.Re8+  Kf4  ,  as we know, ... Kg3 is a big threat. Which move do you think is the only one that makes sense for White?  3.g5  â we have to create counterplay, as running away with the king never helps.  3...Kg3  4.g6  . The point is that if Black plays  4...Ra1+  , it's not a big problem.  5.Re1  Rxe1+  6.Kxe1  and after the exchange, we promote simultaneously.  6...Kg2  7.g7  f2+  8.Kd2  f1=Q  9.g8=Q+  with a draw.  @@StartFEN@@4R3/8/6P1/8/8/5pk1/r7/5K2 b - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Rh2  5.Ke1  , we cannot allow mate on h1. @@StartBracket@@If now Black continues with  5...Rh1+  6.Kd2  f2  7.g7  , it is clear that White will also promote.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@4R3/8/6P1/8/8/5pk1/7r/4K3 b - - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...f2+  6.Ke2  @@StartBracket@@the only move, obviously, since  6.Kf1  is met by  6...Rh1+  and Black wins@@EndBracket@@. @@StartFEN@@4R3/8/6P1/8/8/6k1/4Kp1r/8 b - - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Kg2  ,  Black will win fairly simple from now on.  7.Rf8  Kg1  .  With the king's help, Black is threatening to promote.  8.Ke3  ,  getting away from the discovered check, but without any influence on the outcome of the game.  8...Rg2  is the final precise move. Instead,  8...f1=Q  allows White to survive after  9.Rxf1+  Kxf1  in view of  10.Kf4  .  The text move though forces White to accept the fact that the endgame is lost since the Figaro king is not in time to protect the  pawn on g6 with Kf4 and have the black pawn disappear too.  @@StartFEN@@5R2/8/6P1/8/8/4K3/5pr1/6k1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Rxf2  . Unfortunately, sacrificing the rook is no longer working in this position @@StartBracket@@but  9.g7  f1=Q  loses as well@@EndBracket@@. @@StartFEN@@8/8/6P1/8/8/4K3/5Rr1/6k1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Rxf2  10.Ke4  @@StartBracket@@Kf4 is impossible since the king is cut.@@EndBracket@@  10...Rf6  11.g7  Rg6  .  White loses the pawn and the game.  Therefore, we can conclude that 1.Rh8 is not the right answer. To understand the position further, if White had the option  of playing @@StartFEN@@5R2/8/6P1/8/8/4K3/5pr1/6k1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ke4  and Black wouldn't take  the pawn on g6 but would promote instead,  9...f1=Q  10.Rxf1  Kxf1  is still a draw in view of  11.Kf5  . So now we can ask ourselves, why don't we play 1.Rh6 on the first move?   C@@EndBracket@@  1.Rh6  Ke3  2.Re6+  Kf4  3.g5  ,  we get a similar structure as in the 1.Rh8 variation.  3...Kg3  4.g6  Rh2  5.Ke1  f2+  6.Ke2  Rh1   6...Kg2  7.Rf6  Kg1  8.Ke3  Rg2  repeating the same maneuver that was winning in the 1.Rh8 line.  9.Ke4  Rg5  might look like a smart move, cutting the king, but the Figaro is actually in time!   9...Rg4+  doesn't bring anything since after  10.Ke5  Rg5+  11.Ke6  ,  Black is not in time to sacrifice the rook on g6 and promote because Rxg6+ comes with check.  10.Kf4  Rxg6   10...f1=Q+  11.Kxg5  is quite an easy draw since White's pieces are far advanced.  11...Qc1+  12.Kh5  followed by g7 and White survives the day in this theoretical drawing position.  11.Rxg6+  Kh1  12.Rh6+  Kg2  13.Rg6+  and Black cannot escape the checks.  7.Rf6  of course, White could do this with the rook on e8 as well.  7...Re1+  8.Kd2   8.Kd3  is a possible move, but Black can play  8...Re7  . Therefore, the text move is more resilient.  8...Re7  @@StartBracket@@If Black is promoting  8...f1=Q  , this would even lose the game after  9.Rxf1  Rxf1  10.g7  .  Catch me if you can.  10...Rf2+  11.Ke1  and the pawn promotes. @@StartFEN@@8/4r3/5RP1/8/8/6k1/3K1p2/8 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  8...Re6  also doesn't work due to  9.g7  and White is out of danger since the pawn promotes with check.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@8/4r3/5RP1/8/8/6k1/3K1p2/8 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Rf5  is a very clever move. How to win now with Black? The solution is not an easy one and if you found it â Bravo!   The issue is that if Black tries to promote with  9...Kg2  , then  10.Rg5+  seems to secure a draw since the black king cannot escape from checks and support the f-pawn at the same time.  10...Kh3  11.Rf5  Kg3  , giving the move to the opponent with the triangulation method. @@StartBracket@@Now, the rook cannot move on the f-file since after  12.Rf6  Kg2  , there is no check on the g-file anymore, while @@StartFEN@@8/8/4r1P1/5R2/8/6k1/3K1p2/8 w - - 12 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Rg5+  is well met by  12...Kf4  @@EndBracket@@  .  @@StartFEN@@8/4r3/6P1/5R2/8/6k1/3K1p2/8 w - - 12 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Kd3  .  What now? I am very excited as I love this endgame, which is far from trivial! It is quite difficult in fact, and I hope you will find the winning continuation.   12.Kd1  , White's hope is to lure the black rook to e1:  12...Re1+  13.Kd2  when nothing happens. Black cannot promote since the g-pawn has fast legs as well. @@StartFEN@@8/4r3/6P1/5R2/8/6k1/5p2/3K4 b - - 13 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Kg2  13.Rg5+  Kh3  and Black is winning now.  14.Rf5   14.Rh5+  is hopeless due to  14...Kg4  15.Rh1  Kg3  and Black wins material following ...Kg2.  14...Re1+  15.Kd2  f1=Q  16.Rxf1  Rxf1  . With the king out of the way, nothing can stop the rook from capturing the lonely pawn.  12...Kg2  13.Rg5+  Kf1  .  Since the white king has moved, now the e1-square is in Black's hands.  14.Ra5  is also quite interesting and the same question applies: how to win here?   14.g7  Ke1  15.g8=Q  f1=Q+  , Black promotes with check and after  16.Kc3  or  16.Kd4  Qf6+  , Black will eventually mate with a couple of not-so-difficult checks. There are many different ways, but an illustrative line could be  17.Kc4  Qc6+  18.Rc5  Qa4+  19.Kd3   After  19.Kd5  , the least Black can do is  19...Rd7+  20.Ke5  @@StartBracket@@  20.Ke6  Qb3+  21.Kxd7  Qxg8  . Black has an easy win with the queen against the rook.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@6Q1/3r4/8/2R1K3/q7/8/8/4k3 b - - 9 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Qd4+  21.Ke6  Qd6+  .  The rook is lost and White is getting mated.  19...Qd1+  20.Kc4  Qe2+  .  Going into deeper details would be outside the scope of this example, especially since it is not so difficult either and you will surely find the way on your own.  21.Kd5  Qd3+  22.Kc6  Qd7+  23.Kb6  Qa7+  24.Kb5  @@StartBracket@@  24.Kc6  Rc7+  and Black wins.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@6Q1/q3r3/8/1KR5/8/8/8/4k3 b - - 17 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Rb7+  25.Kc4  Qa2+  and the queen is gone.  14...Re6  , attacking the pawn from the side, with the idea that after  15.g7  Rg6  ,  ...Kg2 can no longer be prevented since White has no more checks on the g-file.  16.Ra7  Kg2  and the f-pawn will promote next. Going for the frontal attack with @@StartFEN@@8/4r3/6P1/R7/8/3K4/5p2/5k2 b - - 17 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Rg7  will be answered by  15.Rg5  Ke1  16.Re5+  Kd1  17.Rf5  and White keeps checking the king and attacking the f-pawn.  Does that mean we should resign because 1.Rh8 and 1.Rh6 don't work? Of course not since, as the solution says, there is also the rather surprising 1.Rh7. }
1... Ke3 2. Re7+ Kf4 3. g5 Kg3 4. g6 Rh2 5. Rh7
{ The lifesaver is not  5.Ke1  but  5.Rh7  , as the g-pawn protects the rook and, therefore, White is able to salvage half a point. }
5... Rf2+ 6. Ke1 Ra2 7. Rf7 { And now the pawn advance brings Black nothing. }
7... f2+ 8. Rxf2 Rxf2 { Of course, Black shouldn't grab the rook. } 9. g7
{ With Black's help, it is now White's turn to promote. The @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/7R/3k2P1/5p2/r7/5K2 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Rh7  solution is also rather counterintuitive.  We would normally expect the rook to be on h8 and help the pawn promote. But here, h7 is the square to be, where the g-pawn will be able to support the rook and escape with a draw. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 1 â Puzzle #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/8/7R/3k2P1/5p2/r7/5K2 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Rh8 { Black has a straightforward winning plan, which one? } 1... Ke3 2.
Re8+ Kf4
{ As we know, ... Kg3 is a big threat. Which move do you think is the only one that makes sense for White? }
3. g5
{ We have to create counterplay, as running away with the king never helps. }
3... Kg3 4. g6
{ The point is that if Black plays  4...Ra1+  , it's not a big problem.  5.Re1  Rxe1+  6.Kxe1  and after the exchange, we promote simultaneously.  6...Kg2  7.g7  f2+  8.Kd2  f1=Q  9.g8=Q+  with a draw. }
4... Rh2 5. Ke1
{ We cannot allow mate on h1. If now Black continues with  5...Rh1+  6.Kd2  f2  7.g7  , it is clear that White will also promote. }
5... f2+ 6. Ke2
{ The only move, obviously, since  6.Kf1  is met by  6...Rh1+  . } 6... Kg2
{ Black will win fairly simple from now on. } 7. Rf8 Kg1
{ With the king's help, Black is now threatening to promote. } 8. Ke3
{ Getting away from the discovered check, but without any influence on the outcome of the game. }
8... Rg2
{ The final precise move. Instead,  8...f1=Q  allows White to survive after  9.Rxf1+  Kxf1  in view of  10.Kf4  . The text move though forces White  to accept the fact that the endgame is lost since the Figaro king is not in time to protect the pawn on g6 with Kf4, and have the black pawn disappear too. }
9. Rxf2
{ Unfortunately, sacrificing the rook is no longer working in this position. But also  9.g7  loses due to  9...f1=Q  . }
9... Rxf2 10. Ke4 { Kf4 is impossible since the king is cut. } 10... Rf6 11. g7
Rg6
{ White loses the pawn and the game. Therefore, we can conclude that 1.Rh8 is not the right answer. To understand the position further, if White had the option of playing @@StartFEN@@5R2/8/6P1/8/8/4K3/5pr1/6k1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ke4  and Black wouldn't take  the pawn on g6 but would promote instead,  9...f1=Q  10.Rxf1  Kxf1  is still a draw in view of  11.Kf5  . So now we can ask ourselves, why don't we play 1.Rh6 on the first move? See the next puzzle. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 1 â Puzzle #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/8/7R/3k2P1/5p2/r7/5K2 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Rh6
{ To refresh our memory, if White tries to defend with @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/7R/3k2P1/5p2/r7/5K2 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Rf5  @@StartBracket@@pushing the pawn is not an option as ...Ke3 creates an immediate mating threat, which makes things even worse@@EndBracket@@.  1...Ke3  2.Kg1  Ra1+  3.Kh2  f2  Black will promote next since  4.Kg2  is met by  4...Rg1+  .  This is a straightforward and easy win.   The text move, however, doesn't help White either. Find the route to victory for Black. }
1... Ke3 2. Re6+ Kf4 3. g5
{ We have a similar structure as in the 1.Rh8 variation. } 3... Kg3 4. g6 Rh2
5. Ke1 f2+ 6. Ke2 Rh1 7. Rf6
{ Of course, White could do this with the rook on e8 as well. } 7... Re1+ 8.
Kd2
{ 8.Kd3  is a possible move, but Black can play  8...Re7  . Therefore, the text move is more resilient. }
8... Re7
{ A@@EndBracket@@ If Black is promoting  8...f1=Q  , this would even lose the game after  9.Rxf1  Rxf1  10.g7  .  Catch me if you can.  10...Rf2+  11.Ke1  and the pawn promotes.   B@@EndBracket@@  8...Re6  also doesn't work due to  9.g7  and White is out of danger since the pawn promotes with check.  Ed.note: continued in the next puzzle. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 1 â Puzzle #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/4r3/5RP1/8/8/6k1/3K1p2/8 w - - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

9. Rf5
{ A very clever move. How to win now with Black? The solution is not an easy one and if you found it â Bravo! }
9... Kg2
{ The issue is that if Black tries to promote, then  10.Rg5+  seems to secure a draw since the black king cannot escape from checks and support the f-pawn at the same time. Or is it?! }
10. Rg5+ Kh3 11. Rf5 Kg3
{ Giving the move to the opponent with the triangulation method. Now, the rook cannot move on the f-file since after  12.Rf6  Kg2  , there is no check on the g-file anymore, while @@StartFEN@@8/8/4r1P1/5R2/8/6k1/3K1p2/8 w - - 12 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Rg5+  is well met by  12...Kf4  . }
12. Kd3
{ What now? I am very excited as I love this endgame, which is far from trivial! It is quite difficult in fact, and I hope you will find the winning continuation.   12.Kd1  White's hope is to lure the black rook to e1:  12...Re1+  13.Kd2  when nothing happens. Black cannot promote since the g-pawn has fast legs as well.  @@StartFEN@@8/4r3/6P1/5R2/8/6k1/5p2/3K4 b - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Kg2  13.Rg5+  Kh3  Black is winning now.  14.Rf5   14.Rh5+  is hopeless due to  14...Kg4  15.Rh1  Kg3  and Black wins material following ...Kg2.  14...Re1+  15.Kd2  f1=Q  16.Rxf1  Rxf1  . With the king out of the way, nothing can stop the rook from capturing the lonely pawn. }
12... Kg2 13. Rg5+ Kf1
{ Since the white king has moved, now the e1-square is in Black's hands. } 14.
g7
{ 14.Ra5  is also quite interesting and the same question applies: how to win here?  14...Re6  , attacking the pawn from the side, with the idea that after  15.g7  Rg6  ,  ...Kg2 can no longer be prevented since White has no more checks on the g-file.  16.Ra7  Kg2  and the f-pawn will promote next.  Going for the frontal attack with @@StartFEN@@8/4r3/6P1/R7/8/3K4/5p2/5k2 b - - 17 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Rg7  will be answered by  15.Rg5  Ke1  16.Re5+  Kd1  17.Rf5  and White keeps checking the king and attacking the f-pawn. }
14... Ke1 15. g8=Q f1=Q+
{ Black promotes with check and after  16.Kc3  or the text move, Black will eventually mate with a couple of not-so-difficult checks. }
16. Kd4 Qf6+
{ There are many different ways to win this endgame, but an illustrative line could be  17.Kc4  Qc6+  18.Rc5  Qa4+  19.Kd3   After  19.Kd5  , the least Black can do is  19...Rd7+  20.Ke5  @@StartBracket@@  20.Ke6  Qb3+  21.Kxd7  Qxg8  Black has an easy win with the queen against the rook.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@6Q1/3r4/8/2R1K3/q7/8/8/4k3 b - - 9 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Qd4+  21.Ke6  Qd6+  when the rook is lost and White is getting mated.  19...Qd1+  20.Kc4  Qe2+  .  Going into deeper details would be outside the scope of this example, especially since it is not so difficult either and you will surely find the way on your own.  21.Kd5  Qd3+  22.Kc6  Qd7+  23.Kb6  Qa7+  24.Kb5  @@StartBracket@@  24.Kc6  Rc7+  and Black wins.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@6Q1/q3r3/8/1KR5/8/8/8/4k3 b - - 17 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Rb7+  25.Kc4  Qa2+  and the queen is gone. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 1 â Puzzle #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/4R1P1/8/8/6k1/4Kp1r/8 b - - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

6... Kg2
{ Black's move is a blunder and now White can salvage half a point. How? } 7.
Rf6 Kg1 8. Ke3 Rg2
{ Repeating the same maneuver that was winning in the 1.Rh8 line. } 9. Ke4 Rg5
{ This might look like a smart move, cutting the king, but the Figaro is actually in time!   9...Rg4+  doesn't bring anything since after  10.Ke5  Rg5+  11.Ke6  Black is not in time to sacrifice the rook on g6 and promote because Rxg6+ comes with check. }
10. Kf4 Rxg6
{ 10...f1=Q+  11.Kxg5  is quite an easy draw since White's pieces are far advanced.  11...Qc1+  12.Kh5  followed by g7 and White survives the day in this theoretical drawing position. }
11. Rxg6+ Kh1 12. Rh6+ Kg2 13. Rg6+ { Black cannot escape the checks. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 1 â Puzzle #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/8/7R/3k2P1/5p2/r7/5K2 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We should know by now that Black is threatening to bring the king to e3 and if that is answered by a check on e5, the king will infiltrate via f4 and g3. It becomes apparent that without the pawn on g4, White would have an easy draw since the resulting endgame is the theoretical Philidor position.   Therefore, White could play @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/7R/3k4/5p2/r7/5K2 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Rb5  Ke3  2.Rb3+  Kf4  3.Rb8  and this would be sufficient for a draw, as Black cannot escape the checks.  Unfortunately, with the g4-pawn on the board, Black can use it as an umbrella against White's checks.  @@StartFEN@@1R6/8/8/8/5kP1/5p2/r7/5K2 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kg3  means game over since  4.Rb1  Rh2  is always a problem.  With the f-pawn, we cannot afford to have the first rank defense, which would be available had Black had the pawn on the g-file instead @@StartBracket@@there is no ...Ri2, to threaten a lethal check anymore@@EndBracket@@. White has to solve this issue, and the question is how? }
1. Rh7 { A very elegant and spectacular solution! } 1... Ke3 2. Re7+ Kf4 3. g5
Kg3 4. g6 Rh2 5. Rh7
{ The lifesaver is not  5.Ke1  but  5.Rh7  , as the g-pawn protects the rook and, therefore, White is able to rescue half a point. }
5... Rf2+ 6. Ke1 Ra2 7. Rf7
{ Black cannot play  7...f2+  due to  8.Rxf2  Rxf2  9.g7  and the pawn promotes.  The @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/7R/3k2P1/5p2/r7/5K2 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Rh7  solution is also rather counterintuitive.  We would normally expect the rook to be on h8 and help the pawn promote. But here, h7 is the square to be, where the g-pawn will be able to support the rook and escape with a draw. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 2 â The Pawn on the Fifth Rank"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5k2/1R6/4K3/4P3/8/8/8/3r4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We have another beautiful endgame in front of us, which is also something to torture people with. White to play and win. We have to be careful though as losing time is not an option. }
1. Rf7+
{ Probably you know that with the black rook on e1, say, after  1.Ra7  Re1  ,  we get the Philidor position. White cannot progress as after  2.Ra5  , Black can just wait with  2...Re2  3.Kd7  Kf7  and the pawn has to drop any promotion dreams.   1.Rb8+  idea leads to a draw unless White realizes in time that after  1...Kg7  , returning to the initial diagram with  2.Rb7+  is the right path, admitting that 1.Rb8+ was the wrong direction. @@StartFEN@@1R6/6k1/4K3/4P3/8/8/8/3r4 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Ke7  Ra1  3.Rb7  Ra8  4.e6  .  A very tricky position and, in fact, many strong players made a mistake here.  4...Kg6  is a very important move.   If you lose your concentration for one second only and play a move like  4...Rc8  , this would lead to a theoretically lost position.  5.Ra7  Rb8  .  Now, just like in the previous example, White has to give the move to Black.  6.Kd6+   6.Ra1  Rb7+  7.Kd6  Rb6+  8.Kd7  Rb7+  9.Kc6  Rb2  10.Rf1  Ra2  would be a draw since Black gets now enough squares for the rook, to check the white king from a fair distance on the a-file.  6...Kf6  7.Kd7  Kg7  8.Ke7  .  This might look a bit odd but the reason is that White wants to bring the rook down to a1, but in a better version than before the triangulation has been executed.  After  8...Kg6  ,  the solution is nice and not trivial at all.   8...Rc8  9.Ra1  and Black doesn't have enough squares available for the rook to deliver disturbing checks from the side.  9...Rc7+  10.Kd8  ,  White will promote soon.   8...Rb1  9.Ra8  Rb7+  10.Kd6  Rb6+  11.Kd7  Rb7+  12.Kc6  . The rook is deprived of any squares. After  12...Rb1  , White will simply promote, while  12...Re7  doesn't save the house from fire either.  13.Kd6  and White will, once again, promote since  13...Kf6  14.Rf8+  loses the rook.  9.Ra1  Rb7+  10.Kd8  Kf6   10...Rb8+  11.Kc7  Rb3  12.Re1  .  If we compare this position and we try to do the same thing with the black king on g7, without giving Black the move,  @@StartFEN@@8/2K3k1/4P3/8/8/1r6/8/R7 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  10.Re1  doesn't achieve much in view of  10...Kf8  .  Here though, the pawn controls the f7-square and will promote unhindered.  11.e7  Rb8+   11...Rxe7  12.Rf1+  Ke6  13.Re1+  and Black loses the rook.  12.Kc7  Re8  13.Kd6  Rb8  14.Rf1+  Kg7  15.Kc7  Ra8  16.Ra1  .  A very important move, distracting the black rook from its duty of defending the back rank.  16...Re8  17.Kd7  and White is winning since the king cannot protect the rook with  17...Kf7  due to  18.Rf1+  .  5.Rb1  @@StartBracket@@  5.Kd7  Kf6  and White is unable to make progress, Black's pieces are fully mobilized to stop the pawn's march.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r7/4K3/4P1k1/8/8/8/8/1R6 b - - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ra7+  6.Kd6  Ra6+  7.Kd7  Ra7+  .  The black rook has too many squares and the white king is unable to escape from checks and protect the pawn simultaneously. Once the king steps on the c-file, the rook won't be under attack and Black will be able to bring the king closer by playing ...Kf6.   To recap, making a draw in the @@StartFEN@@5k2/1R6/4K3/4P3/8/8/8/3r4 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Rb8+  variation is possible thanks to the @@StartFEN@@r7/1R2K1k1/4P3/8/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kg6  resource.  Just play ...Kg6 and ...Kg7, without touching the rook on a8! }
1... Kg8
{ The right direction and the most stubborn defense as well.   After  1...Ke8  , White has an easy win.  2.Ra7  Kd8  .  The king cannot be redirected towards the long side of the board @@StartBracket@@determined by the opponent's pawn location@@EndBracket@@, as that is known to bring trouble.  3.Ra8+  Kc7  4.Kf6  .  It becomes clear that now the black rook will not have enough squares available on the short side of the board, to deliver the saving checks.  4...Rh1  5.e6  Rh6+  6.Kf7  Rh7+  7.Kg6  and the winning mechanism is similar to the one when the rook is on the long side of the board, but on the b-file, which we know it is losing for Black.  7...Re7  8.Kf6  .  White wins easily from here on. }
2. Rd7
{ 2.Ra7  seems logical, but, unfortunately for us, it is not winning.  2...Re1  3.Kd6  @@StartBracket@@  3.Kf6  Rf1+  and now White doesn't have  4.Ke7  since after  4...Rf7+  , the rook is lost.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@6k1/R7/3K4/4P3/8/8/8/4r3 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kf8  and there's no way through. }
2... Re1
{ 2...Ra1  3.Kf6  .  As we determined in the previous example, defending on the eighth rank is not working.  3...Ra8  4.e6  and White has the winning Rg7-h7 mechanism. The back-rank defense works only when the pawn is on the b- or g-files. }
3. Kf6 Rf1+ 4. Ke7 Ra1
{ If you think this is over, you are wrong, the position is still very tricky. }
5. Rd2
{ A@@EndBracket@@ If you thought about the text move or  5.Rd3  @@StartBracket@@even  5.Rd4  wins@@EndBracket@@, you were right. White has to bring the rook down the d-file, with the idea of giving a check on the g-file, cutting the black king further away from the pawn.   B@@EndBracket@@ Going for  5.Ke8  is just wrong due to  5...Ra8+  6.Rd8  Ra6  and Black is already out of danger.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.e6  is also a bad idea, as  5...Kg7  is a known way to defend.  6.Ke8+   6.Kd8+  Kf6  7.e7  Ra8+  8.Kc7  and now Black has  8...Ra7  , but also  8...Ke6  9.Rd8  Ra7+  , where White loses the pawn.  6...Kf6  .  Here comes the nice part.  7.e7  Ke6  ,  White's rook location is playing tricks on us. Had it been elsewhere to deliver a check, the position would have been winning for us. And after  8.Kf8  Black has the saving  @@StartBracket@@  8.Kd8  is no better.  8...Ra8+  9.Kc7  Re8  and White has to settle for a draw.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@5K2/3RP3/4k3/8/8/8/8/r7 b - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Rf1+  with a draw. }
5... Ra7+ 6. Kf6
{ White is threatening Rd8+, therefore, Black's next move is rather forced. }
6... Rf7+ 7. Ke6 Rf1
{ This is another important moment when White can win in different ways, but there is only one clear-cut and technical win. Can you see it? }
8. Ra2
{ The idea is now apparent: White takes away the a-file from Black's rook and prepares to give a check on a8. We should know by now this winning maneuver, when the black rook is forced onto the b-file, from where it will not have enough squares to deliver the saving checks.   8.Ke7  is still winning, but after  8...Rf7+  , White has to admit that was the wrong direction and return to e6 since after  9.Kd8  Ra7  10.e6  Kf8  , the position is a draw. Perhaps you wonder what happens after  11.Rf2+  Kg7  12.e7  , but Black's rook is far enough from the white king and able to hold a draw.  12...Ra8+  13.Kd7  Ra7+  14.Kd6  Ra6+  15.Kd5   Black is going to check White forever since  15.Kc5  runs into  15...Re6  and with the white king cut, the e-pawn is lost.  15...Ra5+  16.Kc6  Ra6+  There is nothing White can do against those continuous checks. }
8... Kg7 { Now again, White has to be careful: Ra7 or Ra8? } 9. Ra7+
{ 9.Ra8  would gift Black half a point, as  9...Re1  is an idea you should never forget about! }
9... Kg6 10. Kd6
{ Remember the position when the king was on g8 and we couldn't enter on e7 because of ...Rf7+? Here we have a similar story, but we can win by luring the rook first. }
10... Rd1+ 11. Ke7
{ White has reached the winning position, as Black's rook is doomed to the losing b-file for the rook. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 2 â Puzzle #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5k2/1R6/4K3/4P3/8/8/8/3r4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Rb8+
{ This check should already give Black hopes since it indicates the start of a wrong idea. The position will be a draw unless White realizes in time that after Black's next move, returning to the initial diagram with 2.Rb7+ is the right path, admitting that 1.Rb8+ was the wrong direction. }
1... Kg7 2. Ke7 Ra1 3. Rb7 Ra8 4. e6
{ A very tricky position and, in fact, many strong players made a mistake here. }
4... Kg6 { This is a very important move. } 5. Rb1
{ If  5.Kd7  Kf6  and White is unable to make progress, Black's pieces are fully mobilized to stop the pawn's march. }
5... Ra7+ 6. Kd6 Ra6+ 7. Kd7 Ra7+
{ The black rook has too many squares and the white king is unable to escape from checks and protect the pawn simultaneously. Once the king steps on the c-file, the rook won't be under attack and Black will be able to bring the king closer by playing ...Kf6.   To recap, making a draw in the @@StartFEN@@5k2/1R6/4K3/4P3/8/8/8/3r4 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Rb8+  variation is possible thanks to the @@StartFEN@@r7/1R2K1k1/4P3/8/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kg6  resource.  Just play ...Kg6 and ...Kg7, without touching the rook on a8! }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 2 â Puzzle #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r7/1R2K1k1/4P3/8/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

4... Rc8
{ If you lose your concentration for one second only and play a move like ...Rc8, this would lead to a theoretically lost position. }
5. Ra7 Rb8
{ Now, just like in the previous example, White has to give the move to Black. }
6. Kd6+
{ 6.Ra1  Rb7+  7.Kd6  Rb6+  8.Kd7  Rb7+  9.Kc6  Rb2  10.Rf1  Ra2  would be a draw since Black gets now enough squares for the rook, to check the white king from a fair distance on the a-file. }
6... Kf6 7. Kd7 Kg7 8. Ke7
{ This might look a bit odd but the reason is that White wants to bring the rook down to a1, but in a better version than before the triangulation has been executed. }
8... Kg6
{ After the text move, the solution is nice and not trivial at all.   A@@EndBracket@@  8...Rc8  9.Ra1  and Black doesn't have enough squares available for the rook to deliver disturbing checks from the side.  9...Rc7+  10.Kd8  and White will promote.   B@@EndBracket@@  8...Rb1  9.Ra8  Rb7+  10.Kd6  Rb6+  11.Kd7  Rb7+  12.Kc6  . The rook is deprived of any squares. After  12...Rb1  , White will simply promote, while  12...Re7  doesn't save the house from fire either.  13.Kd6  and White will, once again, promote since  13...Kf6  14.Rf8+  loses the rook. }
9. Ra1 Rb7+ 10. Kd8 Kf6
{ 10...Rb8+  11.Kc7  Rb3  12.Re1  .  If we compare this position and we try to do the same thing with the black king on g7, without giving Black the move,  @@StartFEN@@8/2K3k1/4P3/8/8/1r6/8/R7 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  10.Re1  doesn't achieve much in view of  10...Kf8  .  Here though, the pawn controls the f7-square and will promote unhindered. }
11. e7
{ A@@EndBracket@@  11...Rxe7  12.Rf1+  Ke6  13.Re1+  and Black loses the rook.   B@@EndBracket@@  11...Rb8+  12.Kc7  Re8  13.Kd6  Rb8  14.Rf1+  Kg7  15.Kc7  Ra8  16.Ra1  . A very important move, distracting the black rook from its duty on defending the back rank.  16...Re8  17.Kd7  and White is winning since the king cannot protect the rook with  17...Kf7  due to  18.Rf1+  . }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 2 â Puzzle #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5k2/1R6/4K3/4P3/8/8/8/3r4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We have another beautiful endgame in front of us, which is also something to torture people with. White to play and win. We have to be careful though as losing time is not an option. }
1. Rf7+ Kg8
{ The right direction and the most stubborn defense as well.   After  1...Ke8  , White has an easy win.  2.Ra7  Kd8  .  The king cannot be redirected towards the long side of the board @@StartBracket@@determined by the opponent's pawn location@@EndBracket@@, as that is known to bring trouble.  3.Ra8+  Kc7  4.Kf6  .  It becomes clear that now the black rook will not have enough squares available on the short side of the board, to deliver the saving checks.    4...Rh1  5.e6  Rh6+  6.Kf7  Rh7+  7.Kg6  and the winning mechanism is similar to the one when the rook is on the long side of the board, but on the b-file, which we know it is losing for Black.  7...Re7  8.Kf6  .  White wins easily from here on. }
2. Rd7 Re1
{ 2...Ra1  3.Kf6  .  As we determined in the previous example, defending on the eighth rank is not working.  3...Ra8  4.e6  and White has the winning Rg7-h7 mechanism. The back-rank defense works only when the pawn is on the b- or g-files. }
3. Kf6 Rf1+ 4. Ke7 Ra1
{ If you think this is over, you are wrong, the position is still very tricky. }
5. Rd2
{ If you thought about the text move or  5.Rd3  @@StartBracket@@even  5.Rd4  wins@@EndBracket@@, you were right. White has to bring the rook down the d-file, with the idea of giving a check on the g-file, cutting the black king further away from the pawn.   Going for  5.Ke8  is just wrong due to  5...Ra8+  6.Rd8  Ra6  and Black is already out of danger.   Ed. note: continued in the next puzzle. }
*


