[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 3 â White to play"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5r2/8/6k1/8/1R6/1KP5/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is the third example I absolutely love as well and had to share with you. White to play and the question is: how would you assess the position? If you think it is a draw, you are right.  What if it is Black to move here? If you believe that White is winning, you are right once again! As surprising as that sounds, whoever has to start first, will be detrimental â we have a mutual zugzwang. Let's analyze this position with White to move first. }
1. Re4
{ Since the king is far away from the c-pawn, we can try to cut the king.   A@@EndBracket@@ If we play  1.Rb6+  instead  , Black will reply  1...Kf7  2.Kb4  Ke7  and the draw is rather simple, as Black can bring the king over and equalize without much concern.   B@@EndBracket@@ Activating the king with  1.Ka4  doesn't work either.  1...Rc8  attacking the pawn and pointing out the weird location of White's rook on b4.  2.Rb6+  @@StartBracket@@  2.c4  doesn't bring anything since after  2...Kf6  , the king is too fast and the game will end in a draw.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2r5/8/1R4k1/8/K7/2P5/8/8 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Kf7  3.Kb4  Ke7  4.c4  Kd7  Black is in time to organize the defense and reach the Philidor position.   C@@EndBracket@@ The straightforward  1.c4  is met by the same fast runner:  1...Kf6  . White cannot prevent Black from bringing the king into the defense. }
1... Kf5 2. Re1 Rb8+ 3. Ka4 Ra8+ 4. Kb4 Rb8+ 5. Ka5 Rc8
{ White has to protect the pawn somehow. } 6. Re3
{ 6.Rc1  Ke6  is also a theoretical draw since the black king is now too close and ready to defend. }
6... Kf4
{ The black king will be able to enter, as otherwise, White loses the pawn. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Exciting Rook Endgames"]
[Black "Example 3 â Black to play"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5r2/8/6k1/8/1R6/1KP5/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Now, let's see why the position is lost with Black to move. } 1... Rf1
{ A@@EndBracket@@ The immediate  1...Kf7  , trying to bring the king closer, fails to  2.Rf4+  and the pawn endgame is winning for White.   B@@EndBracket@@  1...Kf5  2.Rb6  .  White cuts the black king, which is also a known procedure to prevent Black from organizing the defense in a timely manner.  2...Ke5  3.Kb4  Rc8  4.c4  White will slowly promote the pawn.  4...Kd4  is an attempt to catch up with the pawn when the idea behind cutting the king becomes transparent.  5.Rd6+  Ke5  6.c5  and Black just cannot approach the pawn, as the king is cut off.   C@@EndBracket@@  1...Rc8  2.Rf4  .  We can see now the difference between having the king cut on the e- or f-files. Previously, we have seen the position with the king cut on the e-file, which is a draw â the king is too close. Here, the black king is too far and the win becomes trivial.    2...Kg5  3.Rf1  Rb8+  4.Ka4  Rc8  5.Kb4  Rb8+  6.Ka5  Rc8  7.Rc1  .  The black king will try to quickly prevent the imminent but to no avail.  7...Kf6  8.c4  Ke7  9.Kb6  Rb8+  , what else?  9...Kd7  is well met by  10.Rd1+  and the pawn will start running. @@StartFEN@@1r6/4k3/1K6/8/2P5/8/8/2R5 w - - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Kc7  followed by c4-c5-c6 and the rook has no way to give check and rescue the position.   Chessable note: in the C@@EndBracket@@ line given by Aronian in the video, instead of @@StartFEN@@1r6/8/8/6k1/8/1KP5/8/5R2 w - - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ka4  White should opt for  4.Kc4  . Being aware of our opponent's resources is always recommended.   4.Ka4  doesn't spoil the advantage, but it already indicates that White is overly optimistic in this position, especially if after  4...Rc8  5.Kb4  Rb8+  6.Ka5  Rc8  , White will go for  7.Rc1  , which would be a blunder. Following  7...Kf4!   7...Kf6?  would return the favor.  8.c4  Ke7  9.Kb6  Kd7  10.Rd1+  Ke7  11.c5  and White wins.  8.c4  Ke3  9.Kb4   9.c5  Kd2  10.Rc4  Kd3  with a draw.  9...Kd2  and White doesn't have enough time to coordinate the pieces. After  10.Rh1  Rb8+  11.Kc5  Rc8+  12.Kd5  Rd8+  13.Ke6  Rc8  , White will either lose the pawn or accept the fact that there is no way forward.  Back to @@StartFEN@@1r6/8/8/6k1/8/1KP5/8/5R2 w - - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Kc4  Rc8+  5.Kd4  Rd8+  6.Ke5  , White is hitting two birds with one stone: shouldering Black's king, while supporting the pawn as well.  6...Re8+  7.Kd6  Rc8  8.Rc1  . This works now as Black's saving idea in the previous line,  with ...Kf4-e3-d2 no longer works. The c-pawn is too fast. }
2. Re4 { White has a strange yet winning plan here. } 2... Kf5 3. Re2
{ Wait for a second! Black's king is separated from White's pawn by only two files, you might wonder... The issue is that White is in time to push the pawn to c4 when two files will prove enough for a win. In other words, there is a big difference between having the pawn on c3 or c4. }
3... Rb1+ 4. Ka4 Rb8 5. c4 Rc8 6. Kb5 Rb8+ 7. Ka6 Rc8 8. Rc2 Ke4
{ Or  8...Ke5  , which is similar, while after  8...Ke6  9.Kb7  Rc5  10.Kb6  White wins as well. }
9. Kb7 Rc5 10. Kb6 Rc8
{ 10...Kd4  is a very naive way to protect the rook.  11.Rd2+  Kxc4  12.Rc2+  . Game over. }
11. c5 Kd5 12. c6
{ Black has no more resources and will soon resign, creating this paradox that having an extra tempo in the initial position is actually a damaging factor. I hope that you enjoyed those examples and got to learn something too! }
*


