[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Vicious Endgame Tricks"]
[Black "Alexei Shirov vs. Levon Aronian, Moscow 2006"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3
d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 c6 12. d4 Bd6 13. Re1 Qh4 14. g3 Qh3 15.
Re4 g5 16. Qf1 Qh5 17. Nd2 Bf5 18. f3 Nf6 19. a4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 Qg6 21. Nxd6
Qxd6 22. Bxg5 Qg6 23. Qc1 Bd3 24. axb5 axb5 25. Rxa8 Rxa8 26. Kf2 Bc4 27. Bxc4
bxc4 28. g4 Re8 29. Bf4 Qd3 30. Kg3 Qe2 31. Qb1 Qe1+ 32. Qxe1 Rxe1 33. Bd6 Rg1+
34. Kf2 Rb1 35. Ba3 Kg7 36. Kg3 Kg6 37. h3 h5 38. Kh4 Rg1 39. Bc5 Rg2 40. Ba3
f6 41. gxh5+ Kf5 42. f4
{ This is a chapter on two vicious tricks that I've managed to pull on opponents in a classical game. While I've pulled many of them, these two brought me victories, where most of the time such tricks only lead to a draw. The first of these two tricks is from my game against Alexei Shirov in the Tal Memorial.If we take a look at the position, it is clear that Black is better. It is an endgame where I have a rook against a bishop, and it almost feels like a zugzwang.But at this moment it is Black to move, and if I play  42...Kxf4  , Shirov will play  43.h6  when I need to come back with  43...Rg8  , as he wants to promote. And in this position, White is in time. He'll play  44.Kh5  with ideas of h7, so I have to give him a check with  44...Rg5+  when it's a draw. }
42... Rg8
{ I thought about this and I saw that  42...Rg8  ,  immediately threatens to take on f4 with the king. }
43. Bd6 Ke6
{ I'm trying to bring my king back to f7, and only then create the zugzwang. For example, if he plays something along the lines of  44.Ba3  I can play  44...Kf7  45.Bd6  Rg2  46.Ba3  Kg7  with a zugzwang. White loses the pawn on b2 after  47.Bb4  Rxb2  , but losing the pawn isn't even the main problem for White here, as Black also threatens  48.--  Rxb4  49.cxb4  c3  ,  after which the c-pawn promotes.   Something that looked very dangerous for me is if White plays  44.h6  here. Because if I take with  44...Kxd6  and he plays  45.Kh5  , then what am I supposed to do here? White threatens  45...Ke7  46.h7  in order to promote the pawn. In this position, I might even be losing.At this point in the game I was thinking about all these lines and having seen all of them, I was actually very excited about it. }
44. h6
{ Alexei thought for maybe 20 minutes, and when he played  44.h6  . I could see that his eyes were shining. He thought that I had blundered something.What do you think is wrong with White's idea and plan in general? What is the vicious trick I pulled on my opponent here? }
44... Kxd6 { Yeah, the trick is that I do take the bishop! } 45. Kh5 f5
{ And after this, although it seems like White is winning, White is actually dead lost because the king is getting trapped. }
46. h7 Rh8 47. Kg6 Ke7 48. Kg7 Ke8
{ And at this moment Alexei understood everything. He continued for a couple more moves. }
49. Kg6 Kf8 50. h4 Ke7
{ I'm basically rotating my king and forcing him to use all of his moves before giving my rook away. }
51. Kg7 Ke8 52. Kg6 Kf8 { Continuing the triangulation. } 53. h5 Ke7 54. Kg7
Ke8 55. Kg6 Kf8 56. h6 { Now, of course, we continue in the same way. } 56...
Ke8 57. Kf6 Rxh7 { But here's the funny part. I just took. } 58. Kg6
{ And now it looks like he might have a chance if I play  58...Rh8  59.Kg7  Rf8  60.h7  Rh8  , but you know it's going to be the same problem anyway. His extra h-pawn isn't changing anything. }
58... Rf7
{ I went for  58...Rf7  with the same idea and Alexei resigned. So that's one vicious trick. We'll soon have a look at vicious trick number two, which was even more vicious. }
