*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Vicious Endgame Tricks"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Viswanathan Anand, Linares, 2007"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bf5 6. g3 Nbd7 7. Nc3 e6 8.
Bg2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Ne4 11. Qb3 Qb6 12. Nh4 Bxh4 13. gxh4 Nef6 14. e4
Bg6 15. Qxb6 axb6 16. Bf4 Rfe8 17. Rad1 b5 18. Bd6 e5 19. d5 Nh5 20. Bf1 f6 21.
b3 Nf4 22. a4 bxa4 23. bxa4 Bf7 24. Rb1 Ra7 25. Red1 Rc8 26. Ne2 Nxe2+ 27. Bxe2
cxd5 28. exd5 Nf8 29. Bb5 Raa8 30. Be7
{ This is my game against Viswanathan Anand from the 2007 Morelia Linares tournament. }
30... Ng6
{ I thought for quite some time after 30...Ng6 and found a vicious trick that I want you to find. It's a difficult but very interesting one. }
31. d6
{ Yes! The vicious trick is  31.d6  . This move is, of course, also logical. }
31... Nxe7
{ The problem is that  32.dxe7  just leads to a draw. Normally, people would abandon calculating this because after  32...Be8  33.Bxe8  Rxe8  34.Rd8  , there is not much left to play for.  Instead, the automatic @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/1p2P1pp/5p2/4p3/P6P/8/5P1P/1R1R2K1 w - - 0 34@@EndFEN@@  34.Rxb7?  would be a terrible blunder, as after  34...Rxa4  , the tables are suddenly turned.  35.Rd8  is not harmful in any way since Black has the  35...Kf7  resource.  The pawn on h4 is falling, the e7-pawn is neutralized â Black is technically winning. }
32. Bd7
{ But I had this in mind, and first played this intermezzo. Now, Anand cannot really move his rook anywhere.If he goes, let's say,  32...Rcb8  33.dxe7  Be8  , I now have a check.  34.Be6  and Black cannot play  34...Bf7  because of  35.Rxb7  Bxe6  36.Rxb8+  Rxb8  37.Rd8+  when I win the game.   Black cannot play  32...Rcb8  , but he does have a solution that is very difficult to find, and Anand didn't find it. Black had to immediately target my pawn on d6 with the crazy  32...Nf5  that would save him. Black is basically giving away his knight for free.  33.Bxf5  Rd8  . The idea behind it is that Black is setting up a blockade and then with  34.--  g6  ,  push the bishop away from the h3-c8 diagonal.   Therefore,  32...Nf5  was a move that would save Black because after  33.Bxc8  Rxc8  34.Rxb7  Rd8  ,  the knight will move to d4. Afterwards, Black will manage to attack and take my d-pawn, and then sacrifice his bishop for my a-pawn. This would lead to a dead draw, but it's difficult to find. }
32... Nc6
{ 32...Ng6  would also be an option, but it's just losing because I can take  33.Bxc8  Rxc8  34.Rxb7  when Black is losing because he cannot stop both of my pawns.  34...Rd8  35.a5  Bc4  36.Rc1  Bd5  37.a6  and Black's pieces are not coordinated enough to stop the advance of my pawns. }
33. Rxb7 Nd4
{ Hoping to stop the d-pawn, but there is a problem which I hope you will see. }
34. Bxc8 Rxc8 { What's the way for White to win this? } 35. Rdb1
{ Correct, White is now threatening to exchange rooks and then nothing can stop White's pawns from promoting. Anand understood that exchanging rooks is hopeless, and the checks don't really give him any relief.For example,  35...Nf3  36.Kh1  Bd5  is all very good and impressive, but I'm just promoting.  37.Rb8  , the checks are not leading anywhere.  37...Nxh4+  38.f3  and I'll just give you what you want, I will give you hundreds of pawns. But only the a4 and d6-pawns matter. }
35... Rf8 36. Rb8 Be8
{ And here I played a very nice move, which is the easiest to win. What do you think? }
37. a5 { Yes, one more vicious move. } 37... Nf3+ 38. Kf1
{ I believe  38.Kh1  was giving him more chances because of  38...Bc6  where I felt Black would get some counterplay. Instead, I thought to just give him my rook on b1. }
38... Nd2+ 39. Ke1 Nxb1 40. a6 Bc6 41. a7
{ I'm basically promoting and getting a new queen. } 41... Kf7 42. d7 Ke7
{ To stop the queen from appearing. } 43. Rxf8 Kxd7 44. a8=Q Bxa8 45. Rxa8
{ Of course, it would have been a completely different story if Black's knight would have been on d4, which would have been a dead draw. But for the knight to get from b1 to d4 he has to go all the way through c3 and b5. While the knight is doing that, I will just capture those pawns. }
45... h5 46. Ra7+ Ke6 47. Rxg7
{ Now I'm threatening to play Rh7 and capture the pawn. } 47... Kf5
{ This loses immediately. So what is the win here? } 48. Rg3
{ Correct,  48.Rg3  and the knight is trapped. There is no defense  against Rb3, which I'm going to play on the next move and then take the knight. So these were the two tricky games. Of course, I have many more examples, but I think that these two are the most famous displays of my inner trickiness. }
*


