35... Nf3+ { What is White's plan here? } 36. Kh1 Bd5
{ This is all very good and impressive, but the d-pawn is just promoting. } 37.
Rb8 { The checks are not leading anywhere. } 37... Nxh4+ 38. f3
{ We'll just give Black what he wants. Only the a4 and d6-pawns matter. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Vicious Endgame Tricks"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Viswanathan Anand â Puzzle #14"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r3k1/1R3bpp/3P1p2/4p3/P2n3P/8/5P1P/1R4K1 b - - 1 35"]
[SetUp "1"]

35... Rf8
{ In Puzzle #12 White threatened to exchange rooks, after which the pawns would become unstoppable. How can White accomplish that here? }
36. Rb8 { Immediately pinning the black rook against the king. } 36... Be8
{ And here I played a very nice move, which is the easiest to win. What do you think? }
37. a5 { Yes, one more vicious move. We continue in Puzzle #15. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Vicious Endgame Tricks"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Viswanathan Anand â Puzzle #15"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1R2brk1/6pp/3P1p2/P3p3/3n3P/8/5P1P/1R4K1 b - - 0 37"]
[SetUp "1"]

37... Nf3+ { Where does our king go? } 38. Kf1
{ I believe  38.Kh1  was giving him more chances because of  38...Bc6  where I felt Black would get some counterplay. Instead, I thought to just give him my rook on b1. }
38... Nd2+ 39. Ke1 Nxb1 40. a6 Bc6 41. a7
{ I'm basically promoting and getting a new queen. We continue in the next variation. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Vicious Endgame Tricks"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Viswanathan Anand â Puzzle #16"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1R3rk1/P5pp/2bP1p2/4p3/7P/8/5P1P/1n2K3 b - - 0 41"]
[SetUp "1"]

41... Kf7
{ Anand is bringing his king into play in an attempt to prevent the d-pawn from promoting. How do we continue? }
42. d7 Ke7 { To stop the queen from appearing. } 43. Rxf8 Kxd7 44. a8=Q Bxa8
45. Rxa8
{ Of course, it would have been a completely different story if Black's knight would have been on d4, which would have been a dead draw. But for the knight to get from b1 to d4 he has to go all the way through c3 and b5. While the knight is doing that, I will just capture those pawns. We take a look at the conclusion of the game in the next variation. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Vicious Endgame Tricks"]
[Black "Levon Aronian vs. Viswanathan Anand â Puzzle #17"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "R7/3k2pp/5p2/4p3/7P/8/5P1P/1n2K3 b - - 0 45"]
[SetUp "1"]

45... h5 { How did Aronian finish the game? } 46. Ra7+ Ke6 47. Rxg7 Kf5
{ This loses immediately. How? } 48. Rg3
{ Correct,  48.Rg3  and the knight is trapped. There is no defense against Rb3,  which I'm going to play on the next move and then take the knight. So these were the two tricky games. Of course, I have many more examples, but I think that these two are the most famous displays of my inner trickiness. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) My Favorite Geometrical Puzzle"]
[Black "Roger Missiaen 1974 â Puzzle #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "k4b2/8/8/8/8/1b6/2R3K1/3B4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this geometrical puzzle that I absolutely adore due to its richness in themes and motifs, White must win the game. Just how that is the question... }
1. Bf3+
{ Let's try to think things through together: the rook is under attack and if we start with the natural  1.Rc8+  Kb7  2.Rxf8  @@StartBracket@@  2.Bg4  doesn't make much sense since Black can play  2...Bd6  and be totally safe.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@5R2/1k6/8/8/8/1b6/6K1/3B4 b - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Bxd1  with a theoretical draw. We can conclude that 1.Rc8+ is not a good idea. }
1... Ka7
{ In order to win the game, we have to capture one of the bishops. This is a good moment to find a harmonious and clever plan to achieve that.   Black cannot play  1...Kb8  in view of  2.Rb2  and the bishop is lost. }
2. Rc3
{ Now, how many squares does the bishop have? We're going to check the five options that don't put the bishop en prise immediately, but first, let's see why other moves would bring White nothing.   A@@EndBracket@@  2.Rc7+  Ka6  3.Rc8  Bb4  4.Rb8  Ka5  , can we use any tactical tricks with the help of our bishop? Sadly, the answer is obvious: No. After  5.Bc6  Bc4  and Black is out of danger.   B@@EndBracket@@  2.Rb2  Bc4  and again, there is no way to chain those bishops.   C@@EndBracket@@  2.Rc8  Bd6  . Black can also play  2...Bb4  3.Ra8+  Kb6  when the position is safe, but the text move looks completely fine as well. }
2... Ba4
{ 2...Ba2  would have met a similar fate as the text move, while  2...Bf7  3.Rc7+  is clearly not an option,  and @@StartFEN@@5b2/k7/8/8/8/1bR2B2/6K1/8 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Bg8  3.Rc8  is also easy.  The main continuation of the study, @@StartFEN@@5b2/k7/8/8/8/1bR2B2/6K1/8 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Be6  , is presented in the next puzzle. }
3. Rc8 { Wherever the bishop goes, is not going to change Black's fate. } 3...
Bd6 4. Ra8+ { White wins the bishop on a4. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) My Favorite Geometrical Puzzle"]
[Black "Roger Missiaen 1974 â Puzzle #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5b2/k7/8/8/8/1bR2B2/6K1/8 b - - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]

2... Be6 { White can further disrupt the coordination of Black's pieces. How? }
3. Rc6
{ Since we understood that by attacking one of the bishops, we create dissonance in Black's camp, we should stick to the same strategy. The bishop is exposed now on e6, but going back to f7 or g8 is not safe as we've seen before.   A@@EndBracket@@  3.Re3  makes sense, but does it lead anywhere? I don't think so, as after  3...Bc4  , Black can bring the bishop closer to the king with ...Bc4-b5.  4.Re8  Bd6  5.Rd8  @@StartBracket@@  5.Ra8+  Kb6  6.Rc8  Bc7  ends White's hopes for more than a draw.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@3R4/k7/3b4/8/2b5/5B2/6K1/8 b - - 9 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc7  .  The bishops can even be doubled on the c-file since the king is very close.   B@@EndBracket@@  3.Rc7+  Kb8  doesn't give us anything either.  4.Rb7+  Kc8  5.Ra7  Bd6  and nothing is really happening as the king protects the bishops successfully. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) My Favorite Geometrical Puzzle"]
[Black "Roger Missiaen 1974 â Puzzle #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5b2/k7/2R1b3/8/8/5B2/6K1/8 b - - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]

3... Bb3
{ Once again, the only move and the same question arises: what can we do to unsettle Black's pieces? Moreover, what could Black play next?  It turns out that the board is full of squares, but none of them are free from injury, except b4. Since the bishops are still struggling, the solution to the puzzle emerges from predicting and understanding what to do against ...Bb4.  The answer is truly beautiful, hence take your time and try to find it! }
4. Kh1
{ The only move that wins also takes the computer a couple of seconds to understand why it is actually winning. The surprising part is that if White is to move in this position, the game will end in a draw since we have a mutual zugzwang.   4.Rf6  doesn't look like anything after  4...Bc5  . }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) My Favorite Geometrical Puzzle"]
[Black "Roger Missiaen 1974 â Puzzle #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5b2/k7/2R5/8/8/1b3B2/8/7K b - - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

4... Bb4
{ Anything else loses on the spot, but the text move brings no relief either. How should White continue to chase the bishops? }
5. Rc1 Ba5
{ Black is trying to survive, but it's mission impossible.   A@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf8  6.Ra1+  Kb6  7.Rb1  and Black can say goodbye to the bishop on b3.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...Be6  also loses material after  6.Rc7+  followed by either a check on c6 or on b7, depending on Black's move.   C@@EndBracket@@  5...Bd2  or  5...Bd6  have a similar faith after the same pinning idea.  6.Ra1+  Kb6  7.Rb1  and Black can resign.   D@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg8  is the main continuation of the study, which is the topic of the next puzzle. }
6. Ra1 Ka6 7. Be2+ Kb6 8. Rb1 { White wins the bishop on b3. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) My Favorite Geometrical Puzzle"]
[Black "Roger Missiaen 1974 â Puzzle #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/k7/8/8/1b6/1b3B2/8/2R4K b - - 0 5"]
[SetUp "1"]

5... Bg8
{ Black has no choice but to play the only moves in the position. And this is where the beauty of this puzzle shines! Find the winning idea for White. }
6. Rg1
{ Now we understand why we needed the king on h1, instead of g2. To further emphasize the difference, had White played @@StartFEN@@5b2/k7/2R5/8/8/1b3B2/6K1/8 w - - 6 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Kh2  instead, after  4...Bb4  5.Rc1  ,  trying to chase the bishops as in the main line of this puzzle, would have handed Black the ...Bd6+ resource. For instance, after  5...Bg8  6.Rg1  Black can even play  6...Bc4  7.Rg4  since there is always the  7...Bd6+  safety net.  8.Kg2  Bb5  and Black is out of the woods. }
6... Be6
{ What else?!  6...Bb3  7.Rb1+-  and if @@StartFEN@@6b1/k7/8/8/1b6/5B2/8/6RK b - - 11 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bc4  7.Rg4+-  . This is a good moment to explain why we had a mutual zugzwang on move  4. If White was to move here @@StartFEN@@5b2/k7/2R5/8/8/1b3B2/8/7K w - - 7 5@@EndFEN@@5.Be4  Bb4  6.Rc1  Bg8  7.Rg1  Bc4  and  and suddenly, White doesn't have the winning Rg4 move, as the bishop on e4 is blocking the view. }
7. Rg7+ { The king can step on neither the sixth nor the eighth ranks. } 7...
Kb6 { Or  7...Kb8  8.Rb7+  with a win for White. } 8. Rg6
{ Black can safely sign the scoresheets. This is one of my favorite geometrical puzzles, which contains a very nice reciprocal zugzwang. If you found the insanely beautiful Kh1 idea, then you can congratulate yourself as your geometrical vision is excellent. }
*


[Event "?"]
